<html><head> <title>Guide 3 Part 2</title></head><body>Guideline 3<P>
<H3>II. GUIDELINE FOR TOXICOLOGICAL TESTING</H3><P>
<B>A. INTRODUCTION</B><P>
For compounds used in food-producing animals, FDA is concerned with
intermittent and chronic exposure of people to relatively low concentrations of
residues. FDA tailors the type of toxicological testing 
needed for a showing of safety for a specific compound by considering its
proposed use in animal husbandry, the probable exposure of people to the parent
compound and its metabolites (residues) under its conditions of use, their
possible biological effects as deduced by structure-activity relationships, and
their effects as observed in biological systems. Some compounds need only a
minimum of testing; others may need very extensive studies in a number of
diverse biological systems.<P>
The purpose of the toxicological studies is to define the biological effect(s)
of the sponsored compound and its quantitative limits. FDA normally asks for
testing of the sponsored compound. FDA may also ask for separate testing of a
metabolite when such testing is necessary to define adequately the biological
effect of the sponsored compound (see GUIDELINE FOR METABOLISM STUDIES AND FOR
SELECTION OF RESIDUES FOR TOXICOLOGICAL TESTING). FDA generally asks that the
sponsor, at a minimum, determine a dose of the compound that produces an
adverse biological effect in test animals and a dose that does not produce any
significant toxicological or pharmacological effect (the no-observed-effect
level). The spacing of the doses should provide an assessment of the
dose-response relationship.<P>
<B>B. TESTING GENERALLY NEEDED FOR SPONSORED COMPOUNDS</B><P>
FDA generally believes that the following studies are necessary for each
sponsored compound:<P>
<ul>
<li> A battery of genetic toxicity tests as described in the GUIDELINE FOR
THRESHOLD ASSESSMENT.<P>
<li> A 90-day feeding study both in a rodent species (usually the rat) and in a
non-rodent mammalian species (usually the dog). <P>
<li> A two-generation reproduction study with a teratology component in rats. Two
litters should be produced in each generation. If toxicity occurs at a lower
dose, with a higher incidence, or with greater intensity in the second
generation as compared to the first, then the study should include a third
generation.<P>
</ul>

FDA may ask for additional studies as follows:<P>
<ul><li> Chronic bioassays for oncogenicity in each of two rodent species when
indicated by the criteria described in the GUIDELINE FOR THRESHOLD ASSESSMENT.
The sponsor should conduct the study in rats using a protocol that, in addition
to potential oncogenicity will also evaluate chronic toxicity.<P>
<li> A one year feeding study in a rodent species (usually the rat) and in a
non-rodent species (usually the dog) when the exposure of people to residues
exceeds 25 micrograms/kilogram body weight/day (equivalent to a concentration
of 1 part per million in the total diet of people, assuming a 60 kilogram body
weight and a total solid diet of 1500 grams), or when evidence indicates that
the residues bioaccumulate in the tissues of target animals. FDA will calculate
exposure as described in GUIDELINE FOR ESTABLISHING A TOLERANCE.<P>
<li> A teratology study in a second species when the compound is structurally
related to a known teratogen, when the compound has hormonal activity that may
affect the fetus, or when the compound shows adverse effects in the
reproduction/teratology study indicating that the compound may be a
teratogen.<P>
<li> Other specialized testing if necessary to define adequately the biological
effect of the compound. FDA will base this decision on the results of the above
studies and any other information available on the compound. Examples of
specialized studies include testing for neurotoxicity, for immunotoxicity, for
hormonal activity, for toxicity following <i>in utero</i> exposure, or for
toxicity from "biomass" products (see GUIDELINE FOR NEW ANIMAL DRUGS AND FOOD
ADDITIVES DERIVED FROM A FERMENTATION).
</ul><P>
FDA has provided information on acceptable protocols for subchronic, chronic,
reproduction, and teratology studies in TOXICOLOGICAL PRINCIPLES FOR THE SAFETY
ASSESSMENT OF DIRECT FOOD ADDITIVES (The "Redbook"). See 47 FR 46141, October
15, 1982. The sponsor is urged to consult with FDA before designing protocols
for specialized studies not described in that document.<P>
If the testing shows that the sponsored compound is a carcinogen,. FDA will
apply the "no-residue" requirement of section 409(c)(3)(A), 512(d)(1)(H), or
706(b)(5)(B) of the act as operationally defined in 21 CFR subpart E of Part
500. FDA will calculate the concentration of residue giving no significant risk
of cancer, S(O), from the tumor data using a statistical extrapolation
procedure. Because the mechanism of carcinogenesis is not sufficiently
understood, none of the mathematical procedures for extrapolation has a fully
adequate biological rationale. In the absence of information establishing the
mechanism of carcinogenesis for a particular chemical, FDA will use a
non-threshold, linear-at-low dose extrapolation procedure that determines the
upper limit of the risk. FDA will use the linear interpolation procedure of
Gaylor and Kodell (D. W. Gaylor and R. L. Kodell, 'Linear Interpolation
Algorithm for Low Dose Risk Assessment of Toxic Substances,<sup>" </sup>Journal
of Environmental Pathology and Toxicology, 4:305-312, 1980) as modified by
Farmer, Kodell, and Gaylor (J. H. Farmer, R. L. Kodell, and D. W. Gaylor,
"Estimation and Extrapolation of Tumor Probabilities from a Mouse Bioassay with
Survival/Sacrifice Components," Risk Analysis, 2:27-34, 1982). In the
extrapolation FDA will use the upper 95 percent confidence limit on the tumor
data and a permitted maximum lifetime risk to the test animal of 1 in 1
million.<P>
FDA will use an alternative procedure if the sponsor presents sufficient
appropriate information to demonstrate that a different extrapolation procedure
is more appropriate. <P>
For other toxicological endpoints, FDA will calculate the acceptable daily
intake (ADI) from the results of the most sensitive study in the most sensitive
species. From that study the ADI is the highest dose showing no-observed-effect
divided by the appropriate safety factor. FDA will normally use the safety
factors indicated below.<P>
<pre>
   Type of Study                            Safety Factor 
 
   Chronic                                      100 
   Reproduction/Teratology                      100 or 1000 
   (100 for a clear indication of maternal
   toxicity, 1000 for other effects)  
   90-Day                                       1000
         
         </pre><P>
<B>C. TESTING NEEDED FOR SEX STEROIDS</B><P>
The studies needed for a showing of safety for a sex steroid, considering both
carcinogenicity and the other toxicological endpoints associated with these
compounds, are described below.<P>
Although not all sex steroids are demonstrated carcinogens, the evidence
supports FDA's conclusion that all endogenous sex steroids and synthetic
compounds with similar biological activity should be regarded as suspect
carcinogens. FDA has also concluded that the endogenous sex steroids that have
been adequately tested are not genotoxic agents. Therefore, if any of these
compounds gives an oncogenic response in experimental animals, its mechanism of
action is not related to a direct chemical interaction with DNA, but tumor
development is a consequence of hyperproliferation of endocrine sensitive
tissue resulting from persistent overstimulation of the hormonal system. FDA
has concluded that in the absence of the persistent overstimulation of the
hormonal system from residues remaining in the tissues of treated animals,
individuals will not be subject to an increased risk of cancer.<P>
<B>1. Endogenous Sex Steroids</B><P>
FDA has concluded that for the endogenous sex steroids and their simple ester
derivatives safety can be assured without the need for additional animal data.
Because the compounds are endogenous in people and in food-producing animals,
the individual is exposed to rather large quantities of these compound by <i>de
novo</i> synthesis and to much lesser quantities from unmedicated
food-producing animals. FDA has concluded that no physiological effect will
occur in individuals chronically ingesting animal tissues that contain an
increase of endogenous steroid equal to 1% or less of the amount in micrograms
produced by daily synthesis in the segment of the population with the lowest
daily production. That this 1% value represents a safe increased exposure is
supported by scientific information. FDA believes that the 1% value is
reasonable and reflects sound public health policy. In the case of estradiol
and progesterone, prepubertal boys synthesize the least; in the case of
testosterone, prepubertal girls synthesize the least. The daily production
values and the calculated increase permitted above the amount naturally present
in untreated target animals are listed below.<P>
<pre>
              Daily Production        Permitted Increased Exposure 
                (micrograms)                  (micrograms)
      
Estradiol           6                          0.06 
Progesterone      150                          1.50 
Testosterone       32                          0.32
</pre><P>
When a sponsor can demonstrate with a suitable assay that under the proposed
conditions of use the concentration of residue of the endogenous sex steroid in
treated food-producing animals is such that the actual increase in exposure of
people will not exceed the permitted increase, then the compound is shown to be
safe within the meaning of the act.<P>
<B>2. Synthetic Sex Steroids</B><P>
FDA has concluded that animal testing is necessary for establishing the safety
of a synthetic sex steroid. FDA recommends the tests listed below.<P>
<ul>
<li>A battery of three genetic toxicity tests as described in the GUIDELINE FOR
THRESHOLD ASSESSMENT<P>
<li>A two-generation reproduction study with a teratology component in rats. Two
litters should be produced in each generation. If toxicity occurs at a lower
dose, with a higher incidence, or with greater intensity in the second
generation as compared to the first, then the study should include a third
generation. <P>
<li> A teratology study in a second species.<P>
<li>A 90-day feeding study in rats.<P>
<li>A 90-day feeding study in dogs.<P>
<li>A 180-day study in rhesus monkeys or other suitable subhuman primates. The
study should include a 90-day observation period before the 90-day dosing
period. The study should establish a dose that gives no observed hormonal
response. The study should assess the effect of the sponsored compound on
ovulation, the duration of the menstrual cycle, and changes in the
concentration in the blood of the gonadotropins (luteinizing hormone, LH, and
follicle stimulating hormone, FSH) and of the endogenous sex steroids
(estradiol, estrone, and progesterone). In most cases FDA expects that this
will be the most sensitive study.
</ul><P>
FDA will require chronic bioassays for oncogenicity in two rodent species if
either the genetic toxicity tests are positive, or data from the other
bioassays indicates a preneoplastic lesion in other than an endocrine sensitive
tissue.<P>
In the absence of a carcinogenic response or if tumors are observed only in
endocrine sensitive tissue, FDA will calculate the acceptable daily intake
(ADI) from the results of the most sensitive study in the most sensitive
species. FDA will normally use the safety factors indicated in the table in
section B above. FDA will also normally use a safety factor of 100 for the
study in subhuman primates.<P>
If a carcinogenic response is observed in a nonendocrine-sensitive tissue, FDA
will determine the dose that will satisfy the "no-residue" requirement of the
act using the tumor data from that tissue and a statistical extrapolation
procedure.<P><hr> 
 <A HREF="http://www.cvm.fda.gov/fda/infores/guides/guide3/guide3toc.html">
