<BODY>

<H1><A HREF="index.html" ><IMG SRC="images/tualogo1.gif" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0 ALT="TUANZ" ></A> Web site objectives</H1>

<PRE>

</PRE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>TUANZ Web Page Rationale'</H3>
<P>
 New Zealand is a technologically adept society. As we rush towards
 the Twenty First Century, it is important to keep in mind New
 Zealand's ever increasing role within the world as a whole, not
 only as a technological nation, but as a culturally rich and diverse
 country.
</P>

<P>
 The Internet as a communication medium is playing a more important
 role now within New Zealand and it would seem (from the growth
 factor) that we are embracing this technology with open arms.

<P>
 The technology itself is still relatively limited, for the moment,
 but the implications and the possibilities are as unlimited as
 the imagination itself.
<P>
 Designing for the Internet is a challenge unto itself. Making
 home pages appear as striking and inviting as possible with minimal
 memory is probably one of the most difficult and time consuming
 tasks one could ask of a designer - calling on his/her ability
 as both an artist and as a technical wizard.
<P>
 One of the aspects we felt was most important while designing
 the home page for TUANZ was that the information that was to be
 downloaded was imperative (after all TUANZ is a communications
 association) so the design was to take second place.
<P>
 The design therefore, had to compliment the information and it
 had to be simple, clear, concise and most of all inviting so that
 not only would the interest of people within the telecommunications
 industry be maintained, but stray surfers of the 'net would stop
 by and check it out.
<P>
 The design is clean and it conveys it's information well, the
 3-D logo gives the piece a low-key, yet hi-tech. appearance. The
 information is not overwhelming, (a major player in diverting
 interest) and its appearance is clearly focused.

<PRE>

</PRE>

<H3>Creating a TUANZ web site</H3>
<P>
 The process for creating a full and comprehensive web site for
 TUANZ would involve the following steps:
<UL>
<LI>ask staff and TUANZ members what they would like to have on
 the site
<LI>design a draft site content list based on staff and members
 requests and our own Internet and web building experience
<LI>discuss the draft with staff and members
<LI>create a set of web front pages based on the above discussions
<LI>create forms for updating pages (requires CGI script running
 on web server)
<LI>ask for comment from staff and a select number of members
<LI>re-engineer the TOPICS magazine design process to ensure that
 a HTML copy is supplied by the layout designers
<LI>re-engineer any other paper based production procedure to
 ensure that a HTML copy is made of each &quot;final&quot; version
<LI>teach staff how to update page information using forms
<LI>get agreement from staff to commit time to the updating of
 the pages
<LI>build in the bulk of the content
<LI>trial pages to select number of members
<LI>make adjustments based on comments
<LI>go LIVE! Tell the world!
</UL>

<PRE>

</PRE>

<H3>TUANZ Web Site Structure</H3>
<P>
 The directory structure for the web files should be kept as flat
 as possible to make the job of finding information easier. For
 example:
</P>

<IMG SRC="images/directry.gif" WIDTH=115 HEIGHT=210 BORDER=1>

<P>
 In addition a search engine should be added to the TUANZ Information
 page. This engine should be able to find anything within the TUANZ
 &quot;site&quot;.
<P>
 Other items which may be added to the current list of pages provided
 in the Cookoff information are; What's New - regular users of
 your page will almost always want to find out whatas new on the
 site.

<PRE>

</PRE>

<H3>HTML Requirements</H3>
<P>
 It is recommended that the page be design to make us of some of the features of
 HTML 3. With careful application these elements can be used without reducing the
 page to gibberish when  viewd by an &quot;old&quot; browser. Current market
 trends suggest that the Microsoft Internet Explorer browser may significantly
 challenge the dominance of the Netscape Navigator browser. (Some suggest
 that Netscape has only 18 months to live.) Any design should be compatible with
 both these browsers. Some effort should be made to ensure compatablility with
 HTML 1 browsers.
</P>

<PRE>

</PRE>

<H3>Updating the Pages</H3>
<P>
 A web site which is updated regularly is much more likely to
 attract return users. Therefore is it important that someone be
 given the task of updating the page at least once a week and preferable
 daily.
<P>
 Given the lack of HTML skills in the TUANZ office, and assuming
 that a contract HTMLer is not desired, the simplest way to have
 office staff update pages is by the use of Web forms.
<P>
 These forms can be used to update such pages as: 1.3 Calendar,
 1.4 Events, 1.6 Services Directory, 1.7 Classifieds, 2.1 INZ Activities,
 3.1 InterOp Activities, 4.1 NZEC Activities, 5.1 ATMIG Activities.
 These pages would have a simple page design and be almost completely
 text based.
<P>
 Those other pages which require a higher degree of custom design
 and layout, including graphics should be contracted out to a web
 page design firm. The two pages we have created would not be suitable
 for forms updating. It is not intended that these page would be
 changed at all, except for six monthly design refreshers.

<PRE>

</PRE>

<H3>Future Ideas</H3>

<P>
 As the Web develops over the next 12 months new additions may
 become desirable. For example:
<UL>
<LI>online TUANZ subscriptions
<LI>conduct live Web/VRML based discussions on hot topics
<LI>live video of the TUANZ office
<LI>Send out a TOPICS brief via email
</UL>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
