<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Maori Law Review</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="images/paper.gif" BGCOLOR="#003300" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="FFCC00" VLINK="FFCC33">

<H2><A HREF="index.html#contents"><IMG SRC="images/subhead2.gif" BORDER=0 WIDTH=385 HEIGHT=43 ALT="The Maori Law Review"></A></H2>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Tena Koutou. Welcome to the Maori Law Review. 

<H2><HR>What the Review Covers</H2>
<P>
<H3>Maori Land Court</H3>
This court is the successor to the Native Land Court which,
from 1865, operated throughout the country and converted the
customary, and often communal, title of the Maori owners of
New Zealand to an individual
title, so that Maori became owners of undivided shares in
their land as tenants in common.
<P>
The Maori Land Court, and its appellate body, the Maori
Appellate Court, administer land
which remains under this form of title - commonly called
"Maori land" and which consists of
about 1,305,698 hectares or 4.5% of New Zealand's land area.
Title to this multiply-owned land is
often in a fragmented state. The current law for administering
Maori land, Te Ture Whenua
Maori Act 1993 (The Maori Land Act 1993), and the previous law,
the Maori Land Act 1953
provide various mechanisms for the shareholder owners to
reform and manage Maori
land. The chief forms of management are through meetings of
owners, specialist land trusts
and Maori land incorporations.
<P>
Because of the fraction of Maori land remaining, the 1993 Act
has various provisions to ensure
that Maori land remains under multiple ownership unless there
is a clearly expressed wish on
the part of the owners to part with it. The Act gives a first
right of refusal to other owners and
kin where sales of Maori land, or shares in it, are
contemplated. Wills which purport to leave
shares in Maori land outside of certain restricted kin groups
are voided by the Act.
<P>
<B>The Review covers:</B><BR>
- Land Court and Appellate Court decisions of interest<BR>
- Te Ture Whenua Maori Act 1993 and related law; legislative,
regulatory and rule changes
<P>
<H3>Waitangi Tribunal</H3>
Established under the Treaty of Waitangi Act 1975, the
tribunal hears and reports on claims by
Maori that they have been or may be "prejudically affected" by
laws, actions and policies of the
Crown contrary to the principles of the Treaty of Waitangi.
The Treaty of Waitangi was signed
in 1840. In 1985 the tribunal was given retrospective
jurisdiction to examine Crown actions affecting Maori since
1840.
<P>
The tribunal may have up to 17 members, who sit in divisions
as small as 3, of whom one
member must be Maori. Sittings are usually headed by a member
with legal training or a judge
of the Maori Land Court. The chairperson is the Chief Judge of
the Maori Land Court. 
<P>
The tribunal must report to the government on every claim
received. If it finds the claim to be
well founded and that the principles of the Treaty have been
breached, it has power only to
recommend whatever action might be required to remedy the
breach. There is no restriction on
what may be recommended (including the amendment of
legislation), except that no
recommendation may be made for the return of private land. For
small claims, affecting a sub
tribal group (hapu) or extended family group (whanau)
recommendations are usually specific,
specifying the return of particular lands, or payment of
compensation. For larger claims
affecting whole tribes, there will also usually be a
recommendation to undertake negotiations in
light of the tribunal findings.
<P>
In certain cases, for some forest lands and lands held or
formerly held by state owned
corporations, the tribunal has power to order their return to
Maori where claims are proven.
This potentially affects thousands of hectares of public or
former public land. To date,
the tribunal has not exercised this power.
<P>
The tribunal may not hear claims concerning commercial
fisheries. These claims are presumed
to have been settled by an agreement signed with Maori tribes
in 1992 giving them a substantial
interest in New Zealand commercial fisheries by way of cash,
rights to fisheries quota and
shares in the country's largest fishing company.
<P>
<STRONG>The Review covers:</STRONG><BR>
- Reports<BR>
- Practice notes<BR>
- Directions/memoranda<BR>
<P>
<H3>General Courts and law</H3>
<B>The Review also reports on:</B><BR>
- decisions impacting on Maori land and other resources in the
general courts eg Resource
Management Act (the Planning Tribunal operates under this
Act), Rating Powers Act, Maori fisheries legislation.<BR>
- Law changes in areas impacting on Maori land and other
resource use.
<P>
An index is produced annually.
<P>
<H3>Annotations used in the Review</H3>
This publication has adopted a few special conventions used in
the Maori Land Court and
Appellate Court:<BR>
<PRE>
	MLC  = Maori Land Court
	MAC  = Maori Appellate Court
	MB   = Minute Book
	CJ   = Chief Judge
	ACMB = Appellate Court Minute Book
</PRE>
<P>
Also adopted is the Maori Land Court and Appellate Court
practice to cite sections with the
number followed by a slash and the year of the statute
concerned. Eg s41/1953 = s41 Maori
Affairs Act 1953.
<H3>About the editor</H3>
The editor is a consultant on Treaty issues. He worked with
the Waitangi Tribunal as legal
officer for 5 years and has been an adviser to the Maori Land
Court, Head Office. He now
works privately as a consultant on Treaty issues. 
 My resume is <A HREF="tomcv.htm">available</A>.
<P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
