<HEAD>
<TITLE>Tom Bennion Resume</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#003300" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="FFCC00" VLINK="FFCC33">

<P ALIGN=CENTER>
<em><B>CURRICULUM VITAE</B></em>
</P>

<H3 ALIGN=CENTER>Thomas Hugh Bennion</H3>

<BR>


<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<B>STATUS:</B><BR>
Thirty one years old (born 10 November 1963 in Auckland).<P>
<P>
<B></B><B>NATIONALITY:</B><BR>
New Zealander<P>
<P>
<B>QUALIFICATIONS:</B><BR>
Studied at Victoria University, Wellington.<BR>
Graduated 1987 with LLB (Hons) BA (History)<P>
<P>
<B><P>
EXPERIENCE:</B>       <P>
<P>
     1984 worked as part time researcher for the Commission of the
      Environment. Wrote a paper on <I>Management Issues for Crown Pastoral
      Leases</I>.<P>
<P>
     1985-1986 worked as part time researcher for the NZ Law Commission,
      assisting in preparation of Commission report <I>The Treaty of Waitangi
      and Maori Fisheries. Mataitai: Nga Tikanga Maori Me Te Tiriti O
      Waitangi</I>.<P>
<P>
     From September 1988 to November 1993 worked as legal officer for the
      Waitangi Tribunal. Work included: <P>
<P>
      -    legal opinions on the application of Treaty of Waitangi Act 1975
           and other legislation to the work of the Tribunal;<BR>
      -    legal-historical opinions for Tribunal commissioned research
           reports;<BR>
      -    drafting and opinions for Tribunal reports;<BR>
      -    production and updating of consolidated legislation.<P>
<P><P>
     From January 1992 was also a legal adviser for the Maori Land Court,
      which administers land remaining in Maori hands. Work included: <P>
<P>
      -    legal opinions on particular applications;<BR>
      -    advice on legislation affecting the work of the Court.<P>
<P>
     From February 1993 was also acting research manager for the Waitangi
      Tribunal. Work included management of research staff and programme,
      reading and commentary on research.<P>
<P>
     Research papers include <I>Treaty-making in the Pacific in the 19th
      Century and the Treaty of Waitangi</I> (LLM research paper for
      administrative law 1987) and <I>New Zealand Law and the Geothermal
      Resource</I> (Legal-historical research report for geothermal claims,
      July 1991).<P>
<P>
     Since November 1993 have worked as a private consultant on Treaty
      issues. Clients include Maori claimant groups, legal firms, the Waitangi
      Tribunal and the Maori Land Court. Have completed in 1994 research
      reports on the <I>Whanganui River claim</I> (Wai 167), <I>Parikino
      claim</I> (Wai 216), <I>Rating claims</I> (Wai 284 and others), and
      <I>Immigration claim</I> (Wai 223). Also assisted in research and
      publication of a report on <I>Maori sites in Te Whanganui a Tara</I> for
      the Wellington City Council.<P>
<P>
     Since December 1993 have published the <I>Maori Law Review</I>, a
      monthly review of law affecting Maori. The Review currently has 110 NZ
      subscriptions, and also subscribers in the USA, Canada and
      Australia.<P>
<P>
     Current work includes, preparation of a legal text on Maori Land Law
      (to be published in 1995), research on Bay of Plenty (Ngati Awa and
      others) and Ngai Tai (South Auckland) claims.<P>
<P>
<P>
<B>REFEREES:     </B>                  <P>
                 Britson Mikaere<BR>
                 Director, Waitangi Tribunal<BR>
                 PO Box 5022, Wellington<BR>
<P>
                 <P>
                 Judge A McHugh<BR>
                 Former Deputy Chief Judge, Maori Land Court<BR>
                 PO Box 180, Wellington<BR>
<P>


</BLOCKQUOTE>

