<BODY BACKGROUND="images/paper.gif" BGCOLOR="#003300" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="FFCC00" VLINK="FFCC33">

<H2><A HREF="index.html#contents"><IMG SRC="images/subhead2.gif" BORDER=0 WIDTH=385 HEIGHT=43 ALT="The Maori Law Review"></A></H2>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>Garamond Macron Font</H2>
<PRE>

</PRE>
The Maori Language Commission has adopted a system for writing maori words
 which involves the use of dashes above certain vowels to indicate the vowel
 should be extended in the spoken usage. These dashes are called
 <I>macrons</I>. Some authers use double letters to indicate the same thing,
 eg <I>maaori</I>.
<P>
In order to use macrons on a personal computer you must first install a font
 which includes these macronized letters. We use a macronized Garamond font in
 the printed version of <I>The Maori Law Review</I>.
<P>
To install our Garamond macron font in your Windows based system follow these steps:

<P>
<IMG SRC="images/square.gif" BORDER=0 WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=20 ALT="* "> &nbsp;
Download the <A HREF="garamacr.zip">zipped macron font</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/square.gif" BORDER=0 WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=20 ALT="* "> &nbsp;
Unzip the file into a temporary folder/directory using PKunzip or similar utility.
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/square.gif" BORDER=0 WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=20 ALT="* "> &nbsp;
Open the Windows Control Panel, then run the Font utility to install the font.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!----------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<PRE>

</PRE>
