<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">

<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: A Patient Guide to The Clarke</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="A Patient Guide to The Clarke" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="images/patient_guide_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>Welcome to The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry.</P>

			<P>During your stay in The Clarke, your care and recovery
			are our main concern. Our staff will strive to make your
			stay as pleasant and comfortable as possible. Our goal is to
			offer the highest quality care and treatment to you, the
			patient. If you or your family have questions or concerns,
			please feel free to discuss these with members of our staff
			or administration.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#admission">Admission</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#treatment">The Treatment Team</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#hospital_services">Hospital Services</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#hospital_policies">Hospital Policies</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#patients_rights">Patients' Rights</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#floor_directory">Floor Directory</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=1 HEIGHT=20><BR>
				<A NAME="admission"><IMG ALT="Admission" SRC="images/admission.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A>
	
			<P>Upon arrival at the Institute, patients are requested to
			go to the Admitting Department on the ground floor, between
			9 am and 5 pm Please be sure to bring your health insurance
			card or private insurance information. If you are an Ontario
			resident covered by the Ontario Health Insurance Plan, OHIP
			will cover all standard costs of your hospital care, as well
			as your physician's services. If you are a Canadian resident
			covered by other provincial health care plans, it is
			essential for you to seek prior approval from your home
			province health care department before receiving psychiatric
			treatment at The Clarke.</P>
			
			<P>If you are a non-resident of Canada and covered by
			private health insurance, please check with your insurance
			company to ensure that psychiatric treatment is covered by
			your insurance policy.</P>
			
			<P>The Clarke has four-bed, two or three-bed (semi-private),
			and some single (private) rooms. Assignment of rooms is made
			according to the individual needs of patients and the
			availability of beds. Accommodation costs will be charged
			for semi-private and private rooms on a daily basis. These
			charges are usually not covered by provincial health care
			plans. You, or your private health insurance company, if
			any, will be billed for those costs, unless this
			accommodation was required as part of your treatment.</P>

			<P><B>What To Bring</B></P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>a three or four-day wardrobe of casual clothing</P>
						
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>sleepwear (robe, pyjamas or gown, slippers)</P>
						
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>personal toiletries (brush, comb, shaving supplies,
			toothbrush, toothpaste, shampoo, soap)</P>
						
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>change for pay phones, vending machine, etc.</P>
						
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>small amount of cash for coffee shop, outings</P>
						
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>reading material, writing paper, small hobby supplies</P>
			
			<P>Some articles may need to be kept in the nursing station
			for safekeeping. The Institute does not accept
			responsibility for lost or stolen items. If you bring more
			than $10.00 cash, it is suggested that you open an account
			in the Patients' Account Office on the second floor.
			Personal cheques will not be accepted for deposit and
			government cheques will need five banking days for clearance
			before withdrawal can be made. Withdrawals can be made
			between 8:30 am and 4:30 pm, Monday to Friday, except
			statutory holidays.</P>
			
			<P><B>What Not To Bring</B></P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>cameras, recording devices, electric appliances (radios,
			curling irons, hairdryers are permitted if CSA approved)</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>valuables such as jewellery, etc.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>sharp objects</P>
			
			<P><B>Medication</B></P>
			
			<P>Any medication you have been taking at home should be
			brought to the hospital and given to your nurse at the time
			of admission. Your physician will supervise all medications
			while in the Institute. Be sure to inform him/her of any
			medication taken prior to hospitalization, including
			over-the-counter medicines such as aspirin, vitamins, or
			herbal preparations. The medication you bring to the
			hospital will be kept for you during your stay and may be
			returned to you on discharge if your doctor feels you should
			continue with the same medication. Otherwise, a discharge
			prescription for your new medication will be provided by the
			hospital pharmacy. If you have any questions or concerns
			about medication, please feel free to ask staff. Educational
			literature is available regarding many medications.</P>

		<IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=1 HEIGHT=20><BR>
		<A NAME="treatment"><IMG ALT="The Treatment Team" SRC="images/treatment.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A>

			<P>During your stay, a multidisciplinary team will be
			assigned to assist in your care. The team consists of
			physicians, nurses, social worker, and frequently, an
			occupational therapist, pharmacist, psychologist, or
			recreational therapist.</P>
			
			<P>Soon after your admission you will be seen by a staff
			psychiatrist or a psychiatric resident. The staff
			psychiatrist is a member of the treatment team who will
			assess your problems and will direct your treatment. The
			psychiatric resident will interview you in detail to learn
			about your illness and a treatment plan will be drawn up
			with the help of the staff psychiatrist, the rest of the
			treatment team, and with your input.</P>
			
			<P>During your inpatient admission at The Clarke, you will
			be working closely with many of the nursing staff on your
			unit on an individual basis and as participants in group
			programs. The goal of nursing staff on your unit is to
			assist you in achieving the highest possible state of
			health. You will be assigned a primary nurse who, with your
			participation, will develop a plan of nursing care with you.
			Nursing staff will work with you to help identify and
			achieve treatment goals which may be appropriate during your
			admission or following discharge. Nursing staff will ensure
			that your care by other members of your treatment team is
			provided in a coordinated fashion.</P>
			
			<P>Social workers work with patients individually and with
			their families to assist them in understanding and dealing
			with illness. Social workers are employed throughout the
			Institute and are involved in program planning, research and
			education, as well as individual, group, and family
			treatment. A patient's discharge plan is coordinated by a
			social worker. This may include follow-up treatment in the
			community, referrals for housing, employment, and income
			maintenance.</P>
			
			<P>Occupational therapists provide programming to help build
			supports and skills to improve your daily life. Individual
			treatment goals might include: returning to work, building a
			daily routine for your activities, or learning life
			skills.</P>
			
			<P>Recreation therapists provide a wide range of activities
			that offer opportunity for challenge, expression, and
			relaxation.</P>
			
			<P>All prescribed medication is supplied by the Pharmacy
			Department. Pharmacists monitor drug therapy, provide drug
			information and counsel on drug use. Pharmacists provide
			drug education groups on several Units. Specific issues
			pertaining to your drug treatment can be discussed with the
			pharmacist on request.</P>
			
			<P>The team may also include a psychologist who conducts
			tests which aid in diagnosis and treatment planning. They
			also provide individual and group therapy.</P>

			<P><B>If You Are A Relative</B></P>
			
			<P>Family members are important partners in treatment and,
			with a patient's consent, are kept informed of the patient's
			progress by Unit staff. A social worker is available to
			discuss family concerns and family group support programs
			are available. Frequent educational seminars are offered to
			help patients and families understand and deal with illness.
			Educational literature is also available on various mental
			illnesses and medications.</P>
			
			<P><B>Students &amp; Research</B></P>
			
			<P>As a teaching hospital, The Clarke provides training for
			resident psychiatrists. Residents are qualified physicians
			who are completing post-graduate training in psychiatry.
			During your stay, you may be cared for by a resident
			psychiatrist who will be supervised by a staff psychiatrist.
			As well, students in many other health disciplines receive
			training at The Clarke and are involved in the care of
			patients. Patients often find involvement with students both
			enriching and rewarding.</P>
			
			<P>Since The Clarke is a research Institute, some of our
			patients have the opportunity to participate in research
			projects. The purpose of research is to improve
			understanding, treatment and outcome of mental illness.
			Future generations will benefit from research being carried
			on now. Participation in research projects is entirely
			voluntary, and your care during treatment, or acceptance
			into treatment, is not dependent on participation. Please
			feel comfortable to ask questions so that you fully
			understand the research projects being carried out. Many
			patients appreciate the learning opportunity provided by
			participation in research. In turn, we appreciate patients'
			important contribution to this work. Again, participation is
			voluntary and choosing not to take part will not affect your
			care.</P>
			
			<P><B>Unit Programs</B></P>
			
			<P>Each Unit offers a treatment program which will likely
			include participation in a variety of ward activities such
			as support groups, life skills classes, and education
			sessions. As well, recreational activities are organized
			within the hospital and community. Please feel comfortable
			to ask staff about various therapeutic and recreational
			activities and to participate fully in the available
			activities. During your stay, you may visit the public areas
			of the hospital, go on outings and spend weekends at home,
			depending on your condition and after discussion with staff.
			Most Units have a sign-out book near the exit. It is very
			important to indicate your whereabouts in this book when
			leaving the Unit for any reason.</P>

		<IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=1 HEIGHT=20><BR>
		<A NAME="patients_rights"><IMG ALT="Patients' Rights" SRC="images/patients_rights.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A>

			<P>The Mental Health Act of Ontario contains specific
			regulations under which mental health facilities must
			operate. These regulations are carefully formulated to
			protect the patient's legal rights and to promote the
			patient's best interests. Many individual procedures require
			a patient's written consent.</P>
			
			<P>Most patients enter The Clarke of their own accord. This
			is referred to as a voluntary admission. Sometimes, because
			of the nature of the illness, a person may not realize the
			need for psychiatric help. In such cases, a physician or
			justice of the peace may complete an application requesting
			that the patient be assessed at a psychiatric facility.
			Following assessment, the Mental Health Act specifies some
			of the obligations and responsibilities under which mental
			health professionals provide service. All efforts are made
			to inform patients of their condition, to ensure they
			participate in treatment decisions, and to protect their
			rights and interests.</P>
			
			<P>Sometimes patients will require an assessment for
			competency to manage their own financial affairs. It is
			recommended that a patient appoint a substitute
			decision-maker (personal representative) to help in
			determining and carrying out the most appropriate treatment
			plan.</P>
			
			<P>A booklet is available on each Unit "Rights and
			Responsibilities: A Guide to the Mental Health Act",
			explaining the provisions of the Mental Health Act in detail
			and patients and their families are encouraged to become
			familiar with its contents. Under the Mental Health Act,
			some patients have the right to appeal to a Review Board for
			hearings on their right to consent to their stay in
			hospital, their treatment or to manage their finances. In
			such circumstances, a Rights Advisor is available through
			the office of the Executive V.P./C.O.O., 979-4747 ext. 2429.
			Please feel free to ask staff any questions you have
			regarding legal concerns.</P>

		<IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=1 HEIGHT=20><BR>
		<A NAME="hospital_services"><IMG ALT="Hospital Services" SRC="images/hospital_services.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A>

			<P><B>Meals</B></P>
			
			<P>Most patients eat their meals in the dining area located
			in each Unit. Mealtimes vary depending on the Unit. Please
			ask staff for specific times for your Unit. Special diets
			are available on request.</P>
			
			<P>A Coffee Shop is located on the ground floor. The Coffee
			Shop hours are 7:30 am - 3:30 pm, Monday to Friday.</P>
			
			<P>The Institute also operates a Cafeteria which is open
			from 11 am - 6 pm, Monday to Friday.</P>
			
			<P>Service is as follows:</P>
			
			<P>Lunch 11:00 am - 2:00 pm<BR>
			Snacks 2:00 pm - 4:15 pm<BR>
			Dinner 4:15 pm - 6:00 pm</P>
			
			<P><B>Mail</B></P>
			
			<P>Mail is delivered to and picked up on your Unit. The
			address is:</P>
			
			<P>Clarke Institute of Psychiatry<BR>
			250 College Street<BR>
			Toronto, Ontario<BR>
			M5T 1R8</P>
			
			<P>Please have letters, gifts, and flowers addressed to your
			particular Unit and ensure that your full name and address
			are on the package. Stamps are available from a vending
			machine near the Coffee Shop on the ground floor.</P>
			
			<P><B>Laundry</B></P>
			
			<P>Washers and dryers and laundry detergent are available on
			each Unit for patients' use.</P>
			
			<P><B>Telephone</B></P>
			
			<P>Each Unit has its own pay phone. Patients can also
			receive incoming calls on these lines. The Unit phone
			numbers are as follows:</P>
			
			<P><B>Unit                        (Abbr.) (Floor) Telephone</B><BR>
			Mood and Anxiety Unit           (MAU)    (9)   979-9178<BR>
			Clinical Investigation Unit     (CIU)   (10)   979-9018<BR>
			Brief Hospitalization Program   (BHP)          598-9009<BR>
			Community Reintegration Program (CRP)          979-9176<BR>
			General Psychiatric Unit        (GPU)    (5)   979-9174<BR>
			Acute Care Unit                 (ACU)    (5)   979-2221 ext. 2676</P>
			
			<P><B>Recreation Services</B></P>
			
			<P>Newspapers are available on the Unit or through vending
			machines on the ground floor. Television, books, magazines,
			and small craft supplies are available on the Unit. There
			are food and drink-vending machines on the ground floor.
			Information on weekly activities such as video nights, gym
			activities, special outings, and events is posted on each
			Unit. Please ask for information on available recreation
			programs. Suggestions are welcomed.</P>
			
			<P><B>Employment</B></P>
			
			<P>The Work Adjustment and Employment Support Program is a
			mental health service funded by the Ministry of Health and
			located at The Clarke to assist persons with significant
			mental health problems to enter and maintain employment and
			training.</P>
			
			<P><B>Schooling</B></P>
			
			<P>The College Street Secondary School of the Toronto Board
			of Education is located at The Clarke and is available to
			referred patients wishing to continue their education during
			or after their hospital stay. The School gives patients the
			opportunity to work on secondary school credits and to
			develop computer and artistic skills.</P>
			
			<P><B>Religious Services</B></P>
			
			<P>The Institute Chaplain is available to help address your
			spiritual concerns. You may arrange to have the chaplain
			visit you by requesting an appointment through Unit staff or
			by calling his office at extension 2355. A weekly interfaith
			Sunday service is held at 11:00 am in Room 853. The chaplain
			can also direct you, on request, to a priest, rabbi, imam,
			or other faith-group leader.</P>
			
			<P><B>Parking</B></P>
			
			<P>Patients should leave their cars at home while in
			hospital. There is limited metered parking near the
			Institute on Spadina and on municipal lots off Spadina south
			of the Institute. The underground parkade behind the
			Institute, accessible off Spadina, charges an hourly rate,
			but is generally full during the day. Toronto Transit
			Commission buses and streetcars run from the Spadina and
			Queen's Park subway stations and stop at the corner of
			Spadina and College, which is only steps away from The
			Clarke.</P>
			
			<P><B>Appointments Outside The Institute</B></P>
			
			<P>Some tests and procedures may have to be carried out in
			other facilities or clinics. Relatives may be asked to
			assist by accompanying patients to these special
			appointments.</P>
			
			<P><B>Interpreters</B></P>
			
			<P>Interpreting services can be arranged if no family member
			is available to help.</P>
			
			<P><B>Volunteers</B></P>
			
			<P>The Clarke is most grateful to our volunteers, who
			contribute so much to the care of clients. Volunteers offer
			individual and group activities that enhance the quality of
			life for clients in hospital. In addition, they run
			institute-wide social/recreational activities on weekends
			and in the evenings. Ask a member of your treatment team for
			more information about volunteer services.</P>

		<IMG ALT="" SRC="images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=1 HEIGHT=20><BR>
		<A NAME="hospital_policies"><IMG ALT="Hospital Policies" SRC="images/hospital_policies.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A>

			<P><B>Visitors</B></P>
			
			<P>Family and friends are encouraged to visit patients as
			often as desired. Children are welcome on most Units.
			Because the patients are usually busy with tests or
			treatment activities during the weekdays, most visiting
			hours are in the late afternoon or evening. However,
			flexible arrangements can be made for out-of-town visitors
			and special circumstances. The usual visiting hours on the
			Units are listed below. It is a good idea for visitors to
			check with the Unit first by phone to confirm visiting hours
			at any given time.</P>
			
			<P>Unit (Floor) Days Weekends &amp; Hours &amp; Holidays<BR>
			Acute Care Unit (5) daily, 11:00 am - 9:00 pm<BR>
			General Psychiatry Unit (5) daily, 11:00 am - 9:00 pm<BR>
			Mood &amp; Anxiety Unit (9) Mon - Fri, 4:00 - 9:00 pm 1:00 - 9:00 pm</P>
			
			<P>Continuing Care (10) daily, 9:00 am - 9:00 pm<BR>
			Brief Hospitalization Program daily, 9:00 am - 9:00 pm<BR>
			Community Reintegration Program daily, 9:00 am - 9:00 pm<BR>
			Clinical Investigation Unit (11) Mon - Fri, 4:00 - 9:00 pm 11:00 -9:00 pm</P>
			
			<P><B>Smoking and Alcohol</B></P>
			
			<P>To protect the health of patients, the Institute has a No
			Smoking policy. There are, however, certain designated areas
			on the patient units, where smoking is permitted by
			inpatients only.</P>
			
			<P>Use of non-prescribed drugs and alcohol is not allowed in
			the Institute. During your stay, consumption of alcohol
			outside the Institute should be discussed with your
			doctor.</P>
			
			<P><B>Patient &amp; Staff Safety</B></P>
			
			<P>Every effort is made to ensure the safety of all patients
			and staff at the Institute. Violent or abusive behaviour is
			not tolerated.</P>
			
			<P><B>Fire</B></P>
			
			<P>Unit staff will inform you of procedures to follow in the
			event of fire. Fire drills are performed regularly.</P>
			
			<P><B>Inquiries</B></P>
			
			<P>Privacy and confidentiality of our patients is strictly
			respected. Inquiries regarding patient status will only be
			provided to designated persons when visiting the Units, in
			keeping with patient wishes.</P>
			
			<P><B>Discharge</B></P>
			
			<P>Your doctor and treatment team will discuss plans for
			your discharge with you well in advance, so that the most
			appropriate arrangements can be made. Your Unit Social
			Worker can help you with planning for discharge and link you
			with follow-up treatment in the community, support groups,
			and referrals for housing, employment, and income
			maintenance.</P>
			
			<P>To allow for preparations for incoming patients, we
			prefer discharged patients leave in the morning, but these
			hours vary according to the Unit. Please ensure you have all
			your personal belongings. Any articles left in the Institute
			are kept for 30 days and are then donated to a charitable
			organization. If applicable, stop at the Accounting Office
			(2nd Floor) to settle your accounts and/or pick up any
			valuable left for safekeeping. If you have a large amount of
			money deposited with the Accounting Office, it is advisable
			for you to inform Accounting in advance to make arrangements
			for withdrawal.</P>

