			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="research_division"><IMG ALT="The Research Division" SRC="../images/research_division.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>Vice-President Research:</I><BR>
			Dr. Franco Vaccarino</P>

			<P><I>Secretary:</I><BR>
			Janice Broughton-Cafazzo<BR>
			(416) 979-4675</P>
			
			<P><I>Administrative Assistant, Research:</I><BR>
			Karen Drysdale<BR>
			(416) 979-4747 ext. 2455</P>

			<P>The causes, symptoms, treatments, and long-term outcome
			of most mental illnesses are only beginning to be
			understood.  Only research will lead us to a full
			understanding of these illnesses so that improved treatments
			can be found, patient care can be improved, and
			professionals can have access to current information.</P>
			
			<P>Widely recognized as producing some of the finest
			clinical and research programs in the country, Clarke
			research across all disciplines and all levels of analysis
			has contributed significantly to the world-wide
			understanding of psychiatric disorders.</P>
			
			<P>At The Clarke, research is conducted across all clinical
			Divisions and takes many forms. Basic science research using
			state-of-the art technologies is aimed at learning about the
			body chemicals, genetic materials, or brain structures
			involved in psychiatric illnesses. Clinical research
			evaluates how specific treatments are working in practice.
			Qualitative methods are used to learn more about the
			subjective experience of clients with mental health
			problems. Community research surveys broad populations to
			provide information about the extent, nature, and severity
			of psychiatric disability, as the basis for providing
			services.</P>
			
			<P>Twelve sections within The Clarke's Research Dvision
			focus exclusively on research. These sections (described
			below) are affiliated with the University of Toronto's
			Departments of Psychiatry, Physiology, Pharmacology,
			Psychology, and Institute of Medical Sciences, and as such,
			provide a rich environment for training at the graduate and
			post-graduate levels.</P>
			
			<P>The Research Division receives major sponsorship from the
			Medical Research Council of Canada, National Institutes of
			Health, Natural Sciences &amp; Engineering Research Council,
			Ontario Mental Health Foundation, and many other granting
			bodies. In addition, The Clarke actively seeks public,
			private, industry, and government involvement.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="biochemical_psychiatry"><IMG ALT="Biochemical Psychiatry" SRC="../images/biochemical_psychiatry.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979-6828</P>

			<P><I>Head:</I><BR>
			Dr. Jerry Warsh</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Staff:</I><BR>
			Roula Andrepoulos, Christopher Blowes, Masoumeh
			Emamghoreishi, Marty Green, Len Hua, Arvind Kamble, Peter
			Li, Anna Lin, Elizabeth McMillan, David Sibony, Kim Po
			Siu</P>

			<P>Researchers in the Biochemical Psychiatry Section
			investigate biochemical abnormalities underlying psychiatric
			disorders, with particular emphasis on mood disorders. Under
			the leadership of Dr. Jerry Warsh, researchers are currently
			focusing on the role of biochemical processes in bipolar
			affective disorder and on understanding how mood-stabilizing
			agents affect those processes to produce their beneficial
			effects.</P>
			
			<P>Work on bipolar affective disorder builds on direct
			findings from a series of landmark studies by a team from
			the Section and the Mood Disorders Clinic, showing
			disturbances in intracellular signalling. Initial findings
			of abnormally high levels of certain G-proteins in the
			brains and white blood cells of people diagnosed with
			bipolar disorder, and later evidence of alterations in other
			signal-transducing proteins, point to an array of
			disturbances in critical brain cell signalling pathways in
			the illness. These findings have important theoretical,
			diagnostic, and treatment implications. Researchers are
			seeking to determine whether these disturbances are the core
			of the disease or the result of other processes, whether
			they occur only in specific phases of the illness, and
			whether the phenomenon is unique to bipolar disorder.</P>
			
			<P>Research on mood-stabilizing medications suggests they
			improve the efficiency of the interaction between G-proteins
			and other signalling proteins. One aspect of future research
			is developing therapeutic agents targeted at these
			signalling disturbances, which are more effective and
			produce fewer side effects.</P>
			
			<P>Disturbances in intracellular signalling have also been
			found in a subgroup of patients with schizophrenia,
			specifically disturbances in phospholipid-dependent
			intracellular communication which may contribute to the
			promotion or development of schizophrenia.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="biopsychology"><IMG ALT="Biopsychology" SRC="../images/biopsychology.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979-4747 x 2293</P>

			<P><I>Acting Head:</I><BR>
			Dr. Paul Fletcher</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Staff:</I><BR>
			John Chambers, Zhi-Hui Ming, Christina Brown</P>

			<P>The Biopsychology Section conducts research on the
			biological foundations of both normal and pathological
			behaviours relevant to psychiatry. Led by Dr. Paul Fletcher,
			a major focus of this work is the role various neurochemical
			systems (serotonin, dopamine, GABA, and neuropeptide Y) play
			in controlling behaviour. A clearer understanding of the
			link between neurochemical functioning and behaviour lays
			the groundwork for designing more selective drugs for
			treating psychiatric disorders.</P>
			
			<P>One major research area in the section is the
			neurochemical basis of impulsivity which is characterized by
			a loss of behavioral control, a need for immediate
			gratification, active sensation-seeking, and an exaggerated
			response to pleasurable or 'rewarding' stimuli. Impulsivity
			is associated with suicide, aggression, alcoholism,
			substance abuse, bulimia, anxiety, and depression. Because
			reduced serotonin functioning has been linked to all these
			conditions, current research is studying the relationship
			between impulsive behaviour and alterations in the highly
			complex serotonin system - in particular, identifying where
			in the brain disturbances in serotonin function lead to
			impulsive behaviour. The goal is to determine why the
			serotonin system is functioning differently and whether
			compensatory interventions could change these problematic
			behaviours. Impulsive behaviours are evident early in life;
			Dr. Fletcher is investigating how drug and environmental
			manipulations which alter the development of serotonin
			neurons affect adult behaviour.</P>
			
			<P>Dr. Fletcher is also examining the effects on behaviour
			of the interplay between serotonin systems and other
			neurotransmitter systems dopamine, GABA, and neuropeptide Y.
			This work has implications for understanding and treating
			drug abuse, alcohol abuse, and bulimia respectively.</P>
			
			<P>Other collaborative projects include the development of a
			novel model of Alzheimer's disease, and transgenic research
			investigating the role of dopamine D1 receptors in reward
			and cognitive processes.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="culture_community_health"><IMG ALT="Culture, Community &amp; Health Studies" SRC="../images/culture_community_health.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979-6967</P>

			<P><I>Head:</I><BR>
			Dr. Morton Beiser</P>
			
			<P><I>Academic Staff:</I><BR>
			Carmelina Barwick, Graham Bean, Gerald Devins, Samuel Noh</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Scientists:</I><BR>
			Rene Dion, Andy Gotowiec, Ilene Hymen, Jiahui Zhang-Wong</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Support:</I><BR>
			Wendy Hiscox, Norman Phillion, Cynthia Pon, Edward Synowski, Nhi Vu</P>
			
			<P><I>Secretarial Staff:</I><BR>
			Wendy Hampson, Beverly Marson</P>

			<P>Research demonstrates that non-white, non-English
			speaking patients receive lower quality health care than
			majority culture patients. To help further the national goal
			of providing equal and excellent health care to all members
			of Canada's pluralistic society, the Culture, Community, and
			Health Studies section based at The Clarke conducts research
			on cultural aspects of health and illness and on the
			psychosocial adaptation of immigrants and refugees. The
			Section:</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Provides consultation to granting agencies, service
			providers, institutions of higher learning, and all
			levels of government;</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Stimulates the development of models of health care that
			are sensitive and responsive to the needs of Canada's
			multicultural society; and</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sponsors a symposium series on the topic of 'Ethnicity
			and Health' to identify future areas of research.</P>

			<P>Headed by Dr. Morton Beiser, the integrated research,
			treatment, and community outreach program focuses on
			immigrants, refugees, and First Nations peoples. Studies
			undertaken by program researchers include:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>A ten-year collaborative study of refugee resettlement
			examining factors promoting successful adaptation and the
			mental health risks of resettlement of Southeast Asian
			refugees;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>A study of refugee resettlement examining mental health
			and ethnic identification in the children of former 'boat
			people';</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>A study of successful adaptation among Caribbean youth;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>A longitudinal study of intellectual development, mental
			health, and academic achievement of First Nations children
			in Canada and the U.S. to investigate variables such as
			self-esteem, I.Q., anxiety, depression, and antisocial
			behaviour, and the social and environmental context in which
			these factors arise;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>A study of ethnic identification among First Nations youth; and</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The introduction of a model program of patient and
			family education about renal disease specifically designed
			for Native communities in Northern Ontario.</P>

			<P>In a second series of studies, researchers are examining
			social and cultural influences on the expression of illness.
			These studies examine cross-cultural variability of mental
			disorders and cross-cultural validity of measures used to
			assess mental health. In one project, researchers are
			studying an ethnically diverse patient group to examine how
			patients describe their illness (most troubling symptoms,
			perceived causes, treatment preferences, and help-seeking
			behaviours). Another project examines intercultural
			differences in health patterns revealed by the National
			Population Health Survey. Findings will have implications
			for patient-professional communication, therapeutic rapport,
			appropriateness of treatment, and compliance with treatment.
			In other such studies, researchers are investigating
			differences in the onset, expression, and treatment of
			schizophrenia among patients from Asian and Non-Asian
			backgrounds to investigate variables affecting delays in
			seeking help and differing pharmacologic approaches to
			treating patients of various ethnic backgrounds.</P>		

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="health_systems_research"><IMG ALT="Health Systems Research Unit" SRC="../images/health_systems_research.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979-6844</P>

			<P><I>Director:</I><BR>
			Dr. Paula Goering</P>
			
			<P><I>Manager, Clarke Consulting Group:</I><BR>
			Joy Rogers</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Staff &amp; Consultants:</I><BR>
			Isobel Barnes, Jeanette Cochrane, Janet Durbin, Michael
			Higgins, Elizabeth Lin, Tammy Morrell-Bellai, George
			Tolomiczenko</P>

			<P>Informing and improving systems of mental health service
			delivery -- particularly in relation to the severely
			mentally ill -- is the goal of the Health Systems Research
			Unit, the base of the Department of Psychiatry's Mental
			Health Systems Research and Development Program.</P>
			
			<P>Headed by Dr. Paula Goering, the interdisciplinary team
			draws on the experience of other progressive jurisdictions,
			reviews current literature, interviews and consults with
			local stakeholders, analyses data in existing administrative
			databases, and gathers information through epidemiological
			and program evaluation studies. To maximize the possibility
			of these findings being disseminated and translated into
			policy and practice, investigators in the Unit regularly
			assume additional roles as administrators, planners,
			consultants, and advocates, to influence decision-making in
			the education, health care and government arenas. The Clarke
			Institute Consulting Group, based in the Unit, provides a
			vehicle for transferring knowledge and for keeping the
			research staff in touch with 'front line' service delivery
			issues and problems.</P>
			
			<P>Researchers from the Unit have been actively involved in
			all phases of the mental health reform process in Ontario --
			from formulation of principles through to implementation.
			Throughout the reform process, working papers produced by
			the Health Systems Research Unit have formed the basis for
			much of the policy underscoring the implementation of mental
			health reform. To inform planning and policy for mental
			health reform, a team of psychiatric researchers from the
			Unit and McMaster University designed, conducted, and
			analysed the most comprehensive population-based study of
			mental disorder ever undertaken in Ontario as the the basis
			for future Ministry of Health planning. The study, the
			Mental Health Supplement to the Ontario Health Survey,
			gathered information from nearly 10,000 Ontarians to provide
			data about the extent, nature, and severity of psychiatric
			disability, and a picture of mental health care utilization
			in Ontario.</P>
			
			<P>In addition to numerous projects that focus upon
			secondary analysis of the Supplement database, studies
			underway include:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>A Pathways into Homelessness project that will survey
			over 300 residents of Toronto shelters and include an
			additional NARSAD-funded study of cognitive functioning and
			personality;</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>A cross-national comparison of US and Canadian mental
			health care systems; and</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>A study of patient classification methods in psychiatry.</P>
			
			<P>The Unit is a member of the Clinical Epidemiology and
			Health Care Program of the University of Toronto and has
			developed a collaborative relationship with the Institute
			for Clinical Evaluative Sciences. It is also a partner with
			the Ontario Mental Health Foundation and Canadian Mental
			Health Association -- Ontario Division, in a newly-formed
			Mental Health Research &amp; Policy Group which will
			actively promote mental health service research across the
			province.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="human_neurochemical_pathology"><IMG ALT="Human Neurochemical Pathology Lab" SRC="../images/human_neurochemical.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979 4747 x 2277</P>

			<P><I>Head:</I><BR>
			Dr. Stephen Kish</P>
			
			<P><I>Consultant:</I><BR>
			Dr. Oleh Hornykiewicz</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Staff:</I><BR>
			Brian Ross, Leslie Morrison, Kathleen Shannak, Jan Chang,
			Linda Distefano, Anna Moszczynska, Xiao-Chun Cao, Julian
			Wursley, Yushiaki Furukawa, Elizabeth McMillan</P>

			<P>Researchers in the Human Neurochemical Pathology Lab
			conduct neurochemical research with the goal of providing
			insights into the biological mechanisms of abnormal
			functioning in such neuropsychiatric disorders as
			schizophrenia, bipolar affective disorder, substance abuse
			disorders, and Alzheimer's disease. Under the leadership of
			Dr. Stephen Kish, researchers investigate abnormalities in
			neurotransmitter/neuromodulator systems, and analyze
			biologically active molecules, relevant enzymatic systems,
			and specific neurotransmitter receptor sites in autopsied
			human brain.</P>
			
			<P>Housing one of the world's most extensive collections of
			post mortem brain tissue with diagnosed neuropsychiatric and
			neurodegenerative disorders, the Lab has sponsored landmark
			research on manic-depressive illness, schizophrenia, and
			Alzheimer's and Parkinson's diseases. Current research
			focuses on:</P>

			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Intracellular signalling disturbance in bipolar disorder
			and schizophrenia;</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Laboratory and clinical research on possible causes and
			treatment of neuronal damage in Alzheimer's disease;</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Abnormal polyamine and methylation systems in
			schizophrenia, manic depression, and Alzheimer's disease;</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The biological bases for amphetamine addiction and
			paranoid schizophrenia; and</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Accurate diagnostic assessment of declining dopamine
			function in Parkinson's disease.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="molecular_psychobiology"><IMG ALT="Molecular Psychobiology" SRC="../images/molecular_psychobiology.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979-4659/4661</P>

			<P><I>Heads:</I><BR>
			Dr. Chaim Niznik and Dr. Hubert Van Tol</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Staff:</I><BR>
			Fortunata McConkey, Vera Jovanovic, Zdenek Pristupa</P>
			
			<P><I>Students:</I><BR>
			Frank J.S. Lee, Kim Sugamori, Lidia Demchyshyn, Anita
			Hamadani, Neal Tozman</P>

			<P>Researchers in the Molecular Psychobiology section
			investigate the molecular mechanisms involved in the cause,
			expression, and treatment of neuropsychiatric diseases such
			as schizophrenia, manic-depressive illness, drug addiction,
			and psychomotor diseases. Led by Dr. Chaim Niznik and Dr.
			Hubert Van Tol, current research centres on abnormal
			functioning of the dopamine system -- known to be integrally
			involved in Parkinson's and Huntington's diseases, cocaine
			abuse, and schizophrenia. Researchers working on
			identifying, characterizing, and assessing biochemical
			abnormalities in dopamine receptors and transporters have
			shown that receptors for dopamine exist in at least five
			genetically-determined variants, cloned four of those
			variants, and shown that receptor function is markedly
			different in schizophrenic brain.</P>
			
			<P>Dr. Niznik's current and future research is directed
			toward further investigating the two variants of the D1
			receptor gene (D1 and D5), which his team was the first to
			isolate. D1 genes and protein products are associated with
			movement disorders, schizophrenia, and other psychomotor
			events. Dr. Niznik's group is also studying the role of at
			least three more, as yet uncharacterized, variants of D1.
			His work analyzing the chemical and structural composition
			of the dopamine receptors and transporters and the
			mechanisms by which the dopamine receptors and transporter
			interact, may form the basis for the development of drugs
			for treating schizophrenia and motor disorders following
			neuroleptic treatment, and may contribute to improved
			treatments for attention deficit disorders and Parkinson's
			disease. Ultimately, this paves the way for gene replacement
			therapies. In other work, Dr. Niznik is collaboratively
			analyzing the molecular structure and function of the
			transporter to generate laboratory screening systems for
			studying the dopamine uptake process.</P>
			
			<P>Dr. Van Tol was a member of the group which first cloned
			the D2 receptor -- work which resulted in the subsequent
			cloning of four of the five known dopamine receptors (he has
			been involved in cloning all four). In contrast to the D1
			and D2 receptors, little is known about the functions of the
			novel dopamine receptors. Dr. Van Tol's group was the first
			to clone the novel variant of the D2-type receptor, D4,
			which is thought to play an important role in schizophrenia.
			His research has implicated this variant as a potentially
			important target for treating the disorder. His current
			investigations involve:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Cloning other postulated dopamine receptor subtypes;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Characterization of the molecular structure and function
			of the D4 receptor gene;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Functional coupling of the receptor to effectors such as
			adenylyl cyclase and potassium channels;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Cloning novel inwardly rectifying potassium channels
			implicated in controlling release of dopamine; and</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Developing viral mediated gene-transfer techniques to
			express cloned genes in brain tissue.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="neuroendocrinology"><IMG ALT="Neuroendocrinology" SRC="../images/neuroendocrinology.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979-6940</P>

			<P><I>Head:</I><BR>
			Dr. Gregory Brown</P>
			
			<P><I>Lab Co-ordinator:</I><BR>
			Erika Johansson</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Staff:</I><BR>
			Shiu Fun Pang, Guang Liu, Yong Song, Cammie Chan, Fang Lui,
			Anita Hamadani, Audrey Brown, Wan Qi</P>

			<P>Endocrine function -- particularly pituitary and pineal
			function -- provides a useful window on selected aspects of
			brain function in patients with schizophrenia, depression,
			and panic disorder. Led by Dr. Greg Brown, researchers in
			the Neuroendocrinology Section focus on the pineal gland in
			relation to disruptions to chronobiology and circadian
			rhythm regulation, with the ultimate aim of employing the
			knowledge in understanding and treating psychiatric illness.
			Research on sleep disruption caused by shift work or jet
			lag, has application for treatment of depression and
			anxiety.</P>
			
			<P>One of only a few research groups in Canada with this
			particular focus, researchers in the Section are currently
			investigating disruption of pineal function in patients with
			mood disorders, the melatonin receptors (the targets of the
			pineal), and factors regulating the pineal gland in
			animals.</P>
			
			<P>Collaborative studies with the Mood &amp; Anxiety
			Division, focus on the significance of endocrine changes in
			mood and anxiety disorders and on the role of the pineal in
			responsiveness to antidepressant and antianxiety drug
			treatment. These include studies of:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The effects of low nocturnal levels of melatonin in
			depressive illness;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The role of the pineal in treating major depression with
			Paxil;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The function of the serotonin and norephinephrine
			neurotransmitter systems in mood disorders; and</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The role of high daytime levels of melatonin in symptoms
			of panic disorder.</P>

			<P>Research has shown that receptors for melatonin are
			widespread -- found not only in brain and spinal cord but
			also in endocrine and immune systems and other tissues (the
			retina, pituitary, blood vessels, heart, kidney, and
			gastrointestinal tract). Although the functional effects of
			all these receptors is not yet clear, they may be active in
			modulating rhythm in these sites.</P>
			
			<P>In collaboration with colleagues from Molecular
			Psychobiology, Dr. Brown is working to characterize
			receptors of melatonin, define their structure, and identify
			variations. This work forms the basis for the possible
			development of highly-specific drug treatments that target
			particular receptor variants with the aim of normalizing
			circadian rhythm.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="neuroimaging"><IMG ALT="Neuroimaging" SRC="../images/neuroimaging.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979-4747 x 2297</P>

			<P><I>Head:</I><BR>
			Dr. Jose Nobrega</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Staff:</I><BR>
			Lori Dixon, Timea Belej, Roger Raymond</P>

			<P>Led by Dr. Jose Nobrega, researchers in the Neuroimaging
			Section analyse anatomically intact brain to differentiate
			anatomic regions and their relationship to highly specific
			functions in neuropsychiatric disorders. This is done via
			detailed and comprehensive regional analyses of postmortem
			brains from humans and other relevant models. Findings from
			these analyses -- together with the the neurochemical
			profile provided by the Human Neurochemical Pathology Lab
			and the view of spatial relationships afforded by PET --
			provide a view of the brain in its entirety.</P>
			
			<P>Currently, four major areas of research are being
			pursued:</P>

			<OL>
				<LI>The brain mechanisms of certain antidepressant treatments;
				<LI>Brain dopamine: receptors and function;
				<LI>Brain mechanisms of compulsive drug taking;
				<LI>New methodologies for visualizing chemical processes in
			the brain.
			</OL>

			<P>Among studies of brain mechanisms of antidepressant
			treatments, researchers are investigating:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Brain effects of thyroid hormone treatment for
			refractory (treatment-resistant) depression;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Antidepressant effects of sleep deprivation (absence REM
			sleep);</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Effects of electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) on brain
			metabolic activity.</P>

			<P>Studies of brain Dopamine: Receptors &amp; Function are
			focused on:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Restoring dopamine function with microencapsulated
			cells;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Anatomical distribution and function of the dopamine
			receptors, and</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Brain dopamine receptor changes in models of tardive
			dyskinesia and dystonic syndromes.</P>

			<P>Research on mechanisms of compulsive drug taking include
			studies of the influence of psychological and
			pharmacological events on regional brain effects in drug
			addiction:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Chemical changes in glutamate receptor and
			calcium-binding proteins precipitated by alcohol abuse;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Brain regions associated with reward (pleasure) and
			compulsive drug taking;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Effects of chronic cocaine on dopamine, norephinephrine,
			and serotonin transporters.</P>

			<P>Ongoing work is aimed at developing techniques for
			quantitatively visualizing receptor sites, brain hormones
			and enzymes, and events in the cell nucleus -- all markers
			associated with local brain changes in response to
			activating stimulation.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="pet_schizophrenia"><IMG ALT="PET and Schizophrenia" SRC="../images/pet_schizophrenia.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>The research efforts of the Schizophrenia Division
			have been greatly enhanced by strong collaborative efforts
			with our Positron Emission Tomography (PET) Centre. PET has
			enabled investigators in the Schizophrenia Division to
			address critical questions about the integrity of
			neuroreceptors in schizophrenia, the mechanism of action of
			antipsychotic medication and the neural mechanisms
			underlying the cognitive dysfunction found in schizophrenia.
			The effective collaboration of the PET team and the
			Schizophrenia Division promises to yield important insights
			into the brain abnormalities which underlie schizophrenia,
			as well as generate new approaches to pharmacologic
			treatment of schizophrenia.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="positron_emission"><IMG ALT="Positron Emission Tomography (PET)" SRC="../images/positron_emission.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979-4651</P>

			<P><I>Head:</I><BR>
			Dr. Sylvain Houle</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Staff:</I><BR>
			Alan Wilson, Jean DaSilva, Shitij Kapur</P>

			<P>PET is an imaging technology which allows scientists to
			examine chemical processes in live, conscious patients.
			Qualitatively different from other imaging technologies --
			CT or MRI scanning -- which show anatomical structure rather
			than chemical activity, PET allows researchers to examine in
			fine detail biological cellular functions in healthy and
			diseased brains. Used in psychiatric research, it allows
			researchers to determine which chemical messengers are
			malfunctioning and helps identify how the malfunction can be
			corrected. Brain studies made possible through PET improve
			the understanding of psychiatric illnesses such as
			schizophrenia, manic-depressive illness, anxiety disorders,
			and Alzheimer's disease.</P>
			
			<P>PET has added immeasurably to knowledge of brain
			transmission mechanisms and to understanding how and where
			psychoactive drugs work. New areas of research are
			constantly being developed, among them speech and language
			disorders, Parkinson's and Huntington's diseases, and the
			possible physiological bases for addictions. In addition to
			its application to pathology, PET is being applied to
			improving understanding of normal cognitive functions --
			speech, learning, memory, vision, perception.</P>
			
			<P>The PET Centre is a University of Toronto facility,
			funded by the Ministry of Health and located at The Clarke
			to serve the teaching hospital research network. Headed by
			Dr. Sylvain Houle, the Centre is the first of its kind in
			Toronto and one of only four in Canada. The juxtaposition of
			the Centre with other research technologies employed at The
			Clarke, provides a unique environment for research across
			technologies and disciplines.</P>
			
			<P>In the realm of psychiatric neuroscience, researchers are
			using PET technology to investigate:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Brain mechanisms underlying relapse in depression;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The role of the pineal gland in antidepressant and
			antipanic treatment;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Brain regions involved in the roles of serotonin and
			norepinephrine in major depression and panic disorder;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Brain mechanisms underlying delay in the actions of the
			antidepressant treatments;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Effects of the neurotransmitter, cholecystokinin (CCK)
			on cerebral blood flow in panic disorder;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Neuroanatomical changes induced by CCK in generalized
			anxiety disorder, social phobia, post-traumatic stress
			disorder, and obsessive compulsive disorder;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Optimal dosage levels of typical and atypical
			antipsychotic drugs;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The mechanism of action of atypical neuroleptics; and</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Diminishing dopamine function in Parkinson's disease.</P>

			<P>Radiochemists at the Centre are evaluating existing
			compounds and developing and testing new radiolabeled
			compounds (radioligands or radiotracers) to be used as
			probes to study neuropsychiatric diseases. The methodology
			group are conducing research on image analysis and PET
			instrumentation in particular, methods for combining
			findings from other brain imaging technologies (EEG and MRI)
			with results from PET studies.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="psychiatric_neurogenetics"><IMG ALT="Psychiatric Neurogenetics" SRC="../images/psychiatric_neurogenetics.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979-4987</P>

			<P><I>Head:</I><BR>
			Dr. James Kennedy</P>
			
			<P><I>Secretary:</I><BR>
			Kathryn Tzimika</P>
			
			<P><I>Biostatistics and Informatics:</I><BR>
			Fabio Macciardi and David Lang</P>
			
			<P><I>Postdoctoral Fellows:</I><BR>
			David Naimark, Andrew Paterson, Art Petronis, Glen Sunohara, John Vincent</P>

			<P><I>Technicians:</I><BR>
			Nicole King, Fariba Sam</P>

			<P><I>Technology Liaison Officer:</I><BR>
			Thomas Parsons (979-4685)</P>

			<P><I>Clinical Coordinator:</I><BR>
			Wendy Hiscox, RN</P>

			<P>Genetic factors play a role in the causes of
			schizophrenia, manic depressive illness, some anxiety
			disorders, alcoholism, eating disorders, autism, impulse
			control disorders, and some dementias. Researchers in the
			Psychiatric Neurogenetics Section headed by Dr. James
			Kennedy, are actively searching for the abnormal genes
			involved in the causes, expression, treatment, and possible
			cures of these disorders.</P>
			
			<P>The Section houses one of the world's most comprehensive
			collections of interview data and DNA samples from patients
			with psychiatric disorders and their families, allowing
			researchers to pursue diverse lines of inquiry and make
			extensive comparisons among mental illnesses. Aided by new
			technology in molecular genetics, Psychiatric Neurogenetic
			researchers have contributed significantly to advances in
			the understanding of a variety of psychiatric disorders.</P>
			
			<P>Two general strategies are used in the lab. In one
			strategy, investigators scan all the human chromosomes using
			a wide array of DNA markers in the hope of discovering a
			disease gene without prior knowledge of the brain processes
			involved. In the second, researchers test genes known or
			believed to be involved in brain function in psychiatric
			diseases, for example, dopamine receptor genes in
			schizophrenia.</P>
			
			<P>Among several lines of inquiry, researchers are:</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Developing a method for locating and characterizing
			markers in DNA;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Pioneering a laboratory screening technique which may
			ultimately detect genetic vulnerability (unstable DNA) to
			schizophrenia and manic-depressive illness;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Analysing paragenetic phenomena in schizophrenia --
			errors at the functional rather than the structural level of
			DNA;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Genetic variations in schizophrenia affecting production
			and quantity of the D4 receptor gene (elevated six-fold in
			schizophrenic brain);</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Examining variations in the D4 receptor gene and
			variants in the serotonin system in relation to
			responsiveness to atypical neuroleptic medications;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Investigating disturbances in intracellular signalling
			which may contribute to development of schizophrenia, in
			particular variations in cellular physiology in the gene for
			phospholipase A2 (PLA2);</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Confirming the location of the disease gene for Darier's
			disease -- apparently related to psychosis in schizophrenia;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Examining variations in the genes which play a role in
			the development of brain structures which may be involved in
			schizophrenia (N-cadherin and alpha-3 integrin);</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Experimenting with the antisense of specific dopamine
			genes to deactivate those genes and reduce production of
			receptors thought to be implicated in the movement disorder,
			tardive dyskinesia;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Researching the association between abnormalities in the
			D4 receptor gene and in the tyrosine hydroxylase (TH) gene
			in manic-depressive illness, and the implications of this
			for response to lithium treatment;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Investigating the autosomal (non-sex-linked) dominant
			gene implicated in obsessive compulsive disorder;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Studying the genetics of anxiety disorder in relation to
			hypersensitivity to the brain protein cholecystokinin (CCK);</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Studying the interplay of genetic factors, stress, and
			diet in hypertension;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Investigating an increase in the risk for Attention
			Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD) among persons carrying
			the dopamine D4 seven repeat allele.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="transgenics_lab"><IMG ALT="Transgenics Lab" SRC="../images/transgenics_lab.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>Head:</I><BR>
			Dr. Qun-Yong Zhou</P>

			<P>Transgenics research, one of the fastest-growing new
			areas in scientific research, is a means of learning about
			the role of genes in both normal and abnormal behaviour via
			live models. By manipulating genetic makeup -- 'knocking
			out' (removing) identified genes or introducing diseased
			genes at either the embryonic or adult stage, researchers
			will mimic disorders in animals. With these models,
			researchers can use experimental approaches not possible in
			humans to directly study the relationship between genes and
			behaviour, to observe the effects of medications, learn
			about genes whose function is currently unknown, and
			differentiate developmental effects from gene-induced
			effects. Transgenics links genetics, neurochemistry, and
			behaviour in a coherent framework.</P>
			
			<P>Used for psychiatric research, investigators hope to
			pinpoint the genes responsible for such disorders as
			schizophrenia and manic-depressive illness, as the basis for
			designing more directly-targeted drugs which treat illnesses
			more effectively and with fewer side effects. Ultimately the
			goal is gene replacement therapy -- replacing disease genes
			with healthy genes that stabilize the system to eliminate
			disease.</P>
			
			<P>The new transgenics facility at The Clarke -- one of the
			few such labs in Canada exclusively focused on psychiatric
			disease -- will be a vital resource for all basic research
			sections and will stimulate linkages across sections
			allowing departments to share findings.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="womens_mental_health"><IMG ALT="Women's Mental Health Research" SRC="../images/womens_mental_health.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>(416) 979-6922</P>

			<P><I>Head:</I><BR>
			Dr. Brenda Toner</P>
			
			<P><I>Secretary:</I><BR>
			Kathy Downie</P>
			
			<P><I>Psychologist:</I><BR>
			Shelagh Emmott</P>
			
			<P><I>Research Staff:</I><BR>
			Donna Akman, Alisha Ali</P>

			<P>In Canada, women suffer disproportionately from eating
			disorders, major depression, anxiety, borderline personality
			disorders, and somataform disorders such as functional bowel
			disorders, chronic fatigue syndrome, and fibromyalgia. 
			Women use mental health services at twice the rate of
			men.</P>
			
			<P>The Women's Mental Health Research Program conducts
			research on issues affecting women's mental health with the
			goal of developing a mental health care system that is more
			responsive to the needs of women. Established in 1994, the
			aims of the Program are to:</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Identify factors that affect women's mental health;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Educate mental health professionals about mental health
			problems among women; and</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dvelop and integrate into the existing mental health
			care system, more empathic and effective models of mental
			health care for women.</P>

			<P>Research led by Dr. Brenda Toner, examines psychological
			and social variables affecting women's mental health and the
			interplay between these and physiological factors in the
			onset, expression and treatment of mental illnesses. Among
			those variables being investigated are poverty, low self
			esteem, gender-role conflict, and physical, sexual and
			emotional abuse. Recently Dr. Toner's group received a large
			NIH grant to conduct a multicentre study of the treatment of
			functional bowel disorders.</P>
			
			<P>The Women's Mental Health Program collaborates with other
			related programs on a range of research, educational, and
			clinical endeavours and actively sponsors formal linkages
			with a variety of community agencies. Dr. Toner has also
			organized a University of Toronto, city-wide Women's Mental
			Health interest group which examines such issues as gender
			biases in mental health training and practice, sexual
			harassment, sexual and physical abuse, integrating feminist
			principles into traditional therapies, expression of
			psychiatric disorders in women, and ethnicity and
			gender.</P>
			
			<HR>

			<P><B>For More Information, Contact:</B></P>
			
			<P>Dr. Franco Vaccarino<BR>
			Vice-President Research<BR>
			(416) 979-4675 <B>or</B></P>
			
			<P>Administrative Assistant, Research<BR>
			(416) 979-4747 ext 2455 <B>or</B></P>
			
			<P>Section Heads as listed <B>or</B></P>
			
			<P>Communications Department<BR>
			(416) 979-6816<BR>
			Clarke Institute of Psychiatry<BR>
			250 College Street<BR>
			Toronto, Ontario M5T 1R8</P>	
							
