	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: The Clarke Institute Foundation</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="The Clarke Institute Foundation" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/clarke_foundation_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>The majority of the funds necessary to operate the
			Institute are provided by the Ontario Ministry of Health.
			However, growing costs of health care, combined with limited
			public funds accessible for expansion programs, requires us
			to raise funds privately as well.</P>
			
			<P>The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry has formed a
			Foundation which solicits and allocates funds from the
			private sector for the improvement of patient care and
			research at the Institute.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#eight_ways">8 Ways to Give</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#vision">Vision Statement, Mission Statement &amp; Role</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#overview">Overview</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#healthcare">Healthcare Challenges</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#clarkes_response">The Clarke's Response</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#priorities_2000">Priorities  for the Year 2000</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#other_priorities">Other Funding Priorities</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#conclusion">Conclusion</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6 HSPACE=8 VSPACE=3>
			<TD><A HREF="#donation_form">Donation Form</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		


		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="eight_ways"><IMG ALT="8 Ways to Give"
							SRC="../images/eight_ways.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></A></P>
			
			<P><B>There are at least 8 ways to give to The Clarke
			Foundation and help the Foundation help people who suffer
			from mental illness.</B></P>
			
			<OL>
				<LI>With a <B><I>Personal Donation</I></B>.
				
				<LI>With a <B><I>Tribute Gift</I></B> for a birthday,
					anniversary, graduation, holiday, retirement or recognition
					of a special achievement.
				
				<LI>With a <B><I>Memorial Gift</I></B> in the name of
					someone who has passed away. (An acknowledgment card will be
					sent on behalf of the donor.)
				
				<LI>Through <B><I>Planned Giving</I></B>. Pledge a gift
					through your will, insurance policy, annuity or gift of real
					property.
				
				<LI>By attending our <B><I>Special Events</I></B>. Attend
					one of the Clarke Foundations' special events such as the
					&quot;<A HREF="../current_events/courage.html">Courage To
					Come Back</A>&quot; Awards Dinner on November 21, 1996, the
					Chinese New Year's Dinner &amp; Raffle in Feb./97 and the
					&quot;Extraordinary Chair Auction&quot; in May of 1997.
				
				<LI>By <B><I>Sponsoring</I></B> the &quot;<A
					HREF="../current_events/courage.html">Courage</A>&quot;
					campaign or other special events.
				
				<LI>By <B><I>Purchasing</I></B> an Entertainment 97 discount
					book, raffle tickets or other items sold by the Foundation. 
					Proceeds from the sale of these items benefit the
					Foundation.
				
				<LI>By making a donation right here through our
					<B><I>Interactive Donation</I></B> system. (Currently in
					development).
			</OL>
			
			<P>For now, just print the <A HREF="#donation_form">Donation
			Form</A> and fax it to The Clarke Foundation at (416)
			979-6910. Donations may also by made by calling The Clarke
			Foundation at (416) 979-6909.</P>
			
			<P>Tax receipts will be issued for all donations. Tax
			receipts for sponsorships will be issued according to the
			maximum amount allowable by law.</P>
			
			<P>General donations will be directed to the areas of
			greatest need at The Clarke. Donations may also be
			designated to a specific area of your choice, such as Chairs
			in Schizophrenia, Mood Disorders or Anxiety Disorders or
			other programs at The Clarke.</P>
			
			<P>Both personal and corporate donations are welcome.</P>
			
			<P>Have other ideas on how to give? <A
			HREF="mailto:comstrat@inforamp.net">Share them with
			us</A>.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="vision"><IMG ALT="Vision Statement, Mission Statement &amp; Role"
							SRC="../images/vision.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></A></P>
			
			<P><B>Vision Statement:</B></P>
			
			<P>The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry Foundation seeks to
			become the premier fundraising organization in North America
			for psychiatric research, education and patient care.</P>
			
			<P><B>Mission Statement:</B></P>
			
			<P>The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry Foundation is a
			fundraising and granting organization dedicated to the
			betterment of the mental health of the people of Ontario and
			Canada.</P>
			
			<P>The Foundation accomplishes its task by promoting and
			enhancing The Clarke, and by raising funds to support The
			Clarke's work in research, education and patient care.</P>
			
			<P><B>Role:</B></P>
			
			<P>The role of the Foundation is to enhance The Clarke's
			public image, credibility and resources through:</P>
			
			<UL>
				<LI>Building a base of contacts and supporters in selected communities.
				<LI>Creating alliances with mental health organizations.
				<LI>Participating in public education and fundraising events.
				<LI>Organizing, planning and implementing fundraising programs.
				<LI>Investing financial resources in research and educational programs.
			</UL>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="overview"><IMG ALT="Overview"
				SRC="../images/overview.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></A></P>
			
			<P>The challenges facing mental health providers and
			agencies -- universal government restraint, societal
			misunderstanding of mental health issues and chronic
			underfunding of research -- are not insurmountable. Given
			these restraints, The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry aims to
			focus on the areas of greatest need to the community with
			respect to its own particular areas of expertise. It also
			aspires to maximize its effectiveness through stronger
			partnerships with other stakeholders in the mental health
			community. The Clarke's role as the primary teaching
			hospital for the University of Toronto's Department of
			Psychiatry -- a strategic hub within the healthcare system
			-- already serves this goal.</P>
			
			<P>To reach these strategic goals, The Clarke Institute of
			Psychiatry Foundation has initiated a campaign to fund
			chairs in mood disorders, schizophrenia and anxiety
			disorders and professorships in women's mental health and
			psychiatric nursing. Other priorities include the
			establishment of directorships in General Psychiatry and
			Child &amp; Family and programs which support children and
			adolescents.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="healthcare"><IMG ALT="Healthcare Challenges"
				SRC="../images/healthcare.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></A></P>
			
			<P>The escalating cost of servicing the provincial deficit,
			flat government revenues and decreasing provincial transfer
			payments from Ottawa have all had a significant impact on
			healthcare funding. As a result, rationalization,
			integration, regionalization and restructuring are
			continuing to challenge the roles of health, research and
			educational agencies and their boards.</P>
			
			<P>Between 1992 and 1995, The Clarke's operating grants from
			the Ministry of Health decreased by 6.3%. In addition, the
			provincial government announced that funds transferred to
			Ontario hospitals will decrease by 18% during 1996 to 1999.
			Despite these cuts, The Clarke's budget for the 1996/97
			fiscal year will remain intact.</P>
			
			<P>Mental illness research has historically been underfunded
			by government and external granting agencies. (Canadians
			spend about $4 per patient per year on research into mental
			illness compared to about $1,000 to $2,000 per patient per
			year for other diseases.) Unlike other major disease groups,
			the mentally ill form a weak constituency; in fact, many of
			them are too sick to lobby for more funds or are simply
			unwilling to take their cause public as a result of
			stigma.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="clarkes_response"><IMG ALT="The Clarke's Response"
				SRC="../images/clarkes_response.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></A></P>
			
			<P>The Clarke's response to these healthcare challenges is
			laid out in its five-year strategic plan. Priorities
			outlined in this plan include:</P>
			
			<UL>
				<LI>Maintaining the commitment to basic research, focussing
					on the areas of highest public need and greatest expertise
					of The Clarke;
				
				<LI>Increasing integration of research, education and
					clinical care and enhancing the multidisciplinary healthcare
					model;
				
				<LI>Strengthening partnerships with external stakeholders
					and subsequently improving the efficiency and effectiveness
					of the mental health care system;
				
				<LI>Improving technological infrastructure to enhance
					research, care and education.
			</UL>
			
			<P>The Clarke's multidisciplinary approach to care has led
			to a dramatically reduced length-of-stay median of only 16
			days, which allows mental health professionals to help more
			people in less time. Improved linkages with caregivers in
			the community have also eased the burden on
			resource-intensive hospital care. In addition, its
			complimentary commitment to research and education has
			helped The Clarke maintain a leadership position in clinical
			care.</P>
			
			<P>The research arm of The Clarke has proven itself as a
			world leader. In the last five years, for example, funding
			for research from external granting bodies has increased by
			53% from $3.8 million to $7.4 million. The Clarke has
			particular expertise in the fields of psychosomatic
			medicine, eating disorders, schizophrenia, mood disorders,
			multicultural psychiatry and basic pharmacology. Other areas
			growing in importance include women's health, brain imaging,
			and mental health and the law.</P>
			
			<P>Despite the uncertainty prevailing in the healthcare
			system, The Clarke Institute has established itself as a
			strong and stable force working on behalf of the mentally
			ill and the community-at-large.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="priorities_2000"><IMG ALT="Priorities for the Year 2000"
				SRC="../images/priorities_2000.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></A></P>
			
			<P>The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry has embarked on a
			campaign to fund chairs in schizophrenia, mood disorders and
			anxiety disorders. These are permanent positions, funded by
			endowments of $2.2 million per chair which are designed to
			attract and retain world-class scientists.</P>
			
			<P><B>A chair is leadership.</B> Establishment of a chair lets the
			scientific community and others know that The Clarke is
			serious about reducing the pain of people who suffer from
			mental illness and discovering improved treatments and
			cures. A chair will have a galvanizing effect for many
			physicians scattered throughout the community who carry out
			research on a part-time basis. A chair is a coordinator, a
			guide, a resource, an advocate and most of all, a
			leader.</P>
			
			<P><B>A chair is an investment.</B> Research funding flows from
			several sources including government, the Medical Research
			Council, hospitals and donors. They give money to research
			that others have made a clear priority. When the Medical
			Research Council has money to disburse, for example, it will
			look to The Clarke's $2.2 million endowments and recognize
			this research as a national priority. If an advocacy group
			has money to fund a promising young scientist as a research
			fellow, they will look to the chair and recognize its
			leadership. Closer to home, if a donor wants to end the
			suffering of a family member, he or she will recognize the
			chair and the hope that comes with it. A chair is a true
			compounding investment.</P>
			
			<P><B>A chair is hope.</B> A chair is hope because an
			internationally-renowned researcher appointed to a chair is
			committed to one disease. Many medical researchers adopt a
			&quot;bottom-up&quot; approach in their work, tracing a
			particular chemical in the brain, for example, rather than
			focussing on a single disease. Chairs mean a
			&quot;top-down&quot; approach. A person holding the chair in
			schizophrenia, for example, will focus and guide diverse
			research efforts towards this disease. Moreover, an
			endowment means that this effort will continue unimpeded by
			government cutbacks. At a time when talented medical leaders
			are being lured away, an endowment will attract and retain
			the best and the brightest.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="other_priorities"><IMG ALT="Other Funding Priorities"
					SRC="../images/other_priorities.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></A></P>
			
			<P><B>Directorship: Child and Family Division</B></P>
			
			<P>A large proportion of children who need treatment, but do
			not get it, may experience life-long, chronic mental health
			problems. In order to improve the delivery of mental
			healthcare to children, The Clarke is planning to merge its
			Child and Family Division with its Child and Family Studies
			Centre and Family Court Clinic. This new strategic alliance
			will ensure the continuing care of children with psychiatric
			disorders and children affected by the divorce of their
			parents.</P>
			
			<P><I>Five-year term: $500,000</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Directorship: General Psychiatry Division</B></P>
			
			<P>In response to concern with the growing subspecialization
			in psychiatry at the expense of general, hospital-based
			psychiatry, The Clarke created a new General Psychiatry
			Division in 1993. It is designed to respond to any patient
			in psychiatric crisis who &quot;comes through the door&quot;
			and provide access to a high standard of multidisciplinary,
			integrated care. In addition, it is a rich training ground
			for mental health professionals. A five-year directorship
			will steer this new initiative toward
			&quot;reinventing&quot; general psychiatry.</P>
			
			<P><I>Five-year term: $500,000</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Professorship: Psychiatric Nursing</B></P>
			
			<P>Although medicine is oriented towards the treatment and
			cure of disease and nursing is focused on the individual and
			recovery, research indicates that both of these components
			are required for effective healthcare. In fact, studies
			indicate that high-quality nursing care improves quality of
			life and facilitates recovery. Despite these findings, the
			vast majority of funding is directed towards the study of
			disease and the search for cures while corresponding support
			for nursing research especially in the field of psychiatric
			nursing is virtually nonexistent. The Professorship in
			Nursing will develop structure and studies which integrate
			both behavioural and biological science into the practice of
			nursing and further improve the outcomes for patients who
			suffer from psychiatric illness.</P>
			
			<P><I>Endowment fund: $1.1 million</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Professorship: Women's Mental Health</B></P>
			
			<P>Women are diagnosed more frequently with depression,
			anxiety and eating disorders yet often encounter mental
			health services which are fragmented, difficult to access
			and unsuitable for their needs and circumstances. In
			response to this need, The Clarke seeks to establish a
			Professorship in Women's Mental Health which will help
			create a mental health system which is more responsive to
			the needs of women. In addition, this endowment will raise
			the stature of women's mental health in the field of
			psychiatry and ensure continuing education, research and
			leadership.</P>
			
			<P><I>Endowment fund: $1.1 million</I></P>
			
			<P><B>The Arson Prevention Program for Children (TAPP-C)</B></P>
			
			<P>Juvenile firesetters are responsible for at least
			one-third of intentionally set fires which cause in excess
			of $244 million in damage per year. In fact, fire-related
			injuries are second only to transportation accidents in
			causing deaths among children who are two to four times more
			likely to die in fires than are adults. In response to this
			critical need to help curb children and adolescents from
			starting fires, The Clarke established The Arson Prevention
			Program for Children (TAPP-C) in 1991. This program seeks to
			improve understanding and develop a treatment manual for
			children and adolescents who start fires. TAPP-C plans to
			share its research and treatment procedures with mental
			health professionals throughout Canada during the coming
			year.</P>
			
			<P><I>Annual treatment and educational programs: $150,000</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Baffin Island Suicide Prevention</B></P>
			
			<P>Researchers are looking at major risk factors and more
			effective methods of reducing alarmingly high rates of
			suicide among Inuit communities on Baffin Island. The
			research project will call upon the people of Baffin Island
			in an effort to develop a more community-based model of
			suicide prevention.</P>
			
			<P><I>Research support: $75,000</I></P>
			
			<P><B>For Kid's Sake</B></P>
			
			<P>The For Kid's Sake program focuses on children caught in
			the crossfire of parental conflict and violence during
			divorce. As one of the few prevention and treatment programs
			for high-risk separated families, the program aims to reduce
			court litigation over child custody issues and teach more
			adaptive, non-aggressive models of conflict resolution. The
			long-term goal of the project is to prevent mental health
			problems common among parents and children exposed to overt
			conflict. Additional funding is required to carry out a
			full-scale evaluation of this program's effectiveness as
			part of the process for wide-scale implementation.</P>
			
			<P><I>Research support and equipment: $25,000</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Institute for Antisocial Youth</B></P>
			
			<P>Since 1986, violent crime committed by youths has
			increased by 124% as compared to a 40% increase in crime
			committed by adults. To help reverse this trend, the
			Institute for Antisocial Youth provides training and
			education for mental health professionals, advocates
			continuity of care for antisocial youth and promotes
			prevention of youth crime through research and education.
			Its ultimate goal is to reduce violence in our society.</P>
			
			<P><I>Printing and mailing educational material: $39,000</I></P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="conclusion"><IMG ALT="Conclusion"
					SRC="../images/conclusion.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></A></P>
			
			<P>The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry is a national leader
			in the fight against mental illness. Its innovative research
			has opened up new pathways to better cures and treatments;
			its effective clinical care has made a dramatic difference
			in the lives of the mentally ill and their families and
			friends and its dissemination of knowledge has helped mental
			health professionals improve treatment for people who suffer
			from mental illness.</P>
			
			<P>After thirty years of development, The Clarke's ability
			to improve the quality of life for people who suffer from
			mental illness and for the community-at-large is
			unparalleled.</P>
			
			<P>However, The Clarke's potential goes far beyond its
			ability, which is based largely on government funding. It is
			up to the wider community -- families, friends, businesses,
			charitable foundations -- to realize this potential through
			financial and public support of The Clarke's leadership in
			the field of mental health.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="donation_form"><IMG ALT="Donation Form"
					SRC="../images/donation_form.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></A></P>
			
			<P><B>Yes! I would like to support The Clarke and the fight
			against mental illness.</B></P>
			
			<P>[Donation form under construction.]</P>
			
			<P>Please make cheques payable to:</P>
			
			<P>Clarke Institute of Psychiatry Foundation<BR>
			250 College St, Suite G114-115<BR>
			Toronto, Ontario<BR>
			M5T 1R8</P>
			
			<P>Thank you! A tax receipt will be issued for your donation.</P>
			
			<P>Charitable Registration No. 0796417-13</P>			
			
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
