<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About The Clarke: History</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=4>
			<H1><IMG ALT="A History of The Clarke" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/history_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=15 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD ROWSPAN=8><IMG ALT="[Photo]" SRC="../images/charles_clarke.gif" WIDTH=147 HEIGHT=173>
			<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=ABSBORROM WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6>
			<TD><A HREF="#How The Clarke Became a Reality">How The Clarke Became a Reality</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=ABSBORROM WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6>
			<TD><A HREF="#Legislative Mandate">Legislative Mandate</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=ABSBORROM WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6>
			<TD><A HREF="#Education of Professionals">Education of Professionals</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=ABSBORROM WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6>
			<TD><A HREF="#Funding">Funding</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=ABSBORROM WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6>
			<TD><A HREF="#Structure">Structure</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=ABSBORROM WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6>
			<TD><A HREF="#Purposes of The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry">Purposes of The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/bullet_wt_sm.gif" ALIGN=ABSBORROM WIDTH=6 HEIGHT=6>
			<TD><A HREF="#Clarke Directors and Psychiatrists-in-Chief">Clarke Directors and Psychiatrists-in-Chief</A>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=15 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
		<TD><TD><TD><P><I>&quot;Who among us today could build a house;
			race a yacht; be a champion tennis player; play the violin
			with a group of professional musicians; teach psychiatry in
			a faculty of medicine; superintend a large hospital; write
			numerous articles for professional journals, and still have
			enough time to harass busy politicians in order to provide
			better care for the mentally ill?&quot;</I></P>

			<P>M.B.Dymond, Minister of Health, about Dr. C.K. Clarke, in
			his opening address at The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry in
			1966.</P>
						
			<P>The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry, located in Toronto at
			250 College Street and opened in 1966, was named in honour
			of Dr. Charles Kirk Clarke. C.K Clarke, often considered the
			father of Canadian psychiatry, practiced psychiatry in the
			late 1800's and early 1900's in Ontario - a time when almost
			all psychiatric patients were kept in asylums operated by
			the government. Operation of the institutions for the insane
			was frequently affected by political changes.</P>
			
			<P>In 1880, following his training in Toronto, Clarke went
			to the Hamilton Hospital for the insane as Assistant
			Superintendent and, late in 1881, was transferred to the
			Rockwood Asylum in Kingston where he joined his
			brother-in-law, Dr. William Metcalf, who was the
			Superintendent. Together they formed the medical staff.</P>
			
			<P>In early 1885, despite his many administrative and
			clinical innovations in partnership with Dr. Metcalf, Clarke
			had decided to quit because, in his words, &quot;I love
			psychiatry but hate politics.&quot; The day after Clarke's
			resignation was in the hands of the government (August
			13,1885), he and Metcalf were making ward rounds when a
			patient rushed them and stabbed Metcalf fatally.</P>
			
			<P>At the request of the government, Clarke withdrew his
			resignation and became Superintendent at Kingston &quot;in
			order to protect several hundred defenseless creatures from
			a political hireling who might be pitch-forked into the
			position.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>Two of Clarke's earliest measures to improve the
			patients' conditions were the establishment of non-restraint
			and of practical forms of occupational therapy. He set up
			shops for various industries, chiefly brush and broom
			making, where many patients were employed. Soon Kingston was
			supplying the other asylums and selling brooms and brushes
			on the open market. Business and labour complained that this
			was unfair competition; the politicians heard the complaints
			and instructions went from the Superintendent of Asylums to
			Clarke to curtail his mischievous activity. Clarke's
			eventual response was to set up other diversional activities
			including drama clubs and an orchestra.</P>
			
			<P>In 1887, Clarke began the first course in Canada
			providing formal training for nurses and attendants caring
			for the mentally ill. In 1895, he became the first professor
			of mental diseases at Queen's University, Kingston. In 1905,
			he was appointed Superintendent of the Toronto Asylum.</P>
			
			<P>In 1907, he was appointed to a Royal Commission
			established by the Provincial Government to visit major
			mental clinics in Europe. The Commission was so impressed
			with Dr. Kraepelin's Clinic in Munich that it recommended
			establishing a similar clinic in Toronto. In 1908, the
			Government announced its intention to do so at a cost of
			$500,000. However, this clinic was never built because, in
			Clarke's view, of the &quot;jealousy and malicious
			tactics&quot; of his colleagues in the mental hospitals.</P>
			
			<P>Clarke became the first professor of psychiatry at the
			University of Toronto in 1906 and Dean of the Faculty of
			Medicine in 1908 - the same year in which he became Medical
			Superintendent at the newly established Toronto General
			Hospital.</P>
			
			<P>He established the first out-patient psychiatric clinic
			in Canada in a small house which was part of the Toronto
			General Hospital at the time. Dr. Ernest Jones, later a
			colleague of Freud's and his biographer, was the outpatient
			clinic's first Medical Director.</P>
			
			<P>Clarke continued to work for his objective of a
			Psychiatric Clinic which would combine exemplary care with
			research and education.<P>
			
			<P>Writing in 1915, he stated:</P>
			
			<P><I>&quot;...such a Hospital...must be kept
			absolutely free from political control...the ideal
			arrangement would be to have it under the supervision of a
			dignified Board of Trustees of the same class as those to be
			found in the General Hospitals; men who are superior to the
			temptation of political exigency...&quot;</I></P>
			
			<P>During World War I, Dr. Clarke had to assume additional
			administrative responsibilities. As Dean he had the
			unenviable job of persuading the various hospitals to
			improve their clinical facilities in order to provide
			adequate instruction for medical students. Doing this in
			wartime, with the inevitable shortages of staff and
			equipment, must have been enormously difficult. These,
			however, were only part of Dr. Clarke's concerns. He also
			had the responsibility, in March 1995, for organizing the
			University's No. 4 Overseas Hospital consisting of 1040
			beds.</P>
			
			<P>The end of hostilities found Dr. Clarke still deeply
			involved in the complicated problems of running Toronto
			General Hospital and initiating a 6-year curriculum for
			medical students at the University of Toronto. All this was
			in addition to his work as Director of the Mental Deficiency
			Clinic, Professor of Psychiatry and Director of the
			Psychological Laboratory.</P>
			
			<P>At the height of his career, a seemingly insignificant
			meeting altered the course of Dr. Clarke's life. It also
			opened a new era in the history of the treatment of the
			mentally ill in Canada. This meeting was held in the Toronto
			home of Mrs. D A. Dunlop on 26 February 1918. The main
			speaker of the evening was a visitor from the United States,
			Clifford Beers, author of &quot;A Mind That Found
			Itself.&quot; Two months later, the Canadian National
			Committee for Mental Hygiene, now the Canadian Mental Health
			Association, was formed with Dr. C.K. Clarke as Medical
			Director.</P>
			
			<P>In 1918, pressure of work compelled Dr. Clarke to
			relinquish his position as Superintendent of the Toronto
			General Hospital. However, his position as Dean of the
			Faculty of Medicine continued to be as demanding as ever. He
			resigned his appointment as Dean of Medicine in 1920,
			intending to devote himself entirely to the leadership of
			the National Committee for Mental Hygiene. To celebrate his
			50 years of service to psychiatry, the 66-year-old Dr.
			Clarke was honoured in 1923 with an invitation from the
			Royal Medico-Psychological Association of Great Britain and
			Ireland to deliver the Fourth Annual Maudsley Lecture. In
			Toronto, a distinguished Committee was formed to celebrate
			Dr. Clarke's Golden Jubilee. His portrait, which now hangs
			in The Clarke Institute, was painted by Curtis Williamson
			for this occasion but, before it could be presented to him,
			&quot;C.K. became ill and died on 20 January 1924.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=15 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="How The Clarke Became a Reality"><IMG ALT="How The Clarke Became a Reality"
						SRC="../images/history_how.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></P></A>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P>Toronto Psychiatric Hospital possessed only 72 beds and
			its small building was inadequate to support the facilities
			envisaged by Dr. Stokes. For much of his tenure in Toronto,
			he struggled to remedy this. He brought together influential
			people from university and business interests, and by
			allying these with the provincial government, he set in
			motion those forces which ultimately resulted in the opening
			of The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry in 1966.</P>
			
			<P>In the forty years between the opening of the Toronto
			Psychiatric Hospital and the opening of The Clarke on July
			1, 1966, three events occurred that helped The Clarke become
			a reality.</P>
			
			<P>First, in 1923, the government of Ontario was bequeathed
			a sum of money from the Patterson estate to be directed to
			research in the field of mental diseases. The government, at
			least partly in deference to the family's concern about
			being associated with mental disease, did nothing with this
			money other than to turn it over to the Treasury for
			management. In the mid 1950's, Dr. Stokes became aware of
			the money from the Patterson estate, which had grown to
			about $250,000. He encouraged the government to make it
			available for the purpose for which it was intended.</P>
			
			<P>In 1961, Dr. Matthew Dymond, Minister of Health, who was
			actively interested in the field of mental health and who
			wanted to see an Institute independent of the Ontario mental
			hospital system, established the Ontario Mental Health
			Foundation with Mr. Justice Arthur Kelly as its first
			chairman.</P>
			
			<P>Among its many objectives, the Foundation was to
			establish a hospital or hospitals for the diagnosis and
			treatment of mental disorders and for research and
			education. Almost immediately, Mr. Justice Kelly and Dr.
			Stokes began work on the founding of an Ontario psychiatric
			institute. In 1964, their work came to fruition with the
			creation of The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry, through the
			addition of Part 2 to the Ontario Mental Health Foundation
			Act. The Clarke actually opened on July 1, 1966.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=15 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="Legislative Mandate"><IMG ALT="Legislative Mandate"
						SRC="../images/history_mandate.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></P></A>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P>The Institute operates under Part II of the Ontario
			Mental Health Foundation Act, R.S.O.. 1970. This statute
			provides for the organization and function of the Institute
			&quot;...to maintain, manage and operate a hospital with
			facilities for psychiatric research, education, diagnosis
			and treatment.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>In terms of patient care, the Institute is recognized as
			a hospital under the Public Hospitals Act., R.S.O.. 1970,
			and is listed under Group H.</P>
			
			<P>The Institute is designated as a psychiatric facility
			under Ontario Regulation 576 under the Mental Health Act,
			R.S.O. 1980 as amended by 1983 - Chapter 75.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=15 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="Education of Professionals"><IMG ALT="Education of Professionals"
						SRC="../images/history_education.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></P></A>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P>The Clarke has close ties with the University of Toronto.
			The Chairman of the University's Department of Psychiatry is
			also the Director and Psychiatrist-in-Chief of the
			Institute. The Institute has an agreement with the
			University of Toronto which recognizes the hospital as a
			teaching hospital. The Institute is considered a clinical
			teaching unit as defined by the Association of Canadian
			Medical Colleges, i.e. one which provides opportunity for
			undergraduate and graduate medical education under the
			auspices of a Faculty of Medicine of a Canadian University.
			The current agreement came into effect 30 June 1972. Formal
			training is also provided to students in nursing,
			psychology, social work, occupational therapy, speech
			pathology, pharmacy and child care work through affiliation
			agreements with schools of these disciplines at several
			universities and colleges.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=15 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="Funding"><IMG ALT="Funding"
						SRC="../images/history_funding.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></P></A>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P>The Ministry of Health provides almost all the funds
			required to operate the Institute. The medical staff are
			organized into a partnership, called &quot;The Associates in
			Psychiatry.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>All patients coming to the Institute are seen regardless
			of their ability to pay. In general, the physicians are
			remunerated on a fee for service basis through health
			insurance carried by the patient. Research grants and funds
			for special programs are received from the University,
			Foundations and other scientific granting bodies.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=15 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="Structure"><IMG ALT="Structure"
						SRC="../images/history_structure.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></P></A>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P>The Institute operates as a public hospital with its own
			Board of Trustees. Although it is not one of the ten
			provincial psychiatric hospitals, it is considered an
			&quot;agency&quot; of the Provincial Government. Members of
			the Board are appointed by provincial Order-in-Council, with
			one member elected by the medical staff (pursuant to the
			Public Hospitals Act), and two trustees nominated by the
			Ontario Mental Health Foundation.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=15 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="Purposes of The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry"><IMG ALT="Purposes of The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry"
						SRC="../images/history_purposes.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></P></A>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P>The Institute provides, promotes and enhances psychiatric
			research, education, and clinical care as mutually enhancing
			activities. The Clarke serves as a provincial resource
			striving to provide leadership to investigators, educators,
			and clinicians in psychiatry and allied disciplines. To this
			end The Clarke seeks to develop, maintain and evaluate
			exemplary and innovative programs for:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The investigation of factors which contribute to psychiatric disorders and which interfere with mental health;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The diagnosis, treatment, rehabilitation and prevention of psychiatric disorders;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The training of investigators;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The education of students in the health sciences, as they relate to mental disorders, in affiliation with the University of Toronto and in collaboration with other educational institutions;</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>The continuing education of and consultation to professionals with respect to problems related to mental health and illness, and</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Public education in the area of mental health and illness.</P>
			
			<P>The Clarke will plan and provide programs with the
			highest level of academic and clinical standards, and with a
			sensitivity to the needs of the province.</P>
			
			<P>The Clarke will maintain a supportive environment in
			which staff can work to meet institutional, professional and
			personal goals to the highest standards of performance, and
			to feel dignity and satisfaction in their work.</P>
			
			<P>The Clarke will endeavour to meet its goals in these
			areas by making effective and efficient use of its
			resources.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=15 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=350 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P><A NAME="Clarke Directors and Psychiatrists-in-Chief"><IMG ALT="Clarke Directors and Psychiatrists-in-Chief"
						SRC="../images/history_directors.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26 BORDER=0></P></A>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><TD>
			<TD><P>Aldwyn B. Stokes <I>July - Dec. 1966</I><BR>
			Robin C.A. Hunter <I>1967 - 1974</I><BR>
			Frederick H. Lowy <I>1974 - 1980</I><BR>
			Vivian M. Rakoff <I>1980 - 1990</I><BR>
			Paul E. Garfinkel <I>1990 - Present</I></P>
			
			<P><B>For More Information, Contact:</B></P>

			<P>Communications Office<BR>
			250 College Street<BR>
			Toronto, Ontario<BR>
			M5T 1R8<BR>
			(416) 979-6816</P>
			
			<P>&copy; June 1995</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=4><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
