					Sidney Kennedy, MD, FRCP(C)<BR>
					Cynthia Lazar, MD<BR>
					Elizabeth Scott, MSc, BSCOT, OT(C)<BR>
					Jean Simpson, RN, BScN<BR>
					Franco J. Vaccarino, PhD<BR>
					Robert B. Zipursky, MD, FRCP(C)</P><BR>


			<P><B><A NAME="Battle"><IMG ALT="Leadership in the Battle Against Mental Illness"
			SRC="../images/annual_report_battle.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></B></P>
				<P>"Leadership in the battle against mental illness" -- our
				new mission statement. Anyone who has ever been on a
				committee developing something like a mission statement will
				know those seven words were not arrived at readily. There
				were debates, alternatives, suggested rewordings. Some said
				"leadership" was too ambitious, too presumptuous. Some said
				"battle" was the wrong term -- politically incorrect, too
				militaristic. But, in the end, the mission stood.</P>
				
				<P>It is hard to know how far to go with the metaphor, as
				the word "battle" conjures up powerful and painful images...
				opposing forces, weapons, troops, strategies, victors,
				casualties... and memorials. Unfortunately, mental illness
				involves all of those. To us it also signifies hope, help
				and healing for people with mental illnesses.</P>
				
				<P>Our adversaries are the powerful disorders of the mind --
				schizophrenia, manic-depression, depression, antisocial
				personality, many others. But psychiatry as a discipline is
				still young. Many of the treatments we use to fight mental
				illnesses are still in the developmental stages --
				psychotherapy, medications, rehabilitation, education. Most
				of what we now know in psychiatry we have learned since I
				graduated from medical school. I feel both humble and proud
				to tell you that a part of that knowledge has emanated from
				The Clarke.</P>
				
				<P>Engaged in the struggle are the caregivers, researchers,
				fundraisers, families, counselors, self-help groups -- all
				those who lend their skill and care to the campaign. This
				report tells of some of their work together, within the
				Institute and in the community. Strategies are many --
				collaborative research, innovative projects, new therapies,
				patient and public education -- you will read about some of
				them in this report.</P>
				
				<P>The enormity of the battle is reflected in the numbers.
				The one in one hundred who have schizophrenia. The one in
				ten who have depression. The ten in a hundred who have
				obsessions or fears or anxieties that rule their lives.
				These are the people who are truly on the battlefield every
				moment of every day. For many, with the help of families,
				caregivers and therapies, the struggle is waged and won. Too
				many are still casualties -- the suicides, the lost
				potential, the failed careers, the broken families. Like a
				war zone, sometimes you see them, lying on the streets of
				Toronto.</P>
				
				<P>These lives are the reason The Clarke is dedicated to the
				other part of the mission -- "leadership." At times, The
				Clarke has been accused of too little leadership, too little
				sharing. But leadership to us means working through, and
				working with, all of those who are devoted to improving our
				understanding of mental illness. It means listening to those
				who suffer and to their families, and including them in our
				work.</P>
				
				<P>On the occasion of our anniversary, we look back to our
				origins. Although the Institute is only 30 years old, its
				founders go back to the turn of this century, founders who
				believed mental illnesses were illnesses, when everyone
				thought they were demons. If they had not been bold enough
				to lead, we might still be casting out devils. When we feel
				our progress is slow, we need only to look at the wretched
				conditions of less than a century ago to know what a
				challenge they assumed. And what a victory is being won. The
				anniversary renewal of our mission is a tribute to all of
				those who are part of our heritage.</P>
				
				<P>There are other opponents in the battle -- ignorance,
				fear and their ally, stigma. This can be your mission -- to
				understand mental illnesses; to recognize the war, not the
				personal weakness; to trade derision for compassion; to help
				advance the campaign. The mission still stands.</P>
				
				<P>I invite you to join us.</P>
				
				<P>Paul E. Garfinkel, MD</P>
				
				<P><I>President and Psychiatrist-in-Chief<BR>
				Clarke Institute of Psychiatry</I></P>
				
				<P><I>Professor and Chair, Department of Psychiatry<BR>
				University of Toronto</I></P><BR>


			<P><B><A NAME="30_Years_On"><IMG ALT="30 Years On: An Overview"
			SRC="../images/annual_report_30_years.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></B></P>
				<P>At times over the past year, it seemed like our battle
				was not against mental illnesses, but was more a struggle to
				balance competing yet equally important priorities and to
				maintain levels of care, education and research with
				dwindling resources. At The Clarke, the pressure to maximize
				our financial and human resources, and yet improve quality
				and activity, engendered a number of initiatives.</P>
				
				<P>Some of them are briefly outlined below:</P>
				
				<P>The Hospital Restructuring Report of the Metro Toronto
				District Health Council reaffirmed The Clarke's mandate as
				an independent specialty mental health facility and its role
				as a provincial leader in psychiatric research, education,
				diagnosis and treatment. The Report recommended closer
				collaboration in psychiatry among the downtown teaching
				hospitals and this Annual Report outlines some areas where
				this is expanding. The Restructuring Report also recognized
				mental health care as a priority and emphasized augmentation
				of community-based mental health services to reduce use of
				psychiatric beds in general and specialty hospitals. The
				Clarke's response to the Hospital Restructuring Committee's
				Report stressed the need to protect the existing psychiatry
				beds, urging that without significant community input,
				further reductions would stress an already
				stretched-to-the-limit mental health system.</P>
				
				<P>The Strategic Planning Advisory Task Force, in
				consultation with Senior Management and staff, developed a
				plan to guide the Institute through the next five years. The
				Task Force members represented Board members, consumers,
				family members, community representatives and all levels of
				Clarke staff. The Task Force analysed our external and
				internal environments, and defined more explicitly our "core
				businesses." Invited presentations from government and
				community leaders gave insight into community expectations.
				The Task Force developed a new Mission Statement, which more
				clearly describes our purpose and vision; it is reprinted on
				the front of this report. Key directions for the Institute
				to the year 2000 are to maintain our focus on major mental
				disorders; increase emphasis on the integration of clinical
				care, research and education; preserve our commitment to
				basic research as the hope for the future; stress transfer
				of knowledge from research to practice; and expand
				partnerships with organizations who share our goals. New
				work in this direction is described in later pages.</P>
				
				<P>The Institute's 1995-96 Operating Plan was approved by
				the Ministry of Health and received a positive review for
				balancing the budget with minimal effect on service delivery
				and staff. Our Work Group on Diversity conducted an
				extensive survey of staff experiences of prejudice or
				discrimination in the workplace, with encouraging results.
				Nine out of ten respondents agreed that "regarding diversity
				issues, The Clarke is a good place for staff, students and
				volunteers." However, several areas for improvement were
				identified; these concerns are shared and are being
				supported with appropriate initiatives. As part of this
				thrust, diversity awareness training was held for management
				staff and new employment policies on diversity were
				adopted.</P>
				
				<P>Effective April 1995, Ms. Jean Simpson was appointed
				Executive Vice-President and Chief Operating Officer,
				sharing the senior administrative duties of The Clarke with
				Dr. Paul Garfinkel. Dr. David Goldbloom succeeded Dr.
				Richard Swinson as Vice President Medical Affairs and Chief
				of Staff. Dr. Swinson continues as Head of the Anxiety
				Disorders Clinic.</P>
				
				<P>Dr. Gregory Brown retired as Vice President Research, but
				continues as Head of the Neuroendocrinology Research
				Section. Dr. Brown also became our Corporate Liaison
				Officer, to develop partnerships with industry in support of
				psychiatric research. Dr. Franco Vaccarino was appointed
				Vice President Research. Dr Vaccarino is Professor of
				Psychology and Psychiatry at University of Toronto, Senior
				Research Consultant in the Mood and Anxiety Division and an
				internationally-recognized researcher in the behavioural
				action of neuropeptides.</P>
				
				<P>Ms. Beverley Abosh completed her term as Vice President
				of Professional Services this year and was succeeded by Ms.
				Elizabeth Scott. Ms. Scott combines her new role with her
				position as Head of Occupational Therapy. Her training and
				interests are in epidemiology and quality-of-life research
				with persons with serious mental illness. Ms. Abosh
				continues as Head of Social Work and is developing a Family
				Institute which will promote excellence in work with
				troubled families and families of persons with mental
				illness. The Institute will provide consultation and
				training on the impact of mental illness on families and
				evaluation of family interventions.</P>
				
				<P>Consistent with our emphasis on continuing evaluation at
				all levels, program reviews were undertaken in three of our
				clinical Divisions. A program review of the Continuing Care
				Division recommended that this highly-rated model be
				extended to community sectors with a mandate for long-term
				community care. The Clarke, as a tertiary referral centre,
				will focus its resources on the provision of short-term
				multidisciplinary care to patients at all stages of
				schizophrenia, ranging from young adults experiencing their
				first episode of schizophrenia to persistently ill patients
				whose illness has been resistant to current therapies. The
				services of the reorganized Schizophrenia Division, with Dr.
				Robert Zipursky as new Head, are described in more detail in
				this report.</P>
				
				<P>The program review of our two child psychiatry Divisions
				-- Family Court Clinic and Child and Family Studies --
				recommended an integration of these Divisions' programs and
				services, offering a shared range of services to combine
				strengths and increase collaboration. More linkages with our
				adult Divisions were suggested, to increase continuity of
				care across age groups. The review recommended that our
				child psychiatry expertise could best be utilized in more
				extensive consultative and backup services to front line
				professionals, again reiterating the tertiary care
				mandate.</P>
				
				<P>An external review of the potential benefits or
				disadvantages of sharing administrative services between The
				Clarke and neighbouring Addiction Research Foundation found
				that we are providing administrative services in a highly
				effective and efficient manner and that potential cost
				savings are minimal unless major consolidations are
				undertaken. Possible actions are being carefully reviewed in
				light of impact on staff and facilities and the costs that
				may be necessary for the two organizations to work more
				closely together. In the same vein, we streamlined by
				closing our Cafeteria and revamping our ground floor Coffee
				Shop, producing a more pleasant, accessible and
				cost-effective dining area for patients, staff, and
				visitors. We opened a new and welcoming information desk to
				direct patients and visitors to our many services.</P>
				
				<P>Staff involvement and communication were heightened with
				the weekly publication of a newsletter to keep staff
				up-to-date. Open interchange is facilitated with informal
				monthly "Let's Get Acquainted" coffee sessions between the
				President and line staff and a confidential voicemail box
				direct to the President and Executive Vice President. Our
				Board undertook a series of regular tours of the facility,
				giving an opportunity for dialogue between Board and
				frontline staff. A market research survey was undertaken to
				measure knowledge of, and satisfaction with, Clarke programs
				and directions. Results indicated a good level of awareness
				of The Clarke mission and satisfaction with our services,
				and numerous constructive suggestions for future
				improvements.</P>
				
				<P>We are grateful to our funders, particularly the Ministry
				of Health, and to the charitable, corporate and individual
				partners who generously support our work. We appreciate the
				wisdom and direction of Board members who truly share the
				Institute's sense of purpose. We are, as always, indebted to
				our accomplished staff; they are a formidable force. And
				most of all we thank our patients, clients, consumers and
				their families who, by trusting us enough to share their
				struggle, thereby grant us a singular privilege.</P>
				
				<P>Andrea Baumann, PhD<BR>
				<I>Chair, Board of Trustees</I></P>
				
				<P>Paul E. Garfinkel, MD, FRCP(C)<BR>
				<I>President and Psychiatrist-in-Chief</I></P><BR>


			<P><B><A NAME="Financial_Statements"><IMG ALT="Financial Statements"
			SRC="../images/annual_report_financial.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></A></B></P>
				<P><B>Clarke Institute of Psychiatry<BR>
				Statement of Revenue, Expenses and Operating Fund Balance</B></P>

