<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: Media Information: Media Releases: Clarke Institute of Psychiatry Implements Computer-based Treatment for Stuttering</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/media_bkgd.gif" TEXT="#000000"
		  LINK="#FF9900" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Media Releases" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/media_releases_h.gif"></H1></TR>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>DATE: November 22, 1996<BR>
			CONTACT: Communications<BR>
			PHONE #: (416) 979-6816</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Clarke Institute of Psychiatry Implements
			Computer-based Treatment for Stuttering</B></P>
			
			<P>&quot;Dr. Fluency, a ground-breaking new computer program
			being tested by the Speech Pathology Department at The
			Clarke, vastly improves treatment for stuttering,&quot; says
			Dr. Robert Kroll, Head of Speech Pathology and Assistant
			Professor of Speech Pathology and Psychiatry, U of T. The
			advent of computer treatment for stuttering has an
			interesting history.</P>
			
			<P>Ten years ago Dr. Kroll trained Israeli clinicians in the
			therapy program offered by The Clarke. One of the clients
			who took the program, Ari Friedman, was a computer expert
			and later developed this computer program for patients to
			practice at home. After the Israeli government provided
			funding to test the program worldwide, The Clarke was
			designated as a testing site.</P>
			
			<P>A powerful computer with CD ROM is needed to run the
			program, so David Caron, VP, Information Processing Services
			for Bell Sygma has loaned two computers to run the program.
			Mr. Caron is a strong proponent of the program and was
			himself a client of Speech Pathology over 20 years ago.</P>
			
			<P>Speech therapy for stuttering entails a series of speech
			exercises designed to facilitate fluency. Clients learn to
			monitor and control voice speed, vocal cord use and tooth
			and lip pressure. Previously, clients would produce sounds
			and then a therapist would provide personal feedback on
			their exercises. With the new program, the computer listens
			to and analyses speech and then gives feedback to the
			client. In addition to aural feedback, the program provides
			visual feedback through graphics on the computer monitor
			which reinforce the correct position of the tongue and teeth
			when pronouncing various sounds.</P>
			
			<P>An intensive 3 week training program with the computer is
			offered from 9:30 am - 3:30 pm five days a week. This allows
			clients to use Dr. Fluency on an individual and group basis
			and provides feedback to staff, allowing them to examine
			both the initial program and feedback to develop an improved
			treatment program.</P>
			
			<P>Bryan Lipka, a 22-year-old credit agency worker has
			struggled with stuttering since he was a toddler. He came to
			The Clarke program this year to improve his speech and was
			lucky enough to be assigned to test the new Dr. Fluency.
			Bryan says that the computer program, &quot;makes it
			(therapy) more interesting, more accurate and facilitates
			additional home practice.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>&quot;We hope this program will help more people more
			effectively. Often it's difficult for someone to recall
			exercises when they are at home but this program is
			motivating - it aims to increase practice and fluency.
			Treatment, like any other skill, is only effective with
			long-term follow-up and practice,&quot; says Dr.
			Kroll.					</P>
			
			<P>- 30 -</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
