<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: Media Information: Media Releases: Clarke Child &amp; Family Studies Program Sharpens Psychiatric Skills of Pediatricians</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/media_bkgd.gif" TEXT="#000000"
		  LINK="#FF9900" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Media Releases" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/media_releases_h.gif"></H1></TR>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>DATE: November 18, 1996<BR>
			CONTACT: Communications<BR>
			PHONE #: (416) 979-6816</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Clarke Child &amp; Family Studies Program Sharpens
			Psychiatric Skills of Pediatricians</B></P>
			
			<P>Because a significant number of visits to pediatricians
			are due to emotional and/or behavioural problems in
			children, Dr. Tatyana Barankin and a team from The Clarke
			Child and Family Studies Centre will be offering a new
			continuing education series to strengthen pediatricians'
			skills in child psychiatry. Dr. Barankin was trained both in
			pediatrics and child psychiatry. She runs the Risk Clinic at
			The Clarke and is an Assistant Professor, Department of
			Psychiatry, U of T.</P>
			
			<P>&quot;There is a real paucity of information in this
			field. On average, only 2-4 child psychiatrists are
			graduating each year in Toronto. Pediatricians and GP's are
			filling this gap, but require additional training. We need
			to educate doctors about all the child psychiatry resources
			available; when to refer and how to use these
			resources.&quot; says Dr. Barankin</P>
			
			<P>Wanting to share The Clarke's expertise, Dr. Barankin
			envisioned a series of 8-10 training sessions, each 2 hours
			in length, which would help train community pediatricians in
			child psychiatry. The training sessions will involve a
			combination of lectures and presentation of case studies and
			participants will be encouraged to use examples from their
			own practice.</P>
			
			<P>Dr. Barankin hopes the program will help pediatricians
			learn to communicate with a child and family more
			effectively and learn there are no simple tests in
			psychiatry, but there are helpful screening instruments.
			This will help simplify the diagnostic procedure.
			Pediatricians will be exposed to a variety of pragmatic
			short-term treatment techniques that could be utilized in a
			community pediatrician's office.</P>
			
			<P>Dr. Barankin says, &quot;Child psychiatry is more complex
			than adult therapy. Often the way you approach a situation
			or phrase a question makes all the difference. If a doctor
			asks, 'You haven't been sexually abused, have you?' the
			child will be inclined to answer &quot;no.&quot; But that
			may not be the truth. A child who is brought in by their
			parent may not want to talk about their feelings immediately
			with a doctor. A slower, more sophisticated approach is
			needed.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>Assessment and treatment of psychiatric illness will be
			covered in the course and topics will include: interviewing
			techniques, approaches to treatment, depression and anxiety
			disorder in childhood, disruptive behavioural disorder,
			pediatric psychopharmacology, family issues (divorce, death
			etc.) and adolescent problems. The planning team consists of
			Drs. T. Barankin, J. Beitchman, D. Schacter, U. Jain, B.
			Ferguson and A. Saksznajder.</P>
			
			<P>Sessions will be open to community pediatricians in the
			greater Toronto area with a maximum of 20-30 doctors
			participating per session.</P>
			
			<P>Dr. Barankin initiated the program after discussions with
			Dr. Bob Issenman, Head of the OMA Section of Pediatrics,
			when she became aware that pediatricians in the community
			needed greater access to psychiatric resources and as well
			had some deficits in their training in this area.</P>
			
			<P>Pediatricians from the Greater Toronto Area were then
			polled regarding child psychiatry topics where they felt a
			need for more intensive training. Feedback on the planning
			process for these sessions was also provided by a community
			pediatrician. In addition, participants will be asked at a
			later point to evaluate the impact of this training on their
			practice patterns and knowledge gain.</P>
			
			<P>Pediatricians interested in participating in the sessions
			may contact the Education Office at 979-6852 or Dr. Barankin
			at 979-4747, X-2254. Sessions will commence in January and
			will run once a week for two hours. The full training
			process involves 8-10 sessions which are recognized as CME
			credits by the University of Toronto.</P>
			
			<P>- 30 -</P>
						

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
					WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
