<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: Media Information: Media Releases: Clarke Institute Program Helps Children with Learning Disabilities and Anxiety</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/media_bkgd.gif" TEXT="#000000"
		  LINK="#FF9900" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Media Releases" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/media_releases_h.gif"></H1></TR>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>DATE: November 18, 1996<BR>
			CONTACT: Communications<BR>
			PHONE #: (416) 979-6816</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Clarke Institute Program Helps Children with Learning
			Disabilities and Anxiety</B></P>
			
			<P>A new program at the Clarke Institute of Psychiatry,
			Children's Anxiety, Learning and Memory study (CALM), is
			studying the separate and combined effects of anxiety and
			learning disability in children. Childhood anxiety disorders
			and learning disabilities have separately been shown to
			place a child at increased risk for academic, work, social
			and emotional difficulties. This unique study, under the
			direction of psychologist, Dr. Arlene Young, examines the
			effect of anxiety on learning in both learning disabled and
			nondisabled children. 6-8% of all children have learning
			disabilities and they are often first identified in
			childhood.</P>
			
			<P>Parents, teachers and researchers have long noticed an
			association between learning disabilities and anxiety.
			Literature also shows that these children are at risk for
			becoming depressed. Yet, very little research has focused
			specifically on these combined difficulties. Are there
			factors predicting anxiety disorders among learning disabled
			children? What effect does anxiety have on a child's ability
			to learn? Staff at the Clarke Institute's Neuropsychiatry
			Clinic plan to answer these and other questions.</P>
			
			<P>According to Dr. Young, &quot;This study will help us
			understand how two areas of difficulty known to put children
			at increased risk for social or emotional difficulties
			interrelate. We know that worries and anxiety take up
			resources that are needed for learning and remembering new
			information in adults. Much less is known about children and
			very little is known about the effects of anxiety on
			children who are already struggling academically. As a
			result of repeated failure, children often develop school
			avoidance, poor self-esteem and a feeling of &quot;loss of
			control&quot; over events in their lives.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>Children suffering from anxiety and learning disabilities
			may also exhibit social withdrawal, be &quot;worriers&quot;,
			have difficulty dealing with change, or have somatic
			complaints (headaches, stomachaches etc.). Often the anxiety
			component is missed in children with poor language skills
			because they are quiet and tend to &quot;suffer in
			silence.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>The CALM program begins with a team assessment of the
			family by a psychiatrist, psychologist and social worker. It
			is important to get a clear picture of problems/issues and
			an understanding of the child's strengths and weaknesses as
			well as the situation they live in. The children then
			participate in psychological tests and a semistructured
			interview related to anxiety disorders. During this process,
			possible coexisting conditions such as, Attention Deficit
			Hyperactivity Disorder and oppositional behaviour are ruled
			identified.</P>
			
			<P>The Children's Anxiety, Learning and Memory study (CALM)
			is suitable for children 8-12 years old who have anxiety
			disorders, learning disorders or both. Children may be
			referred by parents, teachers, physicians or community
			workers.</P>
			
			<P>The assessment entails cognitive testing and academic
			testing as well as experimental tasks measuring memory,
			learning and attention. Children's interpretation of events
			and the strategies they use to cope with difficulties are
			also measured. Many children with LD and anxiety invert a
			normal view and attribute their success or failure at tasks
			to luck versus skill, thus contributing to poor
			self-esteem.</P>
			
			<P>After completing the assessment results are shared with
			the parents, and with their consent, the school. The program
			hopes to learn what these children do well and what they
			have difficulty with, and then develop a specific treatment
			program to fit this.</P>
			
			<P>Eventually, the team intends to run support groups for
			parents, providing information on learning disabilities and
			anxiety and how they work. This will help the parents change
			how they interact and communicate better with their
			children.</P>
			
			<P>Eighty children will be seen in the first year of the
			program; 20 with learning disability without anxiety, 20
			with anxiety disorders, 20 with both and a control group of
			20 &quot;normal&quot; children.</P>
			
			<P>Team members hope the results of this study will help
			Boards of Education reshape current programs, helping to
			identify and assist children with these difficulties earlier
			and more effectively.</P>
			
			<P>- 30 -</P>

						

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
					WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
