	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: Media Information: Media Releases: Helping Children Cope with Anger and Aggression</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/media_bkgd.gif" TEXT="#000000"
		  LINK="#FF9900" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Media Releases" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/media_releases_h.gif"></H1></TR>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>DATE: November 18, 1996<BR>
			CONTACT: Communications<BR>
			PHONE #: (416) 979-6816</I></P>

			<P><B>Helping Children Cope with Anger and
			Aggression</B></P>
			
			<P>A new group treatment program at The Clarke Institute of
			Psychiatry helps children aged 8-12 cope with anger and
			aggression. The 10 week program, developed by Dr. Meagan
			Smith, Psychologist and Isabel Granic, Research Assistant,
			aims to teach children how to manage and express anger in
			non-aggressive, socially acceptable ways.</P>
			
			<P>Groups will meet once a week for 10 weeks; a session
			began in September/October 1996, and another will begin in
			January and February, 1997. Children will be placed in
			either a Cognitive Behavioural or a Social Interaction
			group.</P>
			
			<P>The Cognitive Behavioural Group melds components of
			relaxation techniques, reattribution training, enhanced
			problem solving and social skills and a psychoeducational
			element aimed at demystifying violence and aggression in the
			media. The Social Interaction Group will enhance children's
			social and interpersonal skills such as cooperation and
			effective communication through recreational activities in a
			supervised, structured setting. These two approaches will be
			compared to identify the most effective means of decreasing
			the intensity and duration of anger in children and reduce
			the incidence of aggressive behaviour.</P>
			
			<P>Children with persistent, disruptive anger and aggression
			difficulties may fight, destroy property, throw temper
			tantrums, frequently argue and/or swear, behave cruelly,
			blame others for their mistakes and manipulate
			others.Without treatment, maladaptive behaviours will
			continue, and often lead to low self-esteem, poor school
			performance and interpersonal conflicts. Children may
			eventually turn to verbal and physical assaults on
			others.</P>
			
			<P>&quot;This program is unique because it specifically
			focuses on anger and aggression in children and tries to
			integrate a variety of components to help them. Clinicians
			and researchers have not had a lot of success - long-term
			effects - with this problem. We hope this program will help
			kids cope with and control their anger, to avoid
			difficulties later in life.&quot; Dr. Meagan Smith,
			Psychologist</P>
			
			<P>A treatment manual has been developed to allow other
			professionals to conduct the program offsite in the
			community, and staff intend to develop a parent component to
			add to the manual at a later stage. The Clarke program is
			staffed by trained group leaders and supervised students and
			volunteers from various disciplines including social work,
			psychology and occupational therapy. A new brochure
			describing the program is available from Isabel Granic at
			979-4747, ext. 2425.</P>
			
			<P>There is no cost for the program and children may be
			referred by family members, teachers, or mental health
			professionals. Children and their parents and teachers will
			be asked to complete questionnaires before and after the
			program, so that treatment effects can be evaluated. Six
			months after completion, children may attend a
			&quot;booster&quot; session, allowing them to review what
			they have learned and to share any difficulties they may be
			experiencing.</P>
			
			<P>- 30 -</P>
						

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
