	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: Media Information: Media Releases: Clarke Institute Community Nursing Program Offers In-Home Crisis Care</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/media_bkgd.gif" TEXT="#000000"
		  LINK="#FF9900" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Media Releases" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/media_releases_h.gif"></H1></TR>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>DATE:  October 15, 1996<BR>
			CONTACT:  Communications<BR>
			PHONE #: (416) 979-6816</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Clarke Institute Community Nursing Program Offers
			In-Home Crisis Care</B></P>
			
			<P>An innovative Community Nursing Program at The Clarke
			Institute provides psychiatric nursing for the acutely
			mentally ill, acting as an alternative to hospitalization
			and allowing people to remain in their home.</P>
			
			<P>Psychiatric nurses working in close consultation with
			physicians and other appropriate professionals, provide
			time-limited, in-home support to patients who are
			experiencing a short-term psychiatric crisis.  Eligible
			participants can be referred by any professional (nurse,
			social worker, doctor), must be under the care of a
			physician at The Clarke and must voluntarily agree to
			participate in the program.  The average period of support
			is 21 visits.</P>
			
			<P>Deborah, a client of the Community Nursing Program, has
			suffered with manic depressive illness for nearly 20 years. 
			Originally enrolled in University, she was unable to
			complete her studies, in part due to her illness. 
			Difficulty in diagnosing her illness prolonged impaired
			functioning with both work and family life.  Because of the
			nature of manic depression (it is cyclical), clients may be
			in the program more than once.  The first time Deborah
			received home visits was 14 months ago; this time it will be
			for nine visits.</P>
			
			<P>Visits occur on a flexible schedule, beginning with up to
			seven days a week and decreasing over time.  They can range
			from one and a half hours to a half-day in length, depending
			on the client's needs.  Janice Harris, a nurse with the
			program who visits Deborah, has six clients at present. 
			Some she sees twice a week, others daily.</P>
			
			<P>Janice assists Deborah with a variety of tasks during a
			visit ranging from medication issues, registering for
			university, talking about relationship problems, nutrition
			counseling or even shopping.  Deborah feels comfortable
			discussing both physical as well as emotional problems with
			Janice and Janice has also helped Deborah get into various
			community programs.  Deborah is now continuing her education
			at York University.</P>
			
			<P>Advantages of the program are that clients feel more
			comfortable at home, have a longer time commitment of
			follow-up and receive assistance with medication and other
			issues.  Deborah says, &quot;There is a real difference in
			care.  A more personal relationship offers support and
			consistency  and clients have more control.&quot;  Janice
			says, &quot;You develop a more holistic view of the whole
			person rather than focusing on the illness.  I am amazed at
			how much more I know about my clients -- how many strengths
			they have.  You pick up on things you see rather than solely
			relying on what they say.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>Because of the stigma surrounding mental illness,
			families find it easier to stay close and feel more
			comfortable with this program than visiting clients in
			hospital.  Most family members feel the program has a
			positive impact on their relatives and they are able to ask
			questions more readily.</P>
			
			<P>To date, results indicate positive clinical outcomes for
			many patients, reduced subsequent hospital stays, and high
			levels of consumer and nursing satisfaction.  Vice-President
			of Nursing, Nancy Johnston, says this initiative provides an
			expanded role for psychiatric nurses as highly-skilled
			professionals, and believes the program could well form the
			basis for a model for consumers and health care providers in
			the 90's.</P>
			
			<P>- 30 -</P>
						

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
