	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: Media Information: Media Releases: Clarke Bridging Psychiatry &amp; Alternative Medicine</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/media_bkgd.gif" TEXT="#000000"
		  LINK="#FF9900" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Media Releases" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/media_releases_h.gif"></H1></TR>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>CONTACT: Communications<BR>
			PHONE: (416) 979-6816<BR>
			DATE: 9 October 1996</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Clarke Bridging Psychiatry &amp; Alternative
			Medicine</B></P>
			
			<P>A two-day symposium beginning on November 1, 1996 -
			Psychiatry &amp; Alternative Medicine: Building Bridges -
			will explore alternative approaches ranging from Chinese
			herbs to Shamanism for treating acute and chronic mental
			illnesses. Sponsored jointly by The Clarke Institute of
			Psychiatry and the Department of Psychiatry at the
			University of Toronto, the goal of the symposium is to
			introduce alternative and complementary approaches to
			psychiatric illness to mainstream mental health
			professionals, and to promote collaboration and research
			between mental health practitioners and practitioners of
			alternative medicine.</P>
			
			<P>Attendees will be introduced to some of the basic
			principles of homeopathy, Chinese traditional medicine,
			Ayurvedic medicine, Shamanism, meditation, and spiritual
			methods. The symposium is open to health care professionals
			across the spectrum.</P>
			
			<P>Dr Jacques Bradwejn who is hosting the program, said the
			impetus for the symposium was twofold: to build bridges
			between alternative and orthodox modes of treatment, and to
			encourage medical practitioners to adopt a more holistic
			approach to the treatment of mental illness.</P>
			
			<P>&quot;We don't talk the same language. In the
			conventional medical model, we define illness by
			symptomology - we make diagnoses and design treatments to
			eliminate symptoms. Alternative approaches tend to be less
			categorical and far more global and preventative. They talk
			about health and illness in terms of balance and energy.
			Their treatment approach is to restore health and mental
			states within the context of a defined philosophical and
			spiritual system.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>Dr Bradwejn, who is Professor of Psychiatry at U of T and
			heads the Psychobiology and Clinical Trials Unit in Anxiety
			at The Clarke, believes that psychiatry, and medicine in
			general, has focused on the biological aspects of illness to
			the exclusion of &quot;the spirit and the even to some
			extent, the mind&quot;. He believes alternative medicine has
			much to offer; he advocates a more integrated approach.</P>
			
			<P>&quot;We need to evolve an integrated model of wellness
			in which people are healed by removing blocks to wellness.
			By definition, that must incorporate the spiritual as well
			as the physical.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>Earlier this year, Dr Bradwejn was instrumental in
			bringing Dr Yue-Ping Zhou, an expert in Chinese herbal
			remedies, to The Clarke to participate in a major group
			study of the biology of anxiety. Dr Zhou is investigating
			specific herbal remedies as possible alternative or
			complementary therapies for anxiety disorders. Dr Zhou was
			brought in after investigators observed that herbs used in
			Chinese, Indian, and Korean traditional medicine, were
			effective in treating symptoms of anxiety. Research suggests
			that the herbs act on the neurotransmitter cholecystokinin
			(CCK) - which plays a key role in panic and other anxiety
			disorders.</P>
			
			<P>For more information or to register contact Mary
			Catherine Moravac, phone: (416) 979-4747 ext 2643 or fax:
			(416) 979-4970.</P>
			
			<P><B>Keynote Speakers:</B></P>
			
			<P>Dr John Kabat-Zinn is founder and director of the Stress
			Reduction Clinic at the University of Massachusetts Medical
			Centre (UMMC), Associate Professor of Medicine in the
			Division of Preventive and Behavorial Medicine, and
			Executive Director of the newly established UMMC Centre for
			Mindfulness in Medicine, Health Care, and Society. His major
			research interests are in mind/body interactions for healing
			and in the clinical applications of mindfulness meditation
			for chronic pain and stress-related disorders.</P>
			
			<P>Dr Jerry Cott has a Ph.D in pharmacology and expertise in
			drug development - both in western and Ayurvedic herbal
			medicines. Dr Cott has spent six years in the pharmaceutical
			industry in the U.S. including four years as a reviewer of
			new drug applications to the Food and Drug Administration.
			Currently he is Chief of the Pharmacological Treatment
			Research Program for the National Institute of Mental
			Health. Dr Cott hopes to promote medicinal plant research
			among the mainstream scientific community. He believes that
			studying botanical remedies will both lead to useful
			treatments and increase understanding of the biology of
			mental disorders.</P>
			
			<P>Psychotherapist, Dr Kenneth Wapnick, has a Ph.D. in
			clinical psychology has been working with a Course in
			Miracles since 1973 - a self-initiated method of healing. He
			has written and lectured extensively on the Course as well
			as conducting a practice in psychotherapy. He is President
			and co-founder with his wife of the Foundation for A Course
			in Miracles, the teaching organization of the Foundation for
			Inner Peace. Dr Wapnick has travelled nationally and
			internationally giving workshops on the course.</P>
			
			<P>Dr Jacques Bradwejn, Head of the Psychobiology &amp;
			Clinical Trials Research Unit in Anxiety, has recently
			returned from a lecture tour of France where he spoke about
			the trend toward integrating research across disciplines and
			across all levels of analysis - an approach being
			spearheaded at The Clarke. He was invited to speak by the
			European Community organization, Erasmus, which trains young
			researchers. He gave presentations at Universities in Paris,
			Nantes, and Bordeaux.</P>
			
			<P>This integrated approach is currently being employed in a
			$1.6 million multi-site, group study of the biology of
			anxiety disorder, being led by Drs Franco Vaccarino,
			Bradwejn, and Sid Kennedy of The Clarke's Mood &amp; Anxiety
			Division. Worldwide, this is possibly the only group to
			methodically target the brain mechanisms and genetics of
			anxiety across all levels of analysis - from basic to
			clinical studies - across several levels of expertise -
			biochemical, pharmacological, technological, and clinical
			researchers from several disciplines.</P>
			
			<P>Dr Yue-Ping Zhou, an expert in Chinese herbal remedies,
			has joined The Clarke as a research fellow in a major group
			study of the biology of anxiety. Dr Zhou, (not to be
			confused with Dr Qun-Yong Zhou who is heading the new
			Transgenic research Facility), is investigating traditional
			herbal remedies as possible alternative or complementary
			therapies for anxiety disorders. He was hired after
			researchers in the project discovered that particular herbs
			used in Chinese, Indian, and Korean traditional medicine,
			were effective in treating symptoms of anxiety. Research
			suggests that the herbs act on the neurotransmitter
			cholecystokinin (CCK) which plays a key role in panic and
			other anxiety disorders. While at The Clarke, Dr Zhou will
			be working under the co-supervision of the Dr Franco
			Vaccarino and Dr Jacques Bradwejn.</P>
			
			<P>As an extension of this renewed interest in alternative
			medical approaches to mental illness, a two-day symposium
			and public forum on Psychiatry and Alternative Medicine is
			being planned for ..... this year. The purposes of the
			symposium are twofold: to introduce alternative and
			complementary approaches to psychiatric illness to mental
			health professionals and family physicians, and to establish
			working relationships with specialists in these areas as the
			basis for future research. In addition to alternative
			physical modes of treatment (herbs, acupuncture, massage),
			the symposium will address spiritual approaches including
			Buddhist and Christian-based spiritual/psychiatric
			systems.</P>
			
			<P>- 30 -</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
