	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: Media Information: Media Releases: Creativity &amp; Psychosis: Schizophrenia Art Exhibit Huge Success</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/media_bkgd.gif" TEXT="#000000"
		  LINK="#FF9900" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Media Releases" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/media_releases_h.gif"></H1></TR>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>Contact: Communications
			Phone: (416) 979-6816
			Date: 28 August 1996</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Creativity &amp; Psychosis: Schizophrenia Art Exhibit
			Huge Success</B></P>
			
			<P>&quot;Mental illness has made my life a desert, where art
			is a cooling respite from the intense sun which is
			death.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>Art as oasis; Alan Parker reflects on his art in the
			context of his twenty-year struggle with schizophrenia,
			manic depression, and thoughts of suicide.</P>
			
			<P>The funding, the forum, the support, the recognition, the
			chance to show that schizophrenia is a many-faceted
			phenomenon - these were the goals of the Clarke Institute of
			Psychiatry's Schizophrenia Art Exhibit on June 26. Fifteen
			clients of The Clarke's Schizophrenia Division showed their
			work - sculpture, painting, and drawing, ranging from mixed
			media to oil, abstract to figurative. Art Show organizer Dr.
			Mary Seeman, Head of the University of Toronto Schizophrenia
			Program, says:</P>
			
			<P>&quot;We had several goals in staging the art show. The
			first was to support these artists financially. The second
			to provide a forum for mounting and selling their work - The
			Clarke itself purchased a number of pieces. Thirdly, to help
			them achieve the public recognition they deserve. And
			finally - and very importantly - to make mental health
			professionals and the public aware that these clients are
			much more than 'just chronic patients'; they are highly
			creative. Many, many clients in the Schizophrenia Division
			are extremely talented, but had neither the money for art
			supplies nor the venue to show their work. We very
			specifically invited a large number of young doctors
			training in psychiatry so that they could see that this
			illness has many faces. Our hope is to encourage some to
			work in the schizophrenia area when they graduate.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>For many of the exhibitors, their illness has both
			informed and shaped their art. Michael's pencil drawings are
			uncompromisingly, almost eerily realistic. But in a future
			project he plans to draw on the delusions, obsessions,
			suspicions, and pervading sense of alienation that have
			dogged him throughout phases of his illness, and turned
			these dark themes into elements in an illustrated science
			fantasy. Now that Michael is able to step back from this
			thinking, he is able to reconstruct his delusions and
			experiences as a rich reservoir of ideas. Now his interest
			in the &quot;bizarre and the weird&quot; is in how it serves
			his art. &quot;It has turned into a form of reality
			testing,&quot; he says, allowing him to separate the real
			from the unreal.</P>
			
			<P>Miron Semec, who studied art in a program for
			artistically gifted children in his native Czechoslovakia,
			says his art has soothed him during crises in his illness,
			allowing him to distance himself from his disease and retain
			a broader outlook. He imbues his paintings - largely
			figurative works of landscapes and people - with the smells,
			colours, and sensations of a happy childhood. His goal: to
			make viewers of his work &quot;feel good, to free them of
			their burdens,&quot; and create for them, like himself,
			&quot;a sense of normalcy&quot;. Fulfilling his long-time
			hope to be both artist and teacher, today he teaches art to
			children in a community program.</P>
			
			<P>As part of the Exhibition, Dr. Vivian Rakoff, Professor
			Emeritus and former Clarke Psychiatrist -in- Chief ,
			presented a lecture on &quot;Creativity and Psychosis&quot;.
			Dr. Rakoff spoke on creativity as a means to connect with
			fellow human beings and psychosis as an illness that breaks
			down that connection.</P>
			
			<P>The pharmaceutical company, Hoescht Marion Roussel,
			donated funds for the lecture and costs associated with
			mounting the exhibition - framing, easels, transportation of
			art - costs that would normally have been insurmountable
			obstacles for these exhibitors. The exhibition was very
			enthusiastically received and generated nearly $1800 in
			sales with 100% of proceeds going directly to the artists.
			The hope is that the exhibition will be mounted annually and
			on a larger scale.</P>
			
			<P>Helena Hamilton pictured here with some of her works and
			with &quot;Creativity and Psychosis&quot; Lecturer Dr.
			Vivian Rakoff and organizer Dr. Mary Seeman, at the
			Schizophrenia Art Show held in June at the Clarke Institute
			of Psychiatry. Helena describes herself as &quot;a paranoid
			schizophrenic and manic depressive,&quot; who despite her
			crippling disease, &quot;is first and foremost a
			professional artist and poet. Art has kept me afloat. Art is
			easier for me than writing. When I paint the process is
			instinctive and unconscious. Whereas when I write I must
			decipher the complexities of my layered thoughts and
			emotions. I am forced to think through the meaning of each
			word, each line&quot;.</P>
			
			<P>Schizophrenia Art Show exhibitor Alan Parker shown here
			with some of his work and with Exhibition Coordinator Dr.
			Mary Seeman and Schizophrenia Division Head, Dr. Robert
			Zipursky. Alan studied at the Ontario College of Art and has
			mounted numerous exhibitions throughout the past 15 years.
			The paintings he showed were from a series of nine canvases
			of the same design and theme that he completed over a
			three-month period in 1995. He describes them as &quot;the
			great mystery of opposites. They are loosely inspired by a
			painting by Dennis Burton of 1967 titled
			Prismadame....During the painting of this series I was
			experiencing psychotic episodes, often states of exquisite
			euphoria.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>- 30 -</P>


		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
					WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
	</BODY>
