<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">

<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: Media Information: Media Releases: New Study Improves Treatment &amp; Saves Drug &amp; Hospital Costs</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/media_bkgd.gif" TEXT="#000000"
		  LINK="#FF9900" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Media Releases" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/media_releases_h.gif"></H1></TR>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>CONTACT: Communications<BR>
			PHONE: (416) 979-6816<BR>
			DATE: July 2, 1996</I></P>
			
			<P><B>New Study Improves Treatment &amp; Saves Drug &amp;
			Hospital Costs: Shows Schizophrenic Patients Do Better On
			Fraction Of Usual Dose</B></P>
			
			<P>&quot;The problem with many antipsychotic drugs, is that
			the side-effects can be so awful that patients become
			convinced the drug is the enemy, and stop taking it. When
			that happens they often lapse into psychosis and have to be
			hospitalized. Since these drugs are the best available
			treatment for schizophrenia, and the cost and side effects
			of these drugs are considerable, it is imperative that we
			find the lowest effective dose.&quot; Dr Shitij Kapur,
			Clarke Institute of Psychiatry Schizophrenia Division &amp;
			the University of Toronto Schizophrenia Program</P>
			
			<P>A team of Clarke Institute of Psychiatry researchers have
			found that patients with schizophrenia improve on far lower
			doses of antipsychotic medication than traditionally
			prescribed, and with far fewer of the debilitating side
			effects. Their finding could improve the life of individuals
			with schizophrenia and save millions in drug and hospital
			costs. On the basis of this work, Dr Kapur who led the
			research, encourages clinicians initiating treatment for
			schizophrenia to use low doses of typical antipsychotics -
			particularly for patients experiencing their first episode
			of psychosis. The findings have been published in the July
			issue of the American Journal of Psychiatry.</P>
			
			<P>Despite 30 years of using antipsychotics, there is still
			no consensus regarding the right dose. Until recently, the
			standard dose of the most-conventionally prescribed
			antipsychotic, haloperidol, was 20 milligrams per day.
			However, clinical experience with patients in The Clarke's
			First Episode Psychosis Program who could not tolerate
			standard doses, has shown that many patients improve with
			much lower doses of medication - some as low as 2
			milligrams. To develop a more objective approach to dosing,
			Dr Shitij Kapur (Deputy Head for Research, Schizophrenia
			Division, Clarke Institute; Fellow, U of T), Dr Robert
			Zipursky (Head, Schizophrenia Division, Clarke Institue;
			Associate Professor, U of T), Dr Gary Remington (Deputy
			Head, Postgraduate Education, Schizophrenia Division, Clarke
			Institute; Associate Professor, U of T), and Dr Philip
			Seeman (Professor, Pharmacology, U of T) have been
			conducting clinical trials in conjunction with positron
			emission tomography (PET) brain-imaging studies. The PET
			scans show the precise effect of the drug in different
			regions of the brain.</P>
			
			<P>Most scientists believe that psychosis in schizophrenia
			is caused by excessive activity of the chemical
			(neurotransmitter) dopamine which transmits messages between
			brain cells, and that antipsychotics
															....2 work
			by zeroing in on and binding with the tiny receptors which
			'stick out' from neurons and cling to dopamine molecules.
			The binding action of the drug blocks transmission between
			cells and results in controlling psychosis. Working with a
			group of patients from The Clarke First Episode Clinic, Dr
			Kapur has led PET studies to examine what is happening at
			the receptor level with low doses of medication. They found
			that doses of about 2 milligrams a day blocked an average of
			67% of the dopamine receptor; this is sufficient to produce
			good response in patients.					</P>
			
			<P>&quot;There is considerable variability in individual
			response to antipsychotics. That some patients may require
			higher doses does not mean that all patients should be
			started on high doses.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>Headed by Dr Robert Zipursky, the multidisciplinary team
			in the First Episode Psychosis Program provides rapid and
			comprehensive treatment to patients experiencing their first
			episode or first break of psychosis. Their approach is based
			on evidence that early intervention minimizes further
			deterioration and improves long-term prognosis.</P>
			
			<P>The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry is a research
			institute fully affiliated with the University of
			Toronto.</P>
			
			<P><B>Schizophrenia</B></P>
			
			<P>Schizophrenia, once thought to be a reaction to stress
			and family influences during childhood, is now recognized as
			a brain disease of unknown cause. Afflicting 1% of the
			general population - at least 250,000 Canadians,160 million
			worldwide - schizophrenia occurs at equal rates in males and
			females and cuts across all levels of education and
			intelligence, all cultures, all social classes. Described as
			'youth's greatest disabler', schizophrenia runs a chronic
			course. After the initial onset, usually in late
			adolescence, symptoms abate and reappear in cycles for many
			years. The first decade of illness is the most severe. Ten
			years after a first psychotic episode, 25% of patients will
			have have recovered completely; 25% will have improved
			moderately; 25% will have improved but still require
			significant ongoing medical, financial, occupational,
			social, residential, and psychological support; 15% will be
			hospitalized intermittently; 10% will have committed
			suicide.</P>
			
			<P>Current treatment for schizophrenia consists of
			antipsychotic medications supported by intensive
			psychosocial rehabilitation therapies. However, while
			existing medications control certain symptoms - albeit
			imperfectly - they can produce serious side effects ranging
			from involuntary muscle movements and spasms, to a number of
			hormonal, allergic, neurological, and psychological
			problems. Newer antipsychotic drugs are being actively
			tested and may hold the key for safer and more effective
			treatment. Cures are still years away.</P>
			
			<P>The costs are enormous. Schizophrenia accounts for 2.5%
			of total health care expenditures in any province - far more
			than any other serious illness. In Canada, people with
			chronic schizophrenia occupy 8% of all hospital beds - more
			beds than people suffering from cancer, heart disease,
			diabetes, and arthritis combined. It is estimated that
			schizophrenia costs Canadian society more than $4 billion
			per year - $2.3 billion in direct health care costs and $2
			billion in indirect costs such as welfare and support
			payments. The emotional cost to the individuals and their
			families is incalculable.</P>
			
			<P>-30-</P>


		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
