<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: Media Information: Media Releases: Serotonin-Dopamine Interaction Holds Key For Improved Treatment Of Schizophrenia</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/media_bkgd.gif" TEXT="#000000"
		  LINK="#FF9900" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Media Releases" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/media_releases_h.gif"></H1></TR>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><I>CONTACT: Communications<BR>
			PHONE: (416) 979-6816<BR>
			DATE: 29 March 1996</I></P>
			
			<P><B>Serotonin-Dopamine Interaction Holds Key For Improved
			Treatment Of Schizophrenia</B></P>
			
			<P>Combining typical antipsychotic drugs with serotonin
			treatment may provide more effective treatment for
			schizophrenia. This theory stems from research on the latest
			generation of neuroleptics - clozapine and risperidone -
			which act on both the serotonin and dopamine
			neurotransmitter systems. Clarke Institute of Psychiatry
			investigators, Dr Shitij Kapur and Dr Gary Remington,
			believe that the serotonin-dopamine interaction holds the
			key for treating a wider array of symptoms and reducing
			movement disorders* which are common side effects of typical
			neuroleptic treatment. Their findings - Serotonin-Dopamine
			Interaction and Its Relevance to Schizophrenia - were
			published as a special article in the April 1996 Issue of
			the American Journal of Psychiatry. This research builds on
			their own clinical and PET brain imaging research examining
			newer neuroleptics - their action, clinical outcome, and
			correlation with movement disorders.</P>
			
			<P>The therapeutic success of clozapine and risperidone has
			focused attention on the interaction between the serotonin
			and dopamine systems - both of which have long-been
			implicated in the cause of schizophrenia. Convincing
			evidence now suggests that the serotonin system inhibits
			dopaminergic function at two levels - the midbrain and
			forebrain - and that this inhibition may help in alleviating
			neuroleptic-induced side effects and treating negative
			symptoms**.</P>
			
			<P>Drs Kapur and Remington, both of the University of
			Toronto's Department of Psychiatry Schizophrenia Program
			based at The Clarke, theorize that these drugs achieve their
			effects by manipulating the serotonin system so as to reduce
			its inhibiting effect on the dopamine system. However, the
			researchers point out that the effects of the
			serotonin-dopamine interaction are different in different
			brain regions. They also caution that the benefits of the
			serotonin-dopamine interaction should only be expected
			within a narrow dose range and may be lost with higher
			dosage levels. 			</P>
			
			<P>Given the difficulty of producing the optimal
			serotonin-dopamine interaction in a one drug, Drs Kapur and
			Remington raise the possiblity of using serotonergic
			treatments as adjuncts to typical neuroleptics rather than a
			single drug with a combined action. Since all individuals
			respond differently, they suggest that controling
			serotonergic and dopaminergic function independently may
			allow physicians to determine the most beneficial levels for
			each individual. &quot;The crucial element is not the
			balance of serotonin and dopamine affinities of a given drug
			in a test tube, but the relevant levels it produces in a
			patient.&quot;</P>
			
			<P>The paper also points to ongoing research using PET
			brain-imaging technology to determine the right dosage for
			these medications</P>
			
			<P><B>Appendix</B></P>
			
			<P>* Movement disorders are side effects of antipsychotics
			and may be seen in up to 75% of patients. The occur as a
			result of the effects of antipsychotics on the dopamine
			system and cause patients to experience stiffness and
			tremors, much like Parkinson's disease; as a result,
			patients often stop taking their medication. It is believed
			that serontonin-dopamine interaction may alleviate movement
			disorders.</P>
			
			<P>** Negative symptoms in schizophrenia refer to a loss of
			normal function which includes restricted range and
			intensity of emotional expression, loss of fluency and
			productivity of thought and speech, and loss of motivation.
			Typical antipsychotics address positive symptoms -
			delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech, and grossly
			disorganized or catatonic behaviour - but have limited
			impact on negative symptoms. So despite being freed from
			their delusions and halluciations, many patients remain
			emotionally withdrawn, alienated, estranged, and therefore,
			unable to resume productive lives. It is hoped that
			treatments using the serotonin-dopamine interaction will
			have special effects on negative symptoms.</P>
			
			<P>- 30 -</P>



		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
					WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
	</BODY>
