	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About Medication: Reversible Monoamine Oxidase Inhibitor - Type A (RIMA)</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Reversible Monoamine Oxidase Inhibitor - Type A (RIMA)" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
			 SRC="../images/rima_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>This drug is used to treat symptoms of depression.
			Depression is a disorder which goes beyond feelings of
			sadness or unhappiness. The symptoms which go to make up
			this disorder include sleeping and eating difficulties, low
			sex drive, poor concentration, trouble with self esteem and
			a sense of hopelessness. The duration is usually more that
			one week.</P>
			
			<P>One of the treatment methods for depression is the use of
			medication called antidepressants. One group of
			antidepressants are the Reversible Monoamine Oxidase
			Inhibitor - Type A (RIMA) (e.g. Moclobemide). The
			antidepressants act by changing levels of certain chemicals
			in the brain. They are not &quot;uppers&quot; nor do they stimulate
			the individual. The drugs may take from a few days to
			several weeks to be really effective, so patience is needed
			to give the drug a chance to work. Early signs of
			improvement are increased appetite, better sleep and
			increased energy. Even though they may take a while to work
			there is a high likelihood of success. It is very important
			that the program is not discontinued, interrupted or changed
			in any way without consulting your doctor. Because of the
			risk of depression returning, it is necessary to continue
			the medication for six months to a year. If a patient
			continually relapses into depression, he/she may need to
			continue to take the medication in small maintenance doses
			for several years. If any change in medication or alteration
			in dose is required, this should be done at the discretion
			of your doctor.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Side Effects</B></P>

			<P>As with any other effective medication, unwanted side
			effects may develop. In most cases these lessen as therapy
			is continued. Occasionally the dose may be reduced by your
			doctor. Side effects may sometimes occur before beneficial
			effects are noticed. Although side effects are annoying, it
			is important that you do not stop your medication without
			first checking with your doctor. Side effects are an
			indication that they work.</P>
			
			<P>Take this drug after meals to minimize side-effects. If a
			meal is missed, the drug should still be taken, but large
			meal should not be eaten for at least 1 hour.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Mild side effects which should be reported to your doctor
			at the next appointment include:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dizziness -- Get up from a lying or sitting position slowly. Dangle your legs over the edge of the bed for a few minutes before getting up. Sit or lie down if dizziness occurs.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Insomnia -- As this drug can cause some stimulation, the last dose of the day should be taken no later than 5:00 p.m.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dry Mouth -- Sour candy, sugarless gum, etc., can help increase salivation. Drink water and brush your teeth regularly.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Constipation -- Increase bulk foods in diet (Bran, salads), exercise more often, drink plenty of fluids, or if necessary use a bulk laxative (e.g. Metamucil).</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Blurred vision -- Usually disappears in about 1 week. (Near vision only is affected). Reading under a bright light or at a distance, or wearing reading glasses may help. If the problem is severe, the doctor may prescribe eye drops.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sweating -- You may sweat more than usual; talcum powder may be helpful.</P>

			<P>The monoamine oxidase inhibitors are not habit-forming,
			but sudden stoppage may cause minor reactions such as
			headache, nausea, irritability or agitation.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Side effects which should be reported immediately to your
			doctor include:</B></P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Severe throbbing headache.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Persistent heartburn, nausea or vomiting.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Soreness of the mouth, gums or throat.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Skin rash or itching, swelling of the face.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Fever or flu-like symptoms.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dark coloured urine.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Difficulty urinating.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Excitability, agitation.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Switch in mood to an unusual state of happiness, irritability, or a marked disturbance in sleep.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Conditions which should be reported as soon as possible include:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Finding out you are pregnant.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Deciding you are going to nurse your baby.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Recurrence of depressive symptoms or fluctuation in mood or behavior.</P>

			<P>Treatment with RIMA (Moclobemide) does NOT require
			special diet restrictions as with other MAOI's. However, you
			should avoid eating excessive amounts of aged, overripe
			cheese or yeast extracts. If a Hypertensive Reaction should
			occur, the symptoms usually come on suddenly, so be alert
			for these signs:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Severe, throbbing headache which starts at the back of the head and radiates forward. Often the headache is accompanied by nausea and vomiting.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Neck stiffness.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Heart palpitations, fast heart beat.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sweating; cold, clammy skin.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dilated pupils.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Chest pain.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sudden unexplained nose bleeds.</P>

			<P>If a combination of these symptoms does occur, contact
			your doctor immediately; if you are unable to do so, go to
			the Emergency Department of your nearest hospital.</P>
			
			<P><B>Moclobemide should always be taken after meals to
			minimize any possible food-related responses</B> (e.g.
			headache).</P>
			
			<P>Other precautions to take:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>These drugs may interact with medication used by a dentist, so let him know the name of the drug you are taking.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Take no other drug without consulting your doctor, or pharmacist, including over-the-counter preparations such as cold or allergy tablets, or cough syrups.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>This drug may impair the mental and physical abilities required for driving a car or operating other machinery.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>If you miss your dose by more than 4 to 5 hours, skip the missed dose and continue with your next scheduled dose, as prescribed by the doctor. If you miss more than one dose contact your doctor for further instructions.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Store your medication in a clean, dry area at room temperature. Keep this and all medication out of the reach of children.</P>

			<P>If you have any questions, do not hesitate to contact
			your doctor, pharmacist or nurse.</P>

			<P>Prepared by the Pharmacy Department<BR>
			Clarke Institute of Psychiatry<BR>
			Form #281 (Oct '92)</P>
							
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
			WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
	</BODY>
