<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">

<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About Medication: Neuroleptics</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Neuroleptics" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
			 SRC="../images/neuroleptics_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>Neuroleptics are also called antipsychotics or major
			tranquilizers. This medication is used to treat symptoms of
			acute or chronic psychosis including schizophrenia, mania
			and organic disorders. Schizophrenia is believed to be
			caused by an overabundance of brain chemicals called
			dopamine, and Neuroleptics are thought to work by blocking
			the dopamine effect. A major part of effective therapy is
			the use of medication and the chance for recovery is
			good.</P>
			
			<P>The drug relieves anxiety in about 1 week, helps control
			mood changes in about 2 weeks, and difficulties in thinking
			and awareness in 6 to 8 weeks. As can be seen, patience is
			needed in order to give the drug a chance to work, and it is
			very important that the therapy program is not discontinued,
			interrupted, or changed in any way without consulting your
			doctor, since this may result in the recurrence of the basic
			disease symptoms and rehospitalizaton within 3 to 12 months.
			If any change in medication or alteration in dose is
			required, this should be done at the discretion of your
			doctor.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Side Effects</B></P>
		
			<P>As with any other effective medication, unwanted side
			effects may develop. In most cases, these respond to
			treatment or disappear as therapy is continued. Side effects
			may sometimes occur before beneficial effects are noticed.
			Although these side effects may be annoying, it is important
			that you do not stop your medication without checking first
			with your doctor, since this is an indication that the drug
			is being absorbed into the body and is beginning to
			work.</P>
			
			<P>MILD SIDE EFFECTS which should be reported to your doctor
			at the NEXT APPOINTMENT include:</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Drowsiness and lethargy -- This problem goes away with time. Avoid driving a car or operating machinery if drowsiness occurs. Alcohol, sedatives and antihistamines (cold &amp; hay fever medication) will worsen the problem.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dry Mouth -- Sour candy, sugarless gum, etc, can help increase salivation. Drink water and brush your teeth regularly.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Constipation -- Increase bulk foods in diet (bran, raw fruits and vegetables), exercise more often, drink more water, and if necessary, use a bulk laxative (Metamucil, Prodiem Plain).</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Blurred vision -- Usually disappears in about 1 week (Near vision only is affected). Reading under a bright light or at a distance, or wearing reading glasses may help. If the problem is severe, the doctor may prescribe eye drops or a tablet.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dizziness -- Get up from a lying or sitting position slowly. Dangle your legs over the edge of the bed for a few minutes before getting up. Sit or lie down if dizziness occurs.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Stuffy Nose -- A decognestant nose spray (e.g. Otrivin) may help.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Weight changes.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Breast tenderness.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>SIDE EFFECTS which should be reported IMMEDIATELY to your doctor include:</B></P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Muscle spasms, excessive rigidity, shaking or restlessness.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Nausea, vomiting, loss of appetite.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Severe constipation.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Soreness of the mouth, gums or throat.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Skin rash or itching.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Fever or Flu-like symptoms.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Yellow tinge in the eyes or to the skin.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dark coloured urine.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Difficulty urinating.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Unusual headache, persistent dizziness.</P>
		
			<P>These symptoms can be controlled with antiparkinsonian
			drugs (e.g. Cogentin, Artane, Kemadrin). They should only be
			used if needed in the dose prescribed by your doctor.</P>
			
			<P>TARDIVE DYSKINESIA is an adverse effect which has been
			recognized in some patients who have been treated with
			neuroleptics, usually for many years. This disorder
			describes potentially irreversible involuntary movements of
			certain muscles -- usually those of the lips and tongue, and
			sometimes those of the hands, neck and other parts of the
			body. Withdrawal of the neuroleptic at the first signs of
			tardive dyskinesia improves the chance that this adverse
			effect will abate with time. This has to be balanced against
			the risk of recurrent psychosis.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>CONDITIONS WHICH SHOULD be reported as soon as possible include:</B></P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Finding out you are pregnant. Menstrual irregularities may occur. These drugs can cause false positive pregnancy results. However, it is important that you tell your doctor if you have missed a period or think you are pregnant.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Recurrence of psychotic symptoms.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Elevated temperature not explained by current illness.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Other PRECAUTIONS to take:</B></P>
		
			<OL>
				<LI>This drug may impair the mental and physical abilities required for driving a car or operating other machinery.
				<LI>This drug may increase the effects of alcohol, making you more sleepy, dizzy and lightheaded.
				<LI>Antacids (e.g. Gelusil, Maalox, Amphogel, etc) interfere with absorption of these drugs and therefore may decrease their effect. To avoid this, if you are taking antacids, take the antacid at least 2 hours before or 1 hour after taking your other medication.
				<LI>Avoid exposure to extreme heat and humidity, since this drug may affect your body's ability to regulate temperature.
				<LI>Some patients may get a serious sunburn with little exposure to sunlight. Avoid direct sun, and use a sunscreen preparation (containing PABA -- e.g. Eclipse) on exposed areas.
				<LI>Check with your doctor before taking other drugs including over-the-counter medications such as cold remedies, etc.
			</OL>
			
			<P>If you have any questions, do not hesitate to contact either your doctor, nurse or pharmacist.</P>
			
			<P>Form #271
			July 1990</P>
																
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
