	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About Medication: Monoamine Oxidase Inhibitors</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Monoamine Oxidase Inhibitors" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
			 SRC="../images/monoamine_oxidase_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>This drug is used to treat symptoms of depression.
			Depression is a disorder which goes beyond feelings of
			sadness or unhappiness. The symptoms which go to make up
			this disorder include sleeping and eating difficulties, low
			sex drive, poor concentration, trouble with self-esteem and
			a sense of hopelessness. The duration is usually more than
			one week.</P>
			
			<P>One of the treatment methods for depression is the use of
			medication called antidepressants. One group of
			antidepressants are the Monoamine Oxidase Inhibitors (e.g.
			Nardil and Parnate). The antidepressants act by changing
			levels of certain chemicals in the brain. They are not
			&quot;uppers&quot; nor do they stimulate the individual. The
			drugs may take from a few days to several weeks to be really
			effective, so patience is needed to give the drug a chance
			to work. Early signs of improvement are increased appetite,
			better sleep and increased energy. Even though they may take
			a while to work there is a high likelihood of success. It is
			very important that the program is not discontinued,
			interrupted or changed in any way without consulting your
			doctor. Because of the risk of depression returning, it is
			necessary to continue the medication for six months to a
			year. If a patient continually relapses into depression, he
			may need to continue to take the medication in small
			maintenance doses for several years. If any change in
			medication or alteration in dose is required, this should be
			done at the discretion of your doctor.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Side Effects</B></P>
		
			<P>As with any other effective medication, unwanted side
			effects may develop. In most cases these lessen as therapy
			is continued. Occasionally the dose may be reduced by your
			doctor. Side effects may sometimes occur before beneficial
			effects are noticed. Although side effects are annoying, it
			is important that you do not stop your medication without
			first checking with your doctor. Side effects are an
			indication that the drug is being absorbed into the body and
			is beginning to work.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>MILD SIDE EFFECTS which should be reported to your
			doctor at the NEXT APPOINTMENT include:</B></P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dizziness -- Get up from a lying or sitting position slowly. Dangle your legs over the edge of the bed for a few minutes before getting up. Sit or lie down if dizziness occurs.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Insomnia -- As this drug can cause some stimulation, the last dose of the day should be taken no later than 3:00 p.m.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dry Mouth -- Sour candy, sugarless gum, etc., can help increase salivation. Drink water and brush your teeth regularly.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Constipation -- Increase bulk foods in diet (bran, salads), exercise more often, drink plenty of fluids, or if necessary use a bulk laxative (e.g. Metamucil).</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Blurred vision -- Usually disappears in about 1 week. (Near vision only is affected). Reading under a bright light or at a distance, or wearing reading glasses may help. If the problem is severe, the doctor may prescribe eye drops.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sweating -- You may sweat more than usual; talcum powder may be helpful.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Decreased appetite.</P>
		
			<P>The monoamine oxidase inhibitors are not addicting, but
			sudden stoppage may cause excitability, headache and
			possibly hallucinations.</P>
			
			<P>If you take the drug several times a day and forget to
			take a dose, take the missed dose when you remember (but no
			later than 3:00 p.m.), then continue with your regular
			schedule. If you miss more than one dose, contact your
			physician for further instructions.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>SIDE EFFECTS which should be reported IMMEDIATELY to
			your doctor include:</B></P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Excitability;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Severe throbbing headache;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Persistent heartburn, nausea or vomiting;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Soreness of the mouth, gums or throat;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Skin rash or itching, swelling of the face;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Fever or flu-like symptoms;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dark coloured urine;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Difficulty urinating.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>CONDITIONS which should be reported AS SOON AS
			POSSIBLE include:</B></P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Finding out you are pregnant.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Deciding you are going to nurse your baby.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Recurrence of depressive symptoms.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Precautions</B></P>
		
			<P>Certain foods and drugs contain chemicals which are
			degraded by the enzyme monoamine oxidase. Since this drug
			inhibits monoamine oxidase, these chemicals increase in the
			body and may raise the blood pressure and cause a severe
			reaction called a hypertensive crisis.</P>
			
			<P>Listed below are the foods and drugs which should be
			AVOIDED while taking this drug.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>FOODS -- DO NOT EAT:</B></P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>All matured or aged cheeses (Cheddar, Brick, Mozzarella, Parmesan, Blue, Gruyere, Stilton, Brie, Swiss, Camembert, etc.).</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Broad bean pods (e.g. Fava beans).</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Meat extract (&quot;Marmite&quot;, &quot;Bovril&quot;, &quot;Oxo&quot;), concentrated yeast extracts.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dried salted fish.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sauerkraut.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sausage (if aged; especially salami, mortadella).</P>
		
			<P>A TIME INTERVAL OF 14 DAYS SHOULD ELAPSE AFTER STOPPING A
			MAOI DRUG BEFORE SAFE RESUMPTION OF THE ABOVE FOODS.</P>
			
			<P>Reactions have been reported with:</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Pickled herring;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sour cream, yoghurt;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Soya sauce, meat tenderizers;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Caviar, snails, tinned fish;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Homemade red wine, beer, sherry;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Tea, coffee, cola;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Tinned and packet soup;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sausage: bologna, salami, pepperoni, summer sausage, or other unrefrigerated fermented meat;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Game meat which has been hung;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Chocolate;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Overripe fruit;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Oriental foods.</P>
		
			<P>It is safe to use cottage cheese, farmer's cheese,
			processed cheese, cheez whiz, havarti, boursin, liver (as
			long as is fresh), wine, spirits (in moderation).</P>
			
			<P>MAKE SURE ALL FOOD IS FRESH, STORED PROPERLY AND EATEN
			SOON AFTER BEING PURCHASED. Never touch food which is
			fermented or possibly &quot;off&quot;. Avoid restaurant
			sauces, gravy and soup</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>DRUGS -- DO NOT USE:</B></P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Cold preparations: decongestants, most antihistamines and cough medicines;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Narcotic pain killers (e.g. No. 222's);</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>All stimulants including &quot;Pep-pills&quot; (e.g. &quot;Wake-Ups&quot;);</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>All appetite suppressants;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Anti-asthma drugs;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Over-the-counter sleep aids (&quot;Sominex&quot;).</P>
		
			<P>It is SAFE to use:</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Plain A.S.A. (Aspirin);</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Acetaminophen (Tylenol, Campain, Atasol etc.);</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Antibiotics;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Antacids;</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Throat lozenges (Bradosol, Dequadin, etc.);</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Tranquilizers.</P>
		
			<P>If a HYPERTENSIVE REACTION should occur, the symptoms
			usually come on suddenly, so be alert for these signs:</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Severe, throbbing headache which starts at the back of the head and radiates forward. Often the headache is accompanied by nausea and vomiting.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Neck stiffness.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Heart palpitations, fast heart beat.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sweating; cold, clammy skin.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dilated pupils.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Chest pain.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sudden unexplained nose bleeds.</P>
		
			<P>If a combination of these symptoms does occur, contact
			your doctor IMMEDIATELY. If you are unable to do so, go to
			the Emergency Department of your nearest hospital.</P>
			
			<P>Other precautions to take:</P>
			
			<OL>
				<LI>These drugs may interact with medication used by a dentist, so let him know the name of the drug you are taking.
				<LI>Take no other drug without consulting your doctor.
				<LI>This drug may impair the mental and physical abilities required for driving a car or operating other machinery.
				<LI>This drug may increase the effects of alcohol, making you more sleepy, dizzy and lightheaded.
			</OL>
			
			<P>IF IN DOUBT ABOUT ANY FOOD OR DRUG TO AVOID, OR IF YOU
			HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, DO NOT HESITATE TO CONTACT YOUR DOCTOR,
			PHARMACIST OR NURSE.</P>
			
			<P>PLEASE READ PRECAUTIONS CAREFULLY!</P>
			
			<P>Form #275
			July 1990</P>
													
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
			WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
	</BODY>
