<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">

<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About Medication: Divalproex or Valproic Acid</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Divalproex or Valproic Acid" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
			 SRC="../images/divalproex_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>The medication you are taking is called Divalproex,
			Valproic acid or Valproate.</P>
			
			<P>Divalproex has traditionally been used to treat epilepsy.
			It has been found useful in the treatment of mood disorders,
			where a patient's mood changes from a depressed feeling to a
			high feeling, or vice versa. When taken regularly as
			prescribed, divalproex helps control these mood swings and
			may prevent further episodes. It has been found helpful in
			patients whose mood swings occur frequently, and in those
			patients who do not respond to lithium carbonate.</P>
			
			<P>The dose of divalproex depends on the amount of drug in
			the blood. Blood samples are taken regularly to check
			whether your dose is too high or too low.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Side Effects</B></P>
			
			<P>As with any other effective medication unwanted side
			effects may occur. Some side effects disappear with time;
			others can be easily managed. It is important to continue
			taking your medication unless otherwise advised by your
			doctor.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>COMMON SIDE EFFECTS which you should report to your
			doctor at the NEXT APPOINTMENT INCLUDE:</B></P>
			
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Stomach upset e.g. nausea, vomiting or mild cramps. This can be reduced by taking your medication with food or milk.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Tremor; mild shaking of the hands or arms.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Drowsiness or lethargy. Avoid activities requiring alertness, such as driving a car or operating machinery. Alcohol, cold medication and sedatives will worsen the problem.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Blurring of vision.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Mild hair loss.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Weight loss or gain.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Changes in your menstrual cycle.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>SIDE EFFECTS which you should report IMMEDIATELY to
			your doctor include:</B></P>
			
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Signs of bleeding, e.g. nose bleeds, easy bruising, pinkish-red urine, bleeding from the gums.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Severe weakness or tiredness.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Continuous nausea or vomiting, abdominal pain.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Yellowing of skin or eyes.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Darkening of urine.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Skin rashes.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Unusual eye movements.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Severe dizziness.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>CONDITIONS to report IMMEDIATELY to your doctor
			include:</B></P>
			
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Reappearance of mood changes.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Finding out you are pregnant.</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Deciding to nurse your baby.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Precautions</B></P>
			
			<P>Divalproex may interfere with other medication prescribed
			by a doctor or purchased from a Pharmacy. Inform all
			physicians that you are taking divalproex. Check with your
			pharmacist before purchasing any over-the-counter drugs.</P>
			
			<P>The following medication may interfere with
			divalproex:</P>
			
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Salicylates e.g. Aspirin, A.S.A. It is safe to use acetaminophen (e.g. Tylenol).</P>
			<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
				<TD><P>Antacids when taken together with divalproex (they can be taken 2 hours apart).</P>
			
			<P>If you miss a regular dose by three hours or less, take
			the dose when you remember it. If more than three hours have
			elapsed, skip the missed dose and resume your normal
			schedule. If you miss more than two doses, call your
			physician for instructions. Never double-up doses on your
			own.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Other Instructions</B></P>
			
			<OL>
				<LI>For the proper control of your condition, take your divalproex exactly as prescribed. On the day of your blood test take your morning dose after the blood draw.
				<LI>If you are taking the capsule form of divalproex, swallow it whole. Chewing the capsule may irritate your mouth.
				<LI>The liquid form of divalproex should not be mixed with carbonated beverages such as soda pop. This may cause an unpleasant taste or mouth irritation.
				<LI>To help your doctor monitor your progress, keep your regular check-ups. Report all changes in your behavior and any side effects you may have.
			</OL>
			
			<P>If you have any questions, do not hesitate to contact
			either your doctor, pharmacist or nurse.</P>
			
			<P>Form #279 Nov/91</P>
													
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
			WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
