Content-length: 11600
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">

<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About Medication: Cyclic Antidepressants</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Cyclic Antidepressants" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
			 SRC="../images/cyclic_antidepressants_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>This drug is used to treat symptoms of depression.
			Depression is a disorder which goes beyond feelings of
			sadness or unhappiness. The symptoms which go to make up
			this disorder include sleeping and eating difficulties, low
			sex drive, poor concentration, trouble with self esteem and
			a sense of hopelessness. The duration is usually more than
			one week.</P>
			
			<P>One of the treatment methods for depression is the use of
			medications called antidepressants. The antidepressants act
			by changing levels of certain chemicals in the brain. They
			are not "uppers" nor do they stimulate the individual. The
			drugs may take from a few days to four weeks to be really
			effective, so patience is needed to give the drug a chance
			to work. Early signs of improvement are increased appetite,
			better sleep and increased energy. Even though they take a
			while to work there is a high likelihood of success. It is
			very important that the therapy program is not discontinued,
			interrupted or changed in any way without consulting your
			doctor. Usually, it is necessary to continue the medication
			for six months to a year to be sure the depression will not
			return. If a patient continually relapses into depression,
			he/she may need to continue to take the medication in small
			maintenance doses for several years. If any change in
			medication or alteration in dose is required, this should be
			done at the discretion of your doctor.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Side Effects</B></P>

			<P>As with any other effective medication, unwanted side
			effects may develop. In most cases, these respond to
			treatment or disappear as therapy is continued. Occasionally
			the dose may be reduced by your doctor. Side effects may
			sometimes occur before beneficial effects are noticed.
			Although annoying, it is important that you do not stop your
			medication without checking first with your doctor, since
			this is an indication that the drug is being absorbed into
			the body and is beginning to work.</P>
			
			<P>Side effects are usually not serious or troublesome. They
			will respond to appropriate treatment, and will decrease or
			disappear with time.</P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B><P>MILD SIDE EFFECTS which should be reported to your doctor
			at the NEXT APPOINTMENT include:</B></P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Drowsiness and lethargy -- This problem goes away with time. Avoid driving a car or operating machinery if drowsiness occurs. Alcohol, sedatives, antihistamines (cold &amp; hay fever medication) will worsen the problem.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Energizing effect seen in some patients may aggravate nervousness, insomnia, and agitation. This should be reported to the physician and may be managed by taking the drug in the morning.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dry Mouth -- Sour candy, sugarless gum, etc, can help increase salivation. Drink water and brush your teeth regularly.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Constipation -- Increase bulk foods in diet (bran, salads), exercise more often, drink plenty of fluids, or if necessary use a bulk laxative (e.g. Metamucil).</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Blurred vision -- Usually disappears in about 1 week. (Near vision only is affected). Reading under a bright light or at a distance, or wearing reading glasses may help. If the problem is severe, the doctor may prescribe eye drops.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dizziness -- Get up from a lying or sitting position slowly. Dangle your legs over the edge of the bed for a few minutes before getting up. Sit or lie down if dizziness occurs.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Rapid heart rate -- This is not usually dangerous, but let your doctor know.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Nausea or heartburn -- If this happens take your medication with food.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Sweating -- You may sweat more than usual; talcum powder may be helpful.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Muscle tremor</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Nightmares -- may be managed by changing the dosing schedule.</P>

			<P>The cyclic antidepressants are not habit-forming, but
			sudden stoppage may cause muscle aches, chills, nausea,
			vomiting and dizziness.</P>
			
			<P>If you take your total daily dose at bedtime and you miss
			one dose do NOT take the missed dose the next day. If you
			take your total dose in the morning (fluoxetine) and you
			miss a dose by more than 4 to 5 hours skip the missed dose
			and continue with your next scheduled dose as ordered by
			your doctor. DO NOT DOUBLE THE DOSE. If you take the drug
			several times a day, take the missed dose when you remember,
			then continue with your regular schedule. If you miss more
			than one dose, contact your physician for further
			instructions.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>SIDE EFFECTS which should be reported IMMEDIATELY
			to your doctor include:</B></P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Soreness of the mouth, gums or throat</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Skin rash or itching, swelling of the face</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Fever or flu-like symptoms</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dark coloured urine</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Difficulty urinating</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Tingling in the hands and feet</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Persistent heartburn</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Switch in mood to an unusual state of happiness, irritability, or a marked disturbance in sleep</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>CONDITIONS which should be reported AS SOON AS
			POSSIBLE include:</B></P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Finding out you are pregnant</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Deciding you are going to nurse your baby</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
				ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Recurrence of depressive symptoms or fluctuation in mood</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Other PRECAUTIONS to take:</B></P>

			<OL>
				<LI>This drug may impair the mental and physical abilities required for driving a car or operating other machinery.
				<LI>This drug may increase the effects of alcohol, making you more sleepy, dizzy and lightheaded.
				<LI>Avoid exposure to extreme heat and humidity since this drug may affect your body's ability to regulate temperature.
				<LI>This drug may interact with medication purchased over-the-counter, or prescribed by a physician or dentist. Inform your dentist and physician about the drug you are taking. Consult with your pharmacist before buying over-the-counter medication.
				<LI>Report any changes in mood or behavior to your physician.
				<LI>Store your mediciation in a clean, dry area at room temperature. Keep this and all medication out of the reach of children.
			</OL>

			<P>If you have any questions, do not hesitate to contact
			either your doctor, nurse or pharmacist.</P>

			<P>Form #273 rev. Oct. 1992</P>
										
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
			WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
	</BODY>
