<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">

<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About Medication: Clozapine</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Clozapine" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
			 SRC="../images/clozapine_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>Clozapine belongs to the group of drugs called
			neuroleptics, (antipsychotics or major tranquilizers). This
			medication is used to treat symptoms of acute or chronic
			schizophrenia, in patients who have not had an adequate
			response to other neuroleptic drugs.</P>
			
			<P>The dose of clozapine is usually increased gradually over
			a number of weeks until a beneficial level is reached. It
			may take up to 8 weeks before you will notice a change in
			mood, awareness, or difficulties in thinking. Therefore
			patience is needed in order to give the drug a chance to
			work. It is important that the therapy program is not
			discontinued, interrupted or changed in any way without
			consulting your doctor, since this may result in recurrence
			of the basic disease symptoms. If any change in medication
			or alteration in dose is required this should be done at the
			discretion of your doctor.</P>
			
			<P>Prescriptions for clozapine are written for a week at a
			time and a blood test, to check the white blood count, is
			required every week. Your doctor can keep you informed as to
			the results of your tests. You will be asked to sign a form
			consenting to the terms of the treatment.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Side Effects</B></P>
		
			<P>As with any other effective medication, unwanted side
			effects may develop. In most cases, these respond to
			treatment or disappear as therapy is continued. Side effects
			may sometimes occur before beneficial effects are noticed;
			this is an indication that the drug is being absorbed into
			the body and is beginning to work. Although these side
			effects may be annoying, it is important that you do not
			stop your medication without checking first with your
			doctor.</P>
			
			<P>MILD SIDE EFFECTS which should be reported to your doctor
			at the NEXT APPOINTMENT include:</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Drowsiness and lethargy - This problem goes away with time. Avoid driving a car or operating machinery if drowsiness occurs. Alcohol, sedatives and antihistamines (cold &amp; hay fever medication) will worsen the problem.
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dry Mouth - Sour candy, sugarless gum, etc, can help increase salivation. Drink water and brush your teeth regularly.
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Drooling, especially at night-time
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Constipation - Increase bulk foods in diet (bran, raw fruits and vegetables), exercise more often, drink more water, and if necessary, use a bulk laxative (Metamucil, Prodiem Plain).
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dizziness - Get up from a lying or sitting position slowly. Dangle your legs over the edge of the bed for a few minutes before getting up. Sit or lie down if dizziness occurs.
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Weight changes.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>SIDE EFFECTS which should be reported IMMEDIATELY to
			your doctor include:</B></P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Soreness of the mouth, gums or throat;
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Fever;
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Flu-like symptoms such as lethargy, weakness, malaise or other signs of infection;
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Periods of blackouts or seizures;
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Severe or persistent dizziness or fainting;
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Skin rash or itching;
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Yellow tinge in the eyes or to the skin;
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Dark coloured urine;
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Unusual headaches;
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Muscle spasms, excessive rigidity, shaking or restlessness;
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Difficulty urinating.</P>
		
			<P>These symptoms can be controlled with medication
			prescribed by your doctor.</P>
			
			<P>TARDIVE DYSKINESIA is an adverse effect which has been
			recognized in some patients who have been treated with
			neuroleptics, usually for many years. The risk of this
			adverse effect with clozapine is considered to be low. This
			disorder describes potentially irreversible involuntary
			movements of certain muscles - usually those of the lips and
			tongue, and sometimes those of the hands, neck and other
			parts of the body.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>CONDITIONS which should be reported as soon as
			possible to your doctor include:</B></P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>If you have missed a period or think you are pregnant.
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Recurrence of psychotic symptoms.
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Elevated temperature.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Other PRECAUTIONS to take:</B></P>
		
			<OL>
				<LI>This drug may impair the mental and physical abilities required for driving a car or operating other machinery.
				<LI>This drug may increase the effects of alcohol, making you more sleepy, dizzy and lightheaded.
				<LI>Antacids (e.g. Gelusil, Maalox, Amphogel, etc) interfere with absorption of this drug and therefore may decrease its effect. To avoid this if you are taking antacids, take the antacid at least 2 hours before or 1 hour after taking your clozapine.
				<LI>Avoid exposure to extreme heat and humidity since this drug may affect your body's ability to regulate temperature.
				<LI>This drug may interact with other medication prescribed by your doctor or purchased at a drug store. Make sure you inform your physician of all drugs you are taking. Check with your doctor before taking over-the-counter medications, such as cold remedies, etc.
			</OL>
			
			<P>IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, DO NOT HESITATE TO CONTACT
			EITHER YOUR DOCTOR, NURSE OR PHARMACIST.</P>
			
			<P>Form #280 Nov/91</P>
																
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
			WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
