<DOCHDR>
http://cip.clarke-inst.on.ca:80/about_medication/anxiolytics.html 192.197.205.222 19970121060444 text/html 7518
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Tuesday, 21-Jan-97 06:01:16 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 06-Dec-96 21:45:55 GMT
Content-length: 7328
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">

<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About Medication: Anxiolytics</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Anxiolytics" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
			 SRC="../images/anxiolytics_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>This medication is used to treat symptoms of anxiety.
			Anxiety is a universal human response to stress and is
			necessary for effective functioning and coping with the
			daily activities of living. It may, however, be a symptom of
			many other disorders both medical and psychiatric. There are
			many different types of anxiety and there are many different
			approaches to treating anxiety.</P>
			
			<P>The anxiolytic agents used today are mainly in the Valium
			group and are also called minor tranquilizers. Examples are
			Valium, Librium, Tranxene, Serax, Ativan, Loftran and Xanax
			(called benzo-diazepines) as well as Buspar.</P>
			
			<P>An anxiolytic agent helps to calm the patient and relieve
			anxiety without causing excessive sedation or motor
			incoordination. However, in high doses these drugs can be
			used to induce sleep. Anxiolytics will alleviate the
			symptoms of anxiety but will not alter the cause of the
			anxiety. Anxiety is usually self-limiting and so it is
			treated with short-term drug use. Anxiolytics are usually
			prescribed for a limited period of time because the effect
			of the drugs can be lost (tolerance). Tolerance usually
			develops after four months of continuous treatment.
			Psychological dependence (craving, habituation) and/or
			physical dependence may occur, however, the risk of
			dependence with anxiolytics is considered low. Withdrawal
			symptoms are likely to occur between 1 and 10 days after
			treatment is stopped, usually after higher doses have been
			given for a long time.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Side Effects</B></P>

			<P>As with any other effective medication, unwanted side
			effects may develop. In most cases, these disappear as
			therapy is continued. Occasionally the dose may be reduced
			by your doctor.</P>
			
			<P>IN PRESCRIBED DOSES, ANXIOLYTIC DRUGS HAVE FEW SIDE
			EFFECTS.</P>
			
			<P>MILD SIDE EFFECTS which should be reported to your doctor
			at the NEXT APPOINTMENT include:</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Drowsiness and lethargy -- This problem goes away with time. Avoid driving a car or operating machinery if drowsiness occurs. Alcohol, sedatives, antihistamines (cold &amp; hay fever medication) will worsen the problem.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Blurred vision -- usually disappears in about 1 week. (near vision only is affected). Reading under a bright light or at a distance, or wearing reading glasses may help. If the problem is severe, the doctor may prescribe eye drops or a tablet.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Muscle incoordination, weakness, dizziness.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Slurred speech.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Upset stomach, nausea -- taking the medication with food or milk may help.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>ADVERSE EFFECTS which should be reported IMMEDIATELY include:</B></P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Periods of blackouts or amnesia.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Confusion or disorientation -- primarily in the elderly.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Development of unexplained skin rash.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Nervousness, excitement or any behavior changes.</P>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><IMG SRC="../images/bullet.gif"
			ALIGN=TOP WIDTH=5 HEIGHT=5 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2 ALT="*">
			<TD><P>Incoordination, causing falls.</P>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
			 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
		
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Other PRECAUTIONS to take:</B></P>

			<OL>
				<LI>This drug may impair the mental and physical abilities required for driving a car or operating other machinery or equipment.
				<LI>This drug may increase the effects of alcohol, making you more sleepy, dizzy or lightheaded.
				<LI>Check with your doctor or pharmacist before taking other drugs including over-the-counter medication such as cold remedies, codeine containing pain pills, etc.
				<LI>Do not stop taking the drug suddenly, especially if you are taking high doses. Any benzodiazepine anxiolytic that has been given continuously should be withdrawn gradually.
				<LI>Avoid excessive consumption of caffeinated beverages (i.e. more than 4 cups of coffee, or 6 cups of tea daily) as it may counteract the effects of anxiolytics.
				<LI>Advise the physician if you are planning to start a family, or find out you are pregnant.
			</OL>

			<P>If you have any questions, do not hesitate to contact
			either your doctor, nurse or pharmacist.</P>
			
			<P>Form #274 Feb/92</P>
																
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
			WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
	</BODY>
