http://cip.clarke-inst.on.ca:80/about_the_clarke/forensic_division.html 192.197.205.222 19970121060510 text/html 4643
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.12
Date: Tuesday, 21-Jan-97 06:01:43 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 28-Nov-96 17:14:26 GMT
Content-length: 4451
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">

<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About The Clarke: Forensic Division</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Forensic Division" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/forensic_division_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>The Forensic Division provides assessment and consultation
			for individuals referred by the courts, as well as treatment
			of patients involved with the law, either currently or in
			the past. However, treatment is not provided to individuals
			with outstanding charges. Our multi-disciplinary team
			includes nurses, occupational therapists, psychiatrists,
			psychologists, psychometrists, recreational therapists, and
			social workers, as well as researchers from a variety of
			disciplines. Services are provided at two sites, the
			Forensic Outpatient Service, located on the fourth floor of
			the Clarke Institute, and the Metropolitan Toronto Forensic
			Services (METFORS), located nearby on the grounds of the
			Queen Street Mental Health Centre, a regional psychiatric
			facility.</P>

			<P>The Forensic Outpatient Service deals with a variety of
			patients currently or previously involved with the law, but
			focuses on sex offenders through the
			<A HREF="../about_services/forensic_division.html#sexual_behaviour_clinic">Sexual Behaviour Clinic</A>,
			and physically aggressive individuals through the
			<A HREF="../about_services/forensic_division.html#anger_management_clinic">Anger Management Clinic</A>.
			Other services include the
			<A HREF="../about_services/forensic_division.html#phallometric_lab">Phallometric Laboratory</A>, the
			<A HREF="../about_services/forensic_division.html#gender_identity_clinic">Gender Identity Clinic</A>, the
			<A HREF="../about_services/forensic_division.html#police_liaison">Police Liaison and Investigative Support Program</A>, and the
			<A HREF="../about_services/forensic_division.html#law_and_mental_health">Law and Mental Health Program</A>.
			Many staff members work in more than one program or clinic.</P>

			<P>Division staff are involved in a wide variety of research
			and education activities, sponsoring conferences and
			lectures on forensic topics, receiving research grants or
			contracts from major funding agencies in Canada, and
			publishing work in professional journals and books. Some
			staff members are cross-appointed to the University of
			Toronto, and are involved in the supervision and teaching of
			students in nursing, occupational therapy, psychiatry,
			psychology, and social work.</P>

			<P><A NAME="metfors">METFORS</A> is a medium security
			facility consisting of an Inpatient Unit with 23 beds and a
			Brief Assessment Unit. Patients are remanded to the
			inpatient unit for a term of up to 30 days. METFORS responds
			to a variety of provisions within the Criminal Code of
			Canada relating to psychiatric assessment and consultation,
			including determination of fitness to stand trial and
			criminal responsibility. Referrals are made through the
			courts (mainly from Metropolitan Toronto, but sometimes from
			other parts of Ontario which may have few or no forensic
			services available to them). The Brief Assessment Unit
			operates three days a week. Although the majority of
			individuals seen in this unit are in custody, assessments
			may also be conducted for individuals who are not in
			custody.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
					WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
	</BODY>
</HTML>
