	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About Education: Practicums</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="About Education" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/about_education_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><IMG ALT="Practicums at The Clarke" SRC="../images/practicums.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>
					
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry was named after
			Dr. C. K. Clarke, a pioneer in Canadian psychiatry and the
			first professor of psychiatry at the University of Toronto. 
			It opened in 1966 and operates as a public hospital under
			the legislative auspices of the Ontario Mental Health
			Foundation. The Institute has its own board of trustees and
			is affiliated with the University of Toronto as a teaching
			hospital. It is an active treatment facility fully
			accredited by the Canadian Council on Health Facilities
			Accreditation and is a centre for education and research in
			the mental health field. Training opportunities in research
			and clinical practice are available at both the pre-doctoral
			and post-doctoral levels.</P>
			
			<P><B>The Department of Psychology</B></P>
			
			<P>The Psychology Department at The Clarke Institute offers
			educational activities in Canada's leading psychiatric
			research institute. The goals of the department in training
			students are to provide clinical and research training in a
			university-based medical centre. The department is
			dedicated to developing academic careers focused on basic
			and applied research in psychopathology. A wide variety of
			assessment and treatment modalities are employed with
			diverse populations of patients.</P>
			
			<P><B>Application Process</B></P>
			
			<P>Applications should include an up-to-date C.V., graduate
			transcripts, three letters of reference, and a statement of
			training goals and objectives. Please direct applications
			or inquiries to:</P>
			
			<P>Percy Wright, Ph.D., C. Psych.<BR>
			Chair, Education and Training Committee<BR>
			Department of Psychology<BR>
			Clarke Institute of Psychiatry<BR>
			250 College Street<BR>
			Toronto, Ontario M5T 1R8<BR>
			Contact: Alisa A. MacLeod<BR>
			Office (416) 979-4747, Ext.2553<BR>
			Facsimile (416) 979-4970</P>
			
			<P>The deadline for applications to be received is February
			15th.</P>			

			<P><B>Department of Psychology Supervisors</B></P>
			
			<P>Martin M. Antony, Ph.D.<BR>
			<I>State University of New York at Albany, 1994.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include the assessment and
			cognitive/behavioural treatment of anxiety disorders
			(including panic disorder, agoraphobia, obsessive-compulsive
			disorder, social phobia, and specific phobia). Primary
			research interests include the psychopathology and treatment
			of anxiety disorders, etiological models of fear and
			anxiety, interactions between biological and psychological
			variables in the psychopathology and effective treatment of
			anxiety.</P>
			
			<P>John Arrowood, Ph.D.<BR>
			<I>State University of New York at Binghamton, 1994.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include forensic assessment and the
			assessment of dangerousness and psychopathic personality.
			Additional clinical interests involve the assessment and
			cognitive/behavioral treatment of Posttraumatic Stress
			Disorder. Research interests include the study of
			impulsivity and information processing deficits in criminal
			populations and developmental antecedents of antisocial
			behaviour.</P>
			
			<P>Leslie Atkinson, Ph.D.<BR>
			<I>York University, 1986</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include personality and cognitive
			assessment of developmentally disabled psychiatric patients.
			 Research interests include assessment, psychometrics and
			attachment theory.</P>
			
			<P>R. Michael Bagby, Ph.D.<BR>
			<I>York University, 1985</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include objective personality assessment
			and psycholegal evaluations. Research interests include the
			personality and depression, psychosomatic medicine,
			personality test construction theory and structural equation
			modelling, assessing competency to stand trial.</P>
			
			<P>Howard Barbaree, Ph.D.<BR>
			<I>Queen's University, 1974</I><BR>
			Clinical and research interests include assessing risk or
			dangerousness in the sexual offender, deviant sexual
			arousal, and treatment program development and evaluation.</P>
			
			<P>Ray Blanchard, Ph.D.<BR>
			<I>University of Illinois, 1973</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include diagnosis and management of
			gender identity disorders, forensically significant erotic
			pathologies, and clinical interest in group psychotherapy
			with gender dysphoric patients. Research interests include
			taxonomy and clinical management of gender identity
			disorders and phallometric diagnosis of paedophilia and
			courtship disorders.</P>
			
			<P>Harvey Brooker, Ph.D.<BR>
			<I>Indiana University, 1962</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include personality and
			neuropsychological assessment, individual dynamically
			oriented psychotherapy, and rehabilitation and vocational
			psychology. Research interests are in the applied clinical
			area, including Ethics and Professional Issues.</P>
			
			<P>Stephen Butler, Ph.D.<BR>
			<I>University of Ottawa, 1987</I><BR>
			Research interests include: child development and
			psychopathology. Clinical interests: assessment and
			treatment of children and families.</P>
			
			<P>Cynthia E. Crawford, M.A.<BR>
			<I>University of Waterloo, 1990</I><BR>
			Current work is in study of outcome/naturalistic examination
			of relapse among depressed out-patients treated with
			short-term cognitive therapy.</P>
			
			<P>Gerald Devins, Ph.D.<BR>
			<I>McGill University, 1981</I><BR>
			Clinical interests: Behavior Therapy with a special focus
			on self-control and behavioral self-management as well as
			behavioral marital therapy. Research is in the area of
			Health Psychology, focusing on quality of life and the
			psychosocial impact of chronic life-threatening and
			disabling conditions (including end-stage renal disease,
			multiple sclerosis, rheumatoid arthritis, cancer, and sleep
			disorders).</P>
			
			<P>H. Bruce Ferguson, Ph.D.<BR>
			<I>Monash University, Melbourne Australia, 1970</I><BR>
			Clinical interests are in attention deficit disorder. 
			Research interests are in attention deficit disorder and
			development of antisocial behavior.</P>
			
