	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About Education: Internships</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="About Education" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/about_education_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=BOTTOM><TD>
			<TD><P><IMG ALT="Internships at The Clarke" SRC="../images/internships.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26></P>
			<TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=60>
					
		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Overview of the Program</B></P>
			
			<P>The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry was named after Dr. C.
			K. Clarke, a pioneer in Canadian psychiatry and the first
			professor of psychiatry at the University of Toronto. It
			opened in 1966 and operates as a public hospital under the
			legislative auspices of the Ontario Mental Health
			Foundation. The Institute has its own board of trustees and
			is affiliated with the University of Toronto as a teaching
			hospital. It is an active treatment facility fully
			accredited by the Canadian Council on Health Facilities
			Accreditation and is a centre for education and research in
			the mental health field.</P>
			
			<P>The Institute is responsible for conducting clinical
			research, offering clinical service, and teaching mental
			health workers and others. It is a training centre for all
			mental health disciplines. Interns have access to a wide
			variety of lectures, seminars, and symposia, provided by
			faculty from The Clarke, as well as frequent visiting
			lecturers from around the world. The internship is
			especially interested in applicants who are bound for
			academic careers in university psychology departments,
			teaching hospitals, and other academic settings. Interns may
			choose to participate in research during the internship
			year. The library is well stocked and computer and
			audio-visual resources are excellent.</P>

			<P>In contrast to other internship programs in which
			rotations occur sequentially, psychology Interns at The
			Clarke Institute of Psychiatry are assigned to two major
			rotations that occur concurrently throughout the year. In
			addition, interns may seek additional training opportunities
			through informal, minor rotations with other supervisors in
			the institute. Our aim is to help interns to build upon
			their existing strengths as well as to gain expertise in
			areas with which they have had little experience. Therefore,
			at least one of the primary rotations is typically in an
			area with which the intern has some familiarity and
			expertise. In addition to the major and minor rotations,
			interns participate in two separate weekly seminar series.
			Finally, interns receive approximately a half day to conduct
			independent research or other activities of the intern's
			choice.</P>
			
			<P>Three interns are accepted each year. Typically, interns
			are assigned to major rotations within the adult (two
			interns) or child (one intern) tracks, although occasionally
			an intern may do major rotations from both tracks.
			Regardless of which track an intern chooses, he or she may
			do minor rotations with supervisors from other areas. For
			example, an intern who is working on two major rotations in
			the child track, may choose to see one or two adult clients
			under the supervision of a third faculty member.</P>
			
			<P>The Internship runs from September 1 to August 31, with
			three weeks for  vacation, various statutory holidays, and
			time to attend conferences. Stipend (based on 1996-1997
			year): Approximately $30 000 (including benefits).</P>
			
			<P><B>Application Procedure</B></P>
			
			<P><I>Applications for an internship should include:</I></P>
			
			<OL>
				<LI>Completed application form
				<LI>Up-to-date CV
				<LI>Graduate transcripts
				<LI>Three letters of reference
				<LI>Statement of training goals and objectives
				<LI>Letter from the director of clinical training of the
					applicant's graduate school, indicating that he or she has
					completed all graduate courses and that their doctoral
					dissertation proposal has been approved. 
			</OL>
			
			<P><I>Please direct applications or inquiries to:</I></P>
			
			<P>Dr. Kenneth J. Zucker, Internship Co-ordinator<BR>
			Child and Family Studies Centre<BR>
			Clarke Institute of Psychiatry<BR>
			250 College Street<BR>
			Toronto, Ontario M5T 1R8<BR>
			Canada</P>
			
			<P>Office: (416) 979-4747, Ext. 2271<BR>
			Facsimile (416) 979-4668<BR>
			Email: <A HREF="ZuckerK@CS.Clarke-Inst.ON.CA">ZuckerK@CS.Clarke-Inst.ON.CA</A></P>
			
			<P><I>The Deadline for Applications to be Received is
			December 6, 1996.</I></P>
			
			<IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
			<P><B>Major Rotations: Adult Track</B><BR>
			<IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/rule.gif" WIDTH=334 HEIGHT=15></P>
			
			<P><B><I>Cognitive Behaviour Therapy: Depression</I></B></P>
			
			<P><I>Primary Supervisors:</I><BR>
			Zindel V. Segal, Ph.D.<BR>
			Mark A. Lau, Ph.D.</P>

			<P>This rotation is conducted in the Cognitive Behaviour
			Therapy (CBT) Unit of the Mood and Anxiety Division of The
			Clarke Institute. The CBT Unit is a clinical/research
			out-patient treatment clinic that offers specialized
			training in short-term cognitive therapy for depressive
			based disorders (patients are seen over 20-weeks).
			Assessment of suitability for cognitive therapy is conducted
			as part of an initial evaluation procedure. The goals of the
			CBT Unit involve the provision of highly refined and
			well-researched clinical services. Investigations are
			conducted to evaluate treatment methods and to investigate
			vulnerability to psychological disorders. Given the clinical
			research role of this unit, patients are often concurrently
			participating in research trials which have a focus on the
			investigation of relapse and recovery following treatment. A
			current orientation of this unit is towards the study of
			vulnerability to major depressive disorder and the
			identification of cognitive markers. This unit also serves
			an important academic and teaching function for continued
			training of psychiatric residents and other mental health
			professionals who are interested in learning about the
			cognitive model of emotional disorders.</P>
			
			<P>Training opportunities on the Cognitive Behaviour Therapy
			Unit involve developing familiarity with diagnosis of:</P>
			
			<OL>
				<LI>Axis I affective disorder;
				<LI>Cognitive assessment of these disorders;
				<LI>Familiarity with administration of a short-term cognitive therapy protocol; and
				<LI>The selection interview for determination of suitability for cognitive treatment.
			</OL>

			<P>In addition, an emphasis on case formulation using a
			cognitive model of emotional disorders is stressed.</P>
			
			<P>There is also an emphasis on understanding the
			interaction between pharmacotherapy and psychological
			treatment of the disorder, the role of interpersonal factors
			in depression, and considerations relevant to treatment
			format selection (i.e., short-term or long-term in nature).
			Opportunities for participation in research are also
			available, yet may be limited by the interns' caseload and
			demands related to clinical service.</P>

			<P><B><I>Cognitive Behaviour Therapy: Anxiety Disorders</I></B></P>
			
			<P><I>Primary Supervisor:</I><BR>
			Martin M. Antony, Ph.D.</P>
			
			<P>This rotation is conducted in the Anxiety Disorders
			Clinic (ADC), located in the Mood and Anxiety Division of
			The Clarke Institute. The ADC is a clinical and research
			unit headed by Dr. Richard Swinson and staffed by
			individuals from a wide range of disciplines including
			psychology, psychiatry, social work, and nursing. The clinic
			sees about 500 new referrals per year, many of whom are
			treated in cognitive-behavioural and pharmacological
			treatment programs. The principal disorders seen in the
			clinic include panic disorder, agoraphobia, social phobia,
			and obsessive compulsive disorder, although opportunities to
			work with individuals with other anxiety-related
			difficulties exist. Training of psychology interns includes
			opportunities to develop skills in clinical assessment,
			diagnostic interviewing, and cognitive-behavioural treatment
			(individual and group) of anxiety disorders. Although most
			clients seen are outpatients, inpatient experience may be
			available as well, especially with obsessive compulsive
			disorder. Also, interns are expected to become familiar with
			the relevant research literature.</P>
			
			<P>In addition to offering clinical services, the Anxiety
			Disorders Clinic is among the most active anxiety research
			centres in Canada. Research interests of clinic staff
			members include the development of short-term, cost
			effective assessments and treatments for anxiety as well as
			the role of cognitive-behavioural factors, biological
			factors, and their interaction in the etiology and treatment
			of anxiety disorders. Depending on the intern's interests
			and experience, opportunities to participate in clinical
			research projects or to develop new projects are available
			as time permits.</P>
			
			<P>Supervision includes weekly individual meetings as well
			as less frequent case conferences that include all clinic
			staff.</P>

			<P><B><I>Adult Forensic Outpatient Service</I></B></P>
			
			<P><I>Primary Supervisors:</I><BR>
			Howard Barbaree, Ph.D.<BR>
			John Arrowood, Ph.D.</P>
			
			<P>The Adult Forensic Service is a clinical and research
			outpatient unit staffed by individuals from all the major
			mental health disciplines, including four full-time
			psychologists and one full-time psychometrist. The Clarke
			Forensic Service was one of the first forensic centres
			established in the country and continues to be at the
			forefront of research and treatment innovations. The
			Forensic Service specializes in the assessment and treatment
			of individuals who have been involved with some aspect of
			the legal system. Specialized clinical activities in which
			interns may be involved include the assessment and
			prediction of dangerousness, psycholegal assessment for the
			courts (including the assessment of psychopathic personality
			and posttraumatic stress), and the provision of expert
			testimony. Interns will become familiar with the psycholegal
			standards involved in forensic assessment and reporting to
			lawyers and the courts. Interns will also have the
			opportunity to take on individual psychotherapy clients and
			to take part in the sex offender and/or anger management
			group treatment programs. Supervision is provided on an
			individual basis. Additionally, interns will have the
			opportunity to attend the Forensic Division seminar series.
			Possibilities also exist for participation in clinical
			research efforts as time permits.</P>
			
			<P><B><I>Clinical Sexology Programme (Phallometric Laboratory)</I></B></P>
			
			<P><I>Primary Supervisor:</I><BR>
			Ray Blanchard, Ph.D.</P>
			
			<P>Phallometric testing is a psychophysiological method for
			the assessment of erotic preferences in human males. In this
			procedure, a man's penile blood volume changes are monitored
			as he experiences a standard, prerecorded set of potentially
			erotic stimuli. The Clarke Phallometric Laboratory was
			established by Kurt Freund, MD, DSc., the first clinical
			sexologist to use penile plethysmography to assess erotic
			preferences in men. It is the oldest laboratory in North
			America for the phallometric assessment of sex offenders and
			paraphilics, and its instrumentation for the collection and
			processing of phallometric data is still the most
			sophisticated in North America, or indeed, in the world.</P>
			
			<P>Most men referred to the Laboratory have been charged
			with, or convicted of, sexual interaction with minors or
			sexual coercion of adult women; the differential diagnosis
			usually involves a determination of paraphilia versus sexual
			misconduct motivated by some other factor. The central goal
			of this internship position is to train the intern to
			administer phallometric tests and to interpret their output.
			Because phallometric testing is highly technical and
			involves the mastery of complex instrumentation, we will
			only consider applicants who will spend half of each work
			week in the Phallometric Laboratory for the entire year of
			their internship. The highly accurate but elaborate
			equipment used in The Clarke Laboratory often requires the
			examiner to supervise the subject while he places the penile
			transducer on his genital or to verify the placement of the
			apparatus in locating he source of equipment problems. For
			this reason, only males can be hired to work in the
			Phallometric Laboratory (Ontario Human Rights Commission
			Exemption File #257).</P>
			
			<P><B><I>Metropolitan Forensic Service (METFORS)</I></B></P>
			
			<P><I>Primary Supervisors:</I><BR>
			David Nussbaum, Ph.D.<BR>
			Percy Wright, Ph.D.</P>
			
			<P>Metropolitan Forensic Service (METFORS) is one of two
			services in the Division of Forensic Psychiatry. METFORS
			provides assessments and consultations to the courts on
			far-ranging pre-trial and pre-sentence issues. In addition,
			the service maintains an important academic role in research
			and the advanced training of psychiatrists and
			psychologists.</P>
			
			<P>The primary training offered at METFORS in the assessment
			of complex clinical and psycholegal cases. Many patients
			have co-occurring Axis I and Axis II disorders, many of
			which are superimposed on substance abuse disorders. These
			patients provide a rich opportunity for diagnostic and
			personality assessments. In addition, interns become
			conversant in the application of psycholegal standards to
			in-patients referred by the courts. Interns must become
			knowledgeable regarding the literature on competency to
			stand trial, insanity, dangerous offender and
			treatability.</P>

			<P><B><I>General Adult Clinical Psychology</I></B></P>
			
			<P><I>Primary Supervisors:</I><BR>
			To be announced<BR>
			Laurie Gillies, Ph.D.</P>
			
			<P>The General Adult Clinical Psychology Rotation includes
			opportunities to see outpatients in the Assessment Clinic,
			Interpersonal Therapy Clinic, Mood Disorders Program and
			Clinic, Psychotherapy Centre, Vocational Services, and
			Emergency Services. In addition, inpatient experience is
			available in the General Psychiatry Division and the
			Schizophrenia Research Program. Interns may be linked to one
			or more of these programs during this rotation.</P>
			
			<P>Experience is gained in both assessment and intervention.
			The specific nature or focus of the assessment training
			varies, dependent on the particular program. Patients are
			referred directly to the Psychology Department for
			psychotherapy so interns can receive training in supportive
			psychotherapy, case management procedures with chronic
			psychiatric disorders, psychodynamically-oriented
			psychotherapy, and interpersonal psychotherapy. Supervision
			of therapy is primarily on an individual basis via
			audiotapes of psychotherapy sessions. Long term cases may be
			carried through the year. Training in group therapy is also
			available.</P>
			
			<P>Assessment training is offered in psychodiagnostic work
			and includes instruction in such tests as the Rorschach,
			TAT, MMPI, MMPI-2, MCMI,-II, and WAIS-R. We also provide
			training in neuropsychological assessment using such tests
			as the Wechsler Memory, Bender-Gestalt, Benton
			Visual-Retention, the Halsted-Reitan battery, and the Luria
			Method. Training is available, as well, in specialized areas
			such as vocational aptitude and interest tests, and
			assessment via self-report measures for suitability for
			cognitive therapy. Interns may also receive training in
			diagnostic interviewing, history taking, and emergency
			evaluation. It is the intention of the training program
			committee that the intern function as much as possible as a
			staff member in a multi-disciplinary context. Interns are
			expected to attend and participate in appropriate unit
			meetings, rounds, and the like.</P>

			<IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>
			<P><B>Major Rotations: Child Track</B><BR>
			<IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/rule.gif" WIDTH=334 HEIGHT=15></P>
			
			<P><B><I>Child and Family Studies Centre</I></B></P>

			<P><I>Primary Supervisors:</I><BR>
			Lynn Oldershaw, Ph.D.<BR>
			Meagan Smith, Ph.D.<BR>
			Arlene Young, Ph.D.<BR>
			Ken Zucker, Ph.D.</P>
			
			<P>Psychology staff in the Child and Family Studies Centre
			currently includes 4 full-time psychologists, and 1
			part-time psychometrist.</P>
			
			<P>Interns will receive training in assessment, diagnosis,
			psychological testing, and therapeutic interventions.
			Interns can gain experience in a broad range of child
			psychopathologies, including the internalizing and
			externalizing disorders, learning and neuropsychological
			disabilities, affective disorders, pervasive developmental
			disorders, and gender identity disorders. Interns can also
			gain experience working with children from "at risk"
			backgrounds, including parents with affective disorder.
			Out-patient and day treatment settings constitute the core
			of the Department.</P>
			
			<P>Supervision is on an individual basis. There are also
			bi-weekly psychology meetings that are didactic in nature.
			The service itself also provides a range of educational
			opportunities.</P>

			<P><B><I>Family Court Clinic</I></B></P>
			
			<P><I>Primary Supervisors:</I><BR>
			Stephen Butler, Ph.D.<BR>
			Helen Radovanovic, Ph.D.</P>
			
			<P>The Family Court Clinic conducts clinical assessments of
			families and youth before the courts in the Toronto area.
			There are currently three specialized programs: 1) the
			Family Program, which deals with custody/visitation, and
			child welfare matters; 2) the Young Offender Program; 3) and
			the Arson Prevention Program for children. These assessments
			incorporate both clinical interviews and psychometric
			testing within the context of a multidisciplinary team
			model. In addition, the Family Court Clinic also provides
			individual and family treatment.</P>
			
			<P>The family program provides comprehensive assessment of
			parents and children involved in custody and visitation
			disputes. These families are characterized by high incidence
			of parental psychopathology, parental substance abuse,
			interparental aggression, and children's behavioural and
			emotional disturbance. The assessment focus on an evaluation
			of the child's needs, parenting ability, parent-child
			relationships, and the interparental relationship.
			Unstructured and structured clinical interviews,
			parent-child observations, and psychometric testing are
			typically used for the assessment. Therapeutic resolution of
			the parental disputes or mediation is provided, where
			applicable.</P>
			
			<P>The Adolescent Team primarily conducts court ordered
			assessments under the Young Offenders Act. Referrals are
			also accepted from community agencies such as probation,
			Children's Aid Societies and schools. The clinical issues
			involved in these assessments include the risk for
			recidivism and continued antisocial behaviour, the
			adolescent's general emotional and behavioural functioning,
			family functioning and the adolescent's and families ability
			to benefit from therapeutic intervention. The assessments
			are comprehensive and include individual and family
			interviews, psychological testing and/or psychiatric
			consultation where appropriate, and review of report from
			community agencies. The goal of the assessment is to assist
			the judge in making a disposition on the youth by providing
			a comprehensive understanding of the youth's clinical needs
			and making specific treatment recommendations. In addition,
			individual and family therapy for adolescents and their
			families are also part of the Adolescent Team.</P>
			
			<P>The Family Court Clinic has recently initiated The Arson
			Prevention Program for Children (TAPP-C). The program is
			designed to develop and test an assessment and intervention
			program for juvenile fire setters that will be implemented
			later on a province wide basis. Juvenile fire setters (ages
			2-16 years) and their families are assessed at the clinic.
			Structured interviews are used to examine the duration,
			breadth, and intensity of the child's fire setting
			behaviours and history. Standardized observations,
			interviews, and questionnaires are used to evaluate child
			and family psychopathology. An estimate of the child's risk
			for future fire setting is derived. Children are channelled
			into fire safety and education programs or mental-health
			treatment programs, as appropriate to their needs.</P>
			
			<P><B>Educational Seminars</B></P>
			
			<P>In addition to direct clinical experience, the internship
			requires the intern participate in a number of didactic
			educational experiences including the Clinical Seminar
			Series and the Continuing Case Conference. In addition,
			interns are encouraged to take advantage of other
			professional development activities including lectures,
			workshops, seminars and professional conferences, both
			within and outside the Institute.</P>
			
			<P><B>Clinical Seminar Series</B></P>
			
			<P>Seminars are provided every week by psychology staff at
			The Clarke Institute. Lectures are typically held at the
			site where each psychologist provides his or her direct
			treatment or assessment functions, so that interns can gain
			familiarity with the various practising sub-sections of The
			Clarke Institute's Department of Psychology even if they are
			not in contact during their ordinary rotations. The seminars
			are structured to provide information relevant to assessment
			and treatment issues as well as to enhance the professional
			functioning of interns vis a vis the independent practice of
			psychology.</P>
			
			<P>Topics in this year's seminar series include finding a
			job in clinical psychology, assessment of young offenders,
			determination of child custody and access, cognitive therapy
			of depression, ethics for psychologists, anxiety disorders,
			assessment using the MMPI, and Rorschach, risk factors for
			mental illness in children, gender identity disturbances in
			children, hyperactivity and attention deficit disorder,
			cultural issues in assessment, child neuropsychology, sexual
			aggression, assessment of sexual arousal through
			phallometric diagnosis, the therapeutic alliance in
			psychotherapy, self-abusive psychiatric patients,
			personality disorders and cognitive behavioural treatment
			for irritable bowel syndrome.</P>
			
			<P><B>Continuing Case Conference</B></P>
			
			<P>This conference provides an opportunity for interns to
			consolidate their psychotherapy skills and to interact with
			members of the Department of Psychology in a mutually
			trusting environment. Three psychology staff members meet on
			a weekly basis with the three interns. They play audiotapes
			of psychotherapy sessions, and listen to tapes of either the
			interns or the psychologists with the goal being to examine
			specific clinical phenomena related to the practice of
			psychotherapy. This case conference serves as a continuing
			forum for the discussion and exploration of personal issues
			relevant to psychotherapy process and outcome as well as
			serving to model for the interns a variety of approaches to
			conceptualization and amelioration of emotional disorders.
			The psychology staff members participating in the case
			conference represent divergent perspectives and provide an
			important atmosphere relevant to disclosure and honest
			discussion of obstacles and successes in therapy.</P>
			
			<P><B>Psychology Internship Faculty</B></P>
			
			<P>Martin M. Antony, PhD<BR>
			<I>State University of New York at Albany, 1994.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include the assessment and
			cognitive/behavioural treatment of anxiety disorders
			(including panic disorder, agoraphobia, obsessive-compulsive
			disorder, social phobia, and specific phobia). Primary
			research interests include the psychopathology and treatment
			of anxiety disorders, etiological models of fear and
			anxiety, interactions between biological and psychological
			variables in the psychopathology and effective treatment of
			anxiety.</P>
			
			<P><B>Psychology Department Staff</B></P>
			
			<P>Martin M. Antony, PhD<BR>
			<I>State University of New York at Albany, 1994</I></P>
			
