</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//Netscape Comm. Corp.//DTD HTML//EN">

<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About The Clarke's Services: Research Division</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FF9900" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#FFFFFF" ALINK="#FF9900" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Research Division" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/research_division_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>The Clarke is unique in that the entire facility is focused
			on research, with an emphasis on the major psychiatric
			disorders.</P>
			
			<P>To inquire about research projects, or participate as
			research subjects, contact the Office of the Director of
			Research, at 979-4675 or 6940.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="behavioural_sexology">Behavioural Sexology Section</A></B><BR>
			
			The Behavioural Sexology Section is a world pioneer in the
			development of specific methods of phallometry as a reliable
			diagnostic tool in the assessment of sex offenders and
			paraphiliacs.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="biopsychology_section">Biopsychology Section</A></B><BR>
			
			The Biopsychology Section studies brain neurochemical
			systems affecting overeating; how brain systems which use
			serotonin contribute to impulsive behaviours; and the role
			of dietary unsaturated fats in behaviour.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="biochemical_psychiatry">Biochemical Psychiatry Section</A></B><BR>
			
			The Biochemical Psychiatry Section investigates biochemical
			abnormalities underlying psychiatric disorders, with a
			special interest in mood disorders.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="culture_community_health">Culture, Community
							and Health Studies Section</A></B><BR>
			
			The Culture, Community and Health Studies Section studies
			include mental health of immigrants and refugees; a 6-year
			study among First Nations children in Canada and the USA;
			cultural influences on expression of mental illness; and
			developing health care models in collaboration with the
			appropriate communities.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="psychiatric_neurogenetics">Psychiatric Neurogenetics</A></B><BR>
			
			Psychiatric Neurogenetics has developed a new method for
			detecting markers for genes that function in the brain.
			Studies showing that DNA markers at the dopamine D4 level
			predict to a significant degree which persons with
			schizophrenia will respond to clozapine versus those who
			will not. Ongoing genetic scans for schizophrenia genes have
			covered several chromosomes. In manic-depression, the
			Section has found significant prediction of lithium response
			based on DNA variations in the TH gene.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="human_neurochemical_pathology">Human Neurochemical Pathology</A></B><BR>
			
			Human Neurochemical Pathology is currently focusing on
			studies designed to understand the causes of schizophrenia
			and drug addiction, through biochemical examination of
			autopsied brains of patients who have died with these
			conditions.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="neuroendocrinology_section">Neuroendocrinology Section</A></B><BR>
			
			Neuroendocrinology Section is studying the pineal hormone
			melatonin, which is a key factor in regulating body rhythms,
			rhythms which are disrupted in patients with anxiety and
			mood disorders.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="molecular_psychobiology">Molecular Psychobiology</A></B><BR>
			
			Molecular Psychobiology is searching for biochemical
			abnormalities that may determine the hyper- or hypo-
			dopaminergic components to disorders such as schizophrenia
			and drug dependence. The work of members of this Section and
			colleagues in the Department of Psychiatry at the University
			of Toronto is highly regarded world-wide as having led to
			the illumination, at the molecular level, of the receptor
			basis for therapy of schizophrenia and Parkinson's disease.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="neuroepidemiology_section">Neuroepidemiology Section</A></B><BR>
			
			Neuroepidemiology Section is a leader in the Canadian Study
			of Health and Aging, drug trials in geriatric depression,
			post stroke depression and Alzheimer's Disease, and
			coordination of dementia drug trials in Canada.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="womens_mental_health">Women's Mental Health
						Research Program</A></B><BR>
			
			Women's Mental Health Research Program is studying the
			origin, expression, diagnosis, prevention and clinical
			outcome of mental health problems in women; training models
			to sensitize professionals to women's issues; women and
			gastro-intestinal disorders; gender role conflict; and
			mental health and ethnicity.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="neuroimaging_section">Neuroimaging Section</A></B><BR>
			
			Neuroimaging Section is identifying specific brain areas,
			pathways and chemical mechanisms involved in
			neuropsychiatric disorders. Specific projects are examining
			the brain effects of electroconvulsive therapy, thyroid
			hormone treatment and REM sleep deprivation. Another area of
			investigation involves brain dopamine receptors function as
			well as brain mechanisms of compulsive drug-taking.</P>
			
			
			<P><B><A NAME="pet_section">Positron Emission Tomography Section</A></B><BR>
			
			The Positron Emission Tomography Section operates the only
			PET Centre in Canada totally devoted to brain research.
			Current research projects include neurocognitive activation
			studies applied to disease such as schizophrenia;
			pharmacological challenges to assess the effects of
			medication on brain circuits; and neuroreceptor studies to
			examine drugs used to treat schizophrenia, depression,
			Parkinson's and Huntington's diseases.</P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_yl.gif"
					WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
	</BODY>
</HTML>
