	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About Education: Psychology Internship Faculty</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="About Education" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/about_education_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					 <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P><B>Psychology Internship Faculty</B><BR>
			<IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/rule.gif" WIDTH=334 HEIGHT=15></P>
			
			<P><B>Martin M. Antony, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>State University of New York at Albany, 1994.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include the assessment and cognitive/behavioural treatment of anxiety disorders (including panic disorder, agoraphobia, obsessive-compulsive disorder, social phobia, and specific phobia). Primary research interests include the psychopathology and treatment of anxiety disorders, etiological models of fear and anxiety, interactions between biological and psychological variables in the psychopathology and effective treatment of anxiety.</P>
			
			<P>Antony, M.M., & Barlow, D.H. (1996).<BR>
			Information processing and emotion theory views of panic disorder: Overlapping and distinct features. In R.M. Rapee (Ed.), Current controversies in the anxiety disorders. New York: Guilford Press.</P>
			
			<P>Antony, M.M., Brown, T.A., Craske, M.G., Barlow, D.H., Mitchell, W.B., & Meadows, E.A. (1995).<BR>
			Accuracy of heart beat estimation in panic disorder, social phobic and non-anxious controls. Journal of Anxiety Disorders, 9, 355-371.</P>
			
			<P>Antony, M.M., Craske, M.G., & Barlow, D.H. (1995).<BR>
			Mastery of your specific phobia. Albany, NY: Graywind Publications.</P>
			
			<P>Brown, T.A., Antony, M.M., & Barlow, D.H. (1995).<BR>
			Diagnostic comorbidity in panic disorder: Effect on treatment outcome and course of comorbid diagnoses following treatment. Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology, 63, 408-418.</P>
			
			<P><B>John S. Arrowood, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>State University of New York at Binghamton, 1994.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include forensic assessment and the assessment of dangerousness and psychopathic personality. Additional clinical interests involve the assessment and cognitive/behavioral treatment of Posttraumatic stress Disorder. Research interests include the prediction of dangerousness in adolescent offenders and developmental antecedents of antisocial behavior.</P>
			
			<P>Arrowood, J. S., Monroe, J. F., and Pratt, A. C. (November 1996).<BR>
			Prevention of secondary posttraumatic stress: Guidelines for treatment program design. Workshop presented at the annual meeting of The International Society for Traumatic Stress Studies, San Francisco, CA.</P>
			
			<P>Arrowood, J. S., Palmieri, P. A. and Campos, P. E. (November, 1994).<BR>
			An examination of the role of fear as a mediator of information processing and attentional biases toward threat cues. Paper presented at the annual meeting of The Association for Advancement of Behavior Therapy, San Diego, CA.</P>
			
			<P>Arrowood, J. S., Rogers, R., and Dickens, S. E. (in press).<BR>
			Bias against the insanity defense: An exploratory Canadian study. Health Law in Canada.</P>
			
			<P><B>Howard Barbaree, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>Queen's University, 1974.</I><BR>
			Clinical and research interests include assessing risk or dangerousness in the sexual offender, deviant sexual arousal, and treatment program development and evaluation.</P>
			
			<P>Barbaree, H.E., Marshall, W.L., & Hudson, S.M. (Eds.). (1993).<BR>
			The juvenile sex offender. New York: Guilford.</P>
			
			<P>Barbaree, H.E. & Mewhort, D.J.K. (1994).<BR>
			The effects of Z-score transformations on measures of relative erectile response strength: A re-appraisal. Behaviour Research and Therapy, 32, 547-558.</P>
			
			<P>Barbaree, H.E., & Peacock, E. (1995).<BR>
			Phallometric assessment in the investigation of allegations of child sexual abuse. In T. Ney (Ed.) Allegations of child sexual abuse. New York: Brunner-Mazel.</P>
			
			<P>Marshall, W.L., Barbaree, H.E., & Fernandez, Y.M. (1995).<BR>
			Some aspects of social competence in sexual offenders. Sexual Abuse: A Journal of Research and Treatment, 7, 113-127.</P>
			
			<P><B>Ray Blanchard, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>University of Illinois, 1973.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include diagnosis and management of gender identity disorders, forensically significant erotic pathologies, and clinical interest in group psychotherapy with gender dysphoric patients. Research interests include taxonomy and clinical management of gender identity disorders and phallometric diagnosis of pedophilia and courtship disorders.</P>
			
			<P>Blanchard, R., & Bogaert, A.F. (1996).<BR>
			Homosexuality in men and number of older brothers. American Journal of Psychiatry, 153, 27-31.</P>
			
			<P>Blanchard, R., Dickey, R., & Jones, C.L. (1995).<BR>
			Comparison of height and weight in homosexual versus non-homosexual male gender dysphorics. Archives of Sexual Behavior, 24, 543-554.</P>
			
			<P>Blanchard, R., Zucker, K.J., Bradley, S.J., & Hume, C.S. (1995).<BR>
			Birth order and sibling sex ratio in homosexual male adolescents and probably prehomosexual feminine boys. Developmental Psychology, 31, 22-30.</P>
			
			<P>Chivers, M., & Blanchard, R. (1996).<BR>
			Prostitution advertisements suggest association of transvestism and masochism. Journal of Sex and Marital Therapy, 22, 97-102.</P>
			
			<P><B>Stephen Butler, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>University of Ottawa, 1987.</I><BR>
			Research interests include: child development and psychopathology. Clinical interests include assessment and treatment of children and families.</P>
			
			<P>Atkinson, L., & Butler, S. (1996).<BR>
			Court-ordered assessment: The impact of maternal compliance on clinical recommendations and judicial decision-making. Child Abuse and Neglect, 20, 185-190.</P>
			
			<P>Butler, S., Mackay-Soroka, S., & Dickens, S. (1995).<BR>
			Comparison of maternal and adolescent ratings of psychopathology in delinquent and non-delinquent males. Canadian Journal of Behavioural Science, 27, 333-342.</P>
			
			<P>Butler, S., Atkinson, L., Magnatta, M., & Hood, E. (1995).<BR>
			Child maltreatment: The collaboration of child welfare, mental health, and judicial systems. Child Abuse and Neglect, 19, 355-362.</P>
			
			<P>Butler, S., Radia, N., & Magnetta, M. (1994).<BR>
			Maternal compliance to court-ordered assessments in cases of child maltreatment. Child Abuse and Neglect, 18, 203-211.</P>
			
			<P><B>Laurie A. Gillies, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>York University, 1990.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include psychoanalysis, interpersonal therapy and the treatment of personality disorder. Research focuses primarily on psychotherapy, personality disorders, and training therapists.</P>
			
			<P>Angus, L., & Gillies, L.A. (1994).<BR>
			Counselling the borderline client: An interpersonal approach. Canadian Journal of Counselling, 28(1).</P>
			
			<P>Doidge, N., Simon, B., Gillies, L.A., & Ruskin, R. (1994).<BR>
			Characteristics of psychoanalytic patients under a nationalized health plan: DSM-III-R diagnoses, previous treatment, and childhood trauma. American Journal of Psychiatry, 15, 586-590.</P>
			
			<P>Mallouh, S.K., Abbey, S.A., & Gillies, L.A. (1994).<BR>
			The role of loss in treatment outcomes of persistent somatization. General Hospital Psychiatry, 17, 187-191.</P>
			
			<P><B>Mark A. Lau, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>McGill University, 1995.</I><BR>
			Clinical Interests include the assessment and cognitive/behavioural treatment of depression. Primary research interests include the psychopathology of depression - in particular, the interaction between information processing mechanisms and neuropsychological dysfunction in depressive cognition. Additional interests include research into a new treatment designed to prevent depressive relapse.</P>
			
			<P>Lau, M.A., Peterson, J.B., & Pihl, R.O. (1995).<BR>
			Provocation, acute alcohol intoxication, cognitive performance, and aggression. Journal of Abnormal Psychology, 104, 150-155.</P>
			
			<P>Lau, M.A., & Pihl, R.O. (in press).<BR>
			Cognitive performance, inhibition and aggression. Aggressive Behaviour.</P>
			
			<P>Lau, M.A., & Pihl, R.O. (1996, August).<BR>
			A possible role for cognitive deficits associated with frontal lobe dysfunction in depressive thinking. Paper presented at the meeting of the American Psychological Association, Toronto, ON.</P>
			
			<P><B>David Nussbaum, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>University of Waterloo, 1983.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include assessment of personality disorders and neuropsychological impairment. Research interests consist of the use of the SCID Personality Questionnaire for diagnostic screening and application of Brain Electrical Activity Mapping to diagnosis.</P>
			
			<P>Nussbaum, D., Chaudhry, M.A., & Martin-Doto, C. (1996).<BR>
			Cognitive impulsivity, verbal intelligence and locus of control in violent and nonviolent mentally disordered offenders. American Journal of Forensic Psychology, 14, 5-30.</P>
			
			<P>Lynn Oldershaw, PhD, University of Toronto, 1989.<BR>
			Research has focused on the behavioural, affective, perceptual, and cognitive processes characterizing problem parent-child interactions, and has involved both nonclinical and clinical populations (abusive families, conduct disorder children, depressed parents).</P>
			
			<P>Oldershaw, L., & Bagby, R.M. (1997).<BR>
			Children and deception. In R. Rogers (Ed.), Clinical assessment of malingering and deception. New York: Guilford Publications.</P>
			
			<P><B>Helen Radovanovic, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>York University, 1990.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include: family therapy, play and individual therapy with children, and assessments of custody/visitation disputes and young offenders. Research interests include the effects of parental conflict and separation on children's adjustment, and children's coping styles.</P>
			
			<P>Radovanovic, H., Bartha, C., Magnatta, M., Hood, E., Sagar, A., & McDonough, H. (1994).<BR>
			A follow-up of families disputing child custody/access: Assessment, settlement, and family relationship outcomes. Behavioral Sciences and the Law, 12, 427-435.</P>
			
			<P>Radovanovic, H. (1993).<BR>
			Parental conflict and children's coping styles in litigating separated families: Relationships with children's adjustment. Journal of Abnormal Child Psychology, 21, 697-713.</P>
			
			<P><B>Zindel V. Segal, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>Queen's University, 1983.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include: Treatment of affective disorder, anxiety disorders, psychological adaptation to recurrent emotional difficulties, process issues in supervision. Research interests include: Assessment of cognitive vulnerability markers in major depressive disorder, self-schematic processing and the assessment of change in personal constructs as a result of successful therapy or recovery from illness.</P>
			
			<P>Moretti, M.M., Segal, Z.V. Miller, D.T., Shaw, B.F., Vella, D.D., & McCann, C.D. (1996).<BR>
			Processing information directed toward the self versus others in clinically depressed, mildly depressed, and remitted depressed subjects. Personality and Social Psychology Bulletin, 22, 68-80.</P>
			
			<P>Segal, Z.V., Gemar, M., Truchon, C., Guirguis, M., & Horowitz, L. (1995).<BR>
			A priming methodology for studying self-representation in major depressive disorder. Journal of Abnormal Psychology, 104, 205-213.</P>
			
			<P>Segal, Z.V., Williams, J.M., Teasdale, J.D., & Gemar, M. (1996).<BR>
			A cognitive science perspective of kindling and episode sensitization in recurrent affective disorder. Psychological Medicine, 26, 371-380.</P>
			
			<P>Teasdale, J.D., Segal, Z.V., & Williams, J.M.G. (1995).<BR>
			How does cognitive therapy prevent depressive relapse and why should attentional control (mindfulness) training help? Behaviour Research and Therapy, 33, 25-39.</P>
			
			<P><B>Meagan Smith, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>State University of New York at Stony Brook, 1993.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include: Assessment of children with behavioural, emotional and learning disorders. Research interests include: Effectiveness of day treatment for psychiatrically disturbed children.</P>
			
			<P>Finegan, J.K., Cole, T.P., Kingwell, E., Smith, M., & Fischel, J.E. (1994).<BR>
			Language and behavior in children with Sotos syndrome. Journal of the Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry, 33, 1307-1315.</P>
			
			<P>Smith, M., Kuksis, M., Zucker, K.J., & Beitchman, J.H. (1996, January).<BR>
			Cognitive profile and psychopathology in children admitted to psychiatric day treatment: A comparison to outpatient and normal controls. Paper presented at the meeting of the International Society for Research in Child and Adolescent Psychopathology, Santa Monica, CA.</P>
			
			<P>Whitehurst, G.J., Arnold, D.S., Epstein, J.E., Angell, A., Smith, M., & Fischel, J.E. (1994).<BR>
			A picture book reading intervention in daycare and home for children from low-income families. Developmental Psychology, 30, 679-689.</P>
			
			<P><B>Percy Wright, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>York University, 1992.</I><BR>
			Clinical interests include forensic assessment (subsuming personality, intellectual, risk and neuropsychological assessment), individual and group treatment of impulse control disorders including paraphilias, kleptomania, oniomania and some persistent fraud cases. Present research interests are measurement of impulsivity, treatment issues in sex offenders and personality correlates of kleptomania and pathological gambling.</P>
			
			<P>Langevin, R., Wright, P., Wilson, R.J., Hucker, S., Zucker, K., & Bradley, S.J. (in press).<BR>
			Quantitative electroencephalographic (EEG) studies of males with sexual anomalies and gender disorders: I. Baseline recordings. Journal of Nervous and Mental Disease.</P>
			
			<P>Arlene Young, PhD, University of Waterloo, 1993.<BR>
			Clinical and research interests: child assessment (including cognitive, educational, personality and neuropsychological assessment); childhood anxiety disorders, reading disorders; language disorders and connections between cognitive skills and developmental psychopathology.</P>
			
			<P>Young, A., & Bowers, T.G. (1995).<BR>
			Individual difference and text difficulty determinants of reading fluency and expressiveness. Journal of Experimental Child Psychology, 20, 428-454.</P>
			
			<P>Young, A., & Bowers, T.G., & MacKinnon, G.E. (1996).<BR>
			Effects of prosodic modelling and repeated reading on poor reader's fluency and comprehension. Applied Psycholinguistics, 17, 59-84.</P>
			
			<P>Beitchman, J.H., & Young, A. (in press).<BR>
			Learning disorders with a special emphasis on reading disability: A review of the past ten years. Journal of the American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry.</P>
			
			<P><B>Kenneth J. Zucker, PhD</B><BR>
			<I>University of Toronto, 1982.</I><BR>
			Clinical and research interests include gender identity disorders in children and adolescents; attachment and child psychopathology; risk factors in child psychopathology; developmental psychopathology; individual child psychotherapy; parental counselling.</P>
			
			<P>Fridell, S.R., Zucker, K.J., Bradley, S.J., & Maing, D.M. (1996).<BR>
			Physical attractiveness of girls with gender identity disorder. Archives of Sexual Behavior, 25, 17-31.</P>
			
			<P>Zucker, K.J., & Bradley, S.J. (1995).<BR>
			Gender identity disorder and psychosexual problems in children and adolescents. New York: Guilford Press.</P>
			
			<P>Zucker, K.J., Bradley, S.J., & Sullivan, C.B.L. (1996).<BR>
			Traits of separation anxiety in boys with gender identity disorder. Journal of the American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry, 35, 791-798.</P>
												
