<HTML>

	<!--
		This HTML document was marked up by David Veldhuizen
		of HTM Interactive <http://www.thom.com/> or <dave@thom.com>
		Copyright 1996; all rights reserved.
	 -->

	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About The Clarke: Child Care Work Department</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Child Care Work Department" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/child_care_work_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>Child Care Work is a highly specialized mental health
			profession aimed at the prevention and treatment of mental
			and emotional disorders in children and adolescents. 
			Treatment promotes intellectual, social, emotional, familial
			and general developmental areas of functioning.  While the
			child and adolescent are often the primary focus of Child
			Care Work, assessment and treatment activities are directed
			at the individual in the context of the family and the
			larger social system in which they live.</P>
			
			<P>The Child Care Work Department consists of
			fully-qualified and experienced professional child care
			workers who provide assessment and direct clinical services.
			 Children and families are referred to our department
			through the various multi-disciplinary teams assigned to the
			existing programs and clinics in the Child and Family
			Studies Centre.</P>
			
			<P>Specific treatment services provided by our department
			include: individual, group, play, family, activity and
			milieu therapy using a wide range of traditional and new
			evidence-based treatment approaches.  Other services include
			consultations to both internal and community professionals
			on: gifted children selective mutism management of
			aggressive behaviour child management parenting family
			support day treatment program designs professional team
			functioning critical incident stress debriefing.</P>
			
			<P>The Clarke's commitment to the education of mental health
			professionals is fulfilled in part by our department
			through: the annual training of child care work students
			from Ontario Community Colleges the clinical supervision and
			training of  other mental health professionals participation
			in community agencies college advisory committees direct
			teaching in college courses.</P>
			
			<P>Research activities are an important part of Child Care
			Work.  Many staff participate in on-going research in
			conjunction with other investigators in the Child and Family
			Studies Centre.  These include studies in defiant disorders,
			children at risk for mood disorders, attention deficit
			disorders and selective mutism.</P>
			
			<P>For more information, send inquiries to:
			<A HREF="mailto:PipitoneJ@cs.Clarke-Inst.on.ca">PipitoneJ@cs.Clarke-Inst.on.ca</A></P>
			
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
					WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
