	<HEAD>
		<TITLE>The Clarke Institute: About The Clarke: Social Work Department</TITLE>
		<LINK REV="made" HREF="mailto:dave@thom.com">
	</HEAD>

	<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#CC6600" ALINK="#FFFFFF" VLINK="#000000">
		<TABLE WIDTH=600 BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR VALIGN=TOP><TD COLSPAN=3>
			<H1><IMG ALT="Social Work Department" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=169
					 SRC="../images/social_work_h.gif"></H1>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=170 HEIGHT=20>
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=345 HEIGHT=20>			
					   <TD><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=85 HEIGHT=20>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP><TD>
			<TD><P>Social workers are assigned to each program or service,
			reflecting the Institute's multi-disciplinary approach to
			health care. While specific responsibilities vary from one
			area to another, in general, social workers are responsible
			for a psychosocial assessment of the patient and his family.
			Ongoing treatment may be provided either to the individual,
			the family, or in a group context. The re-integration of the
			patient in the community is accomplished by post-discharge
			follow-up or referral to an appropriate community
			resource.</P>
			
			<P>The Clarke Institute of Psychiatry, affiliated with the
			University of Toronto, carries a major responsibility for
			teaching. The Department of Social Work is involved in the
			education of social work students in both the field and
			classroom. As a teaching centre in mental health, the
			Department provides a practicum for a number of students
			specializing in Health. Members of staff are also involved
			in teaching at the Faculty of Social Work, University of
			Toronto.</P>
			
			<P>Social work staff are involved in the ongoing educational
			programs for trainees in other disciplines throughout The
			Clarke and in the wider social work community and mental
			health network. The department's Public Education Program
			has produced a series of booklets which are free for Clarke
			staff and patients and are sold throughout Canada the United
			States and Europe. These include: <CITE>Depressive Illness:
			A Guide for Patients and Families</CITE>;
			<CITE>Manic-Depressive Illness: A Guide for Patients and
			Families</CITE>; <CITE>Schizophrenia: A Guide for Patients
			and Families</CITE>; <CITE>Marriage Counselling: An
			Information Guide</CITE>; <CITE>Alzheimer's Disease and
			Related Disorders: A Guide for Families and
			Caregivers</CITE>; <CITE>Paranoid Conditions: A Guide for
			Families</CITE>. All booklets are available in French and
			English; <CITE>Manic-Depressive Illness: A Guide for
			Patients and Families</CITE> is available in Chinese.
			Booklet information may be obtained by calling (416)
			979-4747, Ext. 2576</P>
			
			<P><CITE>Mental Illness in the Family: Issues and
			Trends</CITE>, edited by Beverley Abosh and April Collins,
			is a compilation of essays on dealing with the various
			aspects of mental illness and the family. This book can be
			obtained through the University of Toronto Press.</P>
			
			<P>Research is an integral component of social work practice.
			A number of staff are involved in a variety of projects both
			as principal investigators and in conjunction with other
			health professionals.</P>
			
			<P><A NAME="sw_family_program"><IMG SRC="../images/sw_family_program.gif" WIDTH=302 HEIGHT=26
				ALT="The Social Work Department Family Program"></A></P>
			
			<P>This program is committed to assessing family needs and
			developing ways to address these needs through
			hospital-based services and community resources. Among the
			services offered are psycho-educational groups, information
			booklets, public information sessions, and family
			consultation.</P>
			
			<P>The main components of the Family Program are:</P>

			<UL>			
				<LI><B>TIPS, (&quot;Taking Initiative in Psychiatric
					Settings&quot;)</B> a program of evening information forums
					for consumers and families.
				<LI><B>The Family Advisory Group</B> -- Comprised of relatives of
					individuals seen in the various Divisions of the Clarke,
					this Group provides input on future directions of The Family
					Program as well as Institute activities. From a list of
					family needs compiled by The Advisory Group, a proposal for
					a &quot;Family Resource and Self-Help Centre&quot; funded by the
					Clarke Foundation. The Resource Centre, which will be run
					by family members and volunteers will provide an adjunct to
					professional care and will offer a comfortable place for
					relatives and friends to drop in, on-site volunteers who
					have a family member or friend with mental illness, support
					and understanding and information about the Clarke and
					community resources.
			</UL>
						
			<P><A HREF="mailto:ABOSHB@CS.Clarke-inst.on.ca">We are
			interested in hearing from anyone working with families of
			the mentally ill.</A></P>

		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD COLSPAN=3><IMG ALT="" SRC="../images/spacer.gif" WIDTH=600 HEIGHT=30>
		<TR VALIGN=TOP>
			<TD><P ALIGN=RIGHT>
				<A HREF="../contents.html"><IMG ALT="*" SRC="../images/back_button_wt.gif"
					WIDTH=154 HEIGHT=58 BORDER=0 HSPACE=8></A></P>
			<TD><P><I><A HREF="../contents.html">Back to Main Contents</A></I></P>
		</TABLE>
	</BODY>
